\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It is billed as one of the largest summits ever held. By the start of the World Summit for Sustainable Development a week from today, tens of thousands of delegates will have gathered in Johannesburg with the avowed goal of eradicating poverty and stopping environmental destruction.\par \par \uc2 How much attention should businesses pay to this sprawling, grandly titled conference? At first sight, not a lot. There are no treaties on the drawing board; there will be no new rules or regulations for the private sector. Indeed, the failure to agree a final agenda for the summit means that few binding decisions of any kind are likely to be made.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Deadlock over environmental treaties means the summit has been broadened to include development and poverty alleviation. But there is scarcely any harmony in these areas between the main rich countries, following a bitter dispute between the US and Europe over funding for the World Bank and continued questions about the US's commitment to multilateral initiatives. It is almost certain to be a bad-tempered cacophony of competing voices and conflicting goals.\par \par \uc2 Yet western businesses cannot afford to ignore this summit. It crystallises trends that are shaping the relationship between lawmakers and the private sector. Both governments and anti-globalisation campaigners believe - for different reasons - that business holds the key to sustainable development. The dispute over whether businesses are a positive or negative influence is set to pervade the summit's debates.\par \par \uc2 Many campaigning organisations now recognise that foreign direct investment by companies can be a force for good. But a recent conference on private sector involvement at the World Bank still revealed deep concerns. Development campaigners suspect that the bank's new focus on improving the climate for business investment is merely a code for reducing labour and environmental protection.\par \par \uc2 David Ellerman, an adviser to the World Bank, says it has too often taken a one-sided view of investment. "One person's stability is another person's rigidity," he wrote in a study. "The bank tends to ignore trade-offs and implicitly identify with one group, usually external or foreign investors, and then count an improvement in the investment climate for that group as being an improvement per se."\par \par \uc2 Critics accuse the World Bank of providing "corporate welfare" for northern hemisphere businesses. The Institute for Policy Studies, the leftwing Washington think-tank, seized on the collapse of Enron to show how the activities of the disgraced energy trader had been financed by the bank and by governments' export credit guarantee agencies. "Enron would not have scaled such grand global heights, nor fallen so dramatically, without its close financial relationships with government agencies," said Jim Vallette and Daphne Wysham, authors of a report on the corporation.\par \par \uc2 The recognition that business is in the spotlight is forcing international companies to play a leading role at the summit. "Business is going to come in big numbers," says Bjorn Stigson, president of the World Business Council for Sustainable Development, a Geneva-based group representing 160 multinationals. "There is a growing understanding that you have to address the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainable development. You cannot leave these issues unattended."\par \par \uc2 The increasing role for business partly stems from an awareness that the lofty rhetoric needs to give way to action. There are now hundreds of declarations, agreements, guidelines and legally binding treaties on alleviating poverty and environmental damage. But few have been adequately implemented.\par \par \uc2 There is a growing belief that this implementation gap can only be narrowed by harnessing the experience of business and other groups, such as conservation and aid charities. "The most creative agents of change may well be partnerships," says Kofi Annan, UN secretary-general.\par \par \uc2 Business shares this enthusiasm for partnerships, according to Sir Mark Moody-Stuart, a former chairman of Royal Dutch/Shell who heads Business Action for Sustainable Development, a group spearheading industry's involvement in the summit.\par \par \uc2 Pursuing environmental and social issues can help companies save costs, increase revenues, reduce risk, build their reputation and improve access to financing, according to a recent study by the International Finance Corporation, part of the World Bank Group. "There are compelling commercial reasons to take action, despite a common assumption that sustainability is a luxury which emerging markets cannot afford," it concluded.\par \par \uc2 Many companies are reluctant to draw attention to their achievements for fear of being accused of hypocrisy. CorpWatch, a pressure group, plans to award "green oscars" at the summit for companies that demonstrate skills at "giving human rights, social and environmental abuses a patina of respectability".\par \par \uc2 Other campaign groups will also be vociferous in arguing that multinational companies should be held to account through legally binding global rules.\par \par \uc2 This argument cuts no ice with business groups such as the WBCSD, which says there is no shortage of legislation in developing countries. The correct approach, it says, is better governance and better enforcement of existing legislation.\par \par \uc2 But the campaigners are proving highly influential. The pressure on companies to improve their sustainability performance is also mounting from other sources, such as the growth of "socially responsible" investment funds, supply-chain initiatives and the growing number of guidelines designed to foster \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 There may also be longer-term strategic reasons for focusing on social and environmental concerns. "Not only can corporate and social needs be integrated, but the success of the developing world in improving prosperity is of fundamental strategic importance to almost every company," according to Michael Porter of Harvard Business School.\par \par \uc2 He urges companies to see environmental protection as an opportunity for cost savings and innovative new products. "Products that address environmental scarcities will have enormous market potential," he wrote in a recent report published by the WBCSD, the World Resources Institute and the UN \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Programme (Unep).\par \par \uc2 Some companies can already point to real achievements. Multinationals - along with local communities - have done much more than governments to promote sustainable development in the past 10 years, says Mr Stigson.\par \par \uc2 Western businesses have introduced environmental reporting, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainability programmes. Direct investments in developing countries now exceed the failed UN targets for official development assistance.\par \par \uc2 But businesses will not solve the world's environmental and social problems. "There is a growing gap between the efforts of business and industry to reduce their impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the worsening state of the planet," according to a recent report by Unep.\par \par \uc2 In most industry sectors, only a few companies are trying to integrate social and environmental factors into business decisions, it said. Moreover, industry has shown no willingness to change its spots when it comes to subsidies. In the past decade, business lobbying has repeatedly foiled attempts to eliminate environmentally damaging subsidies or introduce taxes on pollution.\par \par \uc2 As a result, business will get little credit for its many positive initiatives, says Claude Fussler, director of stakeholder relations at the WBCSD. "Cynics think business wants it both ways: voluntary action to keep legislation away while an unchanged market framework protects business as usual."\par \par \uc2 This perception carries risks. If the idea of partnership between governments and business is perceived to fail, it could be replaced by a far more rigid, prescriptive approach. Businesses might once again be subject to "command-and-control" regulation.\par \par \uc2 The stakes are high in Johannesburg. Business can expect to come under intense scrutiny. It has much to gain if it can demonstrate its commitment to sustainable development. If not, the tolerance of governments may begin to run out. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\r