tlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Final talks aimed at breaking the main logjams facing the World Summit on Sustainable Development begin on Saturday in Johannesburg, two days before the official start of the international meeting aimed at revitalising efforts to reduce global poverty and protect the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Civil servants and corporate executives were on Friday attempting to resolve deep differences on issues as diverse as energy policy, globalisation and good governance before their political masters begin arriving later on Sunday.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 More than a quarter of the summit's proposed text remains to be agreed over the next two weeks. Deep divisions over trade access and agricultural subsidies in the developed world marred preparatory meetings.\par \par \uc2 The meeting, the biggest of its kind since the Rio summit in 1992, is also likely to be overshadowed by international concern about food shortages affecting 14m people in southern Africa and political turmoil and economic collapse in Zimbabwe.\par \par \uc2 The rejection of genetically modified US food aid by Zimbabwe, Zambia and Mozambique is likely to spur heated debate about the protection of biodiversity. On the sidelines, leaders of Britain and its former colonies are expected to put pressure on Zimbabwe's president Robert Mugabe, who is attending the summit. Mr Mugabe on Friday dissolved his cabinet and is likely to announce a more hardline team on Monday to drive through his controversial land reforms.\par \par \uc2 The work of the informal contact groups could be crucial to the eventual success or failure of the summit, which has been criticised for its sprawling agenda covering issues as varied as global warming, fisheries, human health and wildlife protection. Preliminary talks earlier this year foundered over trade and levels of aid, and many other issues remain to be resolved.\par \par \uc2 Few expect the contact groups to make any significant breakthroughs, but it is believed they could make progress in areas such as sanitation and energy. Any movement on such central issues could "kick-start" the summit and provide politicians with a firmer base to achieve progress.\par \par \uc2 The area thought most likely to see progress is sanitation. Many delegates think it likely the European Union will persuade the US to agree to limited targets and timetables on the number of people with access to safe water.\par \par \uc2 International business is eying the summit as an opportunity to publicise some of its green initiatives and to promote \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the developing world. About 50 chief executives of multinational companies are expected to attend the summit. General Motors, the auto group, Monsanto, the food producer, AT&T, the telecommunications group and Alcoa, the aluminium producer are among the companies with delegations.\par \par \uc2 Business Action for Sustainable Development, a coalition of international chambers of commerce, has urged against turning the summit into a "finger-pointing" exercise blaming business for pollution and exploitation of developed countries.\par \par \uc2 The UN and non-governmental organisations agree the summit's ultimate success will depend on whether it produces real commitment to further action by world leaders. The stance of the US is expected to be crucial - even though President George W. Bush is not attending. The US delegation will be led by Colin Powell, secretary of state. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gdip : \uc2 International Relations | gglblz : \uc2 Globalization | gglobe : \uc2 Global/World Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvert