c\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 COMMENT &ANALYSIS - Ecology opens for business - Companies are pushing green credentials in Johannesburg, say James Lamont and John Mason.\par \par \uc2 One of the first sights to greet visitors to Johannesburg this week was a giant poster of a diamond jellyfish. It reads "Ecology is Forever" - a play on the more familiar De Beers marketing mantra of "Diamonds are Forever".\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 De Beers is one of many companies taking advantage of the World Summit in South Africa's business capital to raise its "green" profile. The diamond producer is showcasing its construction of schools, land rehabilitation and women's farming and its support of classical music in Soweto, a township on the outskirts of Johannesburg.\par \par \uc2 Others are similarly bold about promoting themselves to the world's governments and non-governmental organisations. Outside the summit, BMW has erected a giant globe filled with a bar and a bank of computer screens. Rival motor company DaimlerChrysler and HP, the US information technology group, are official conference sponsors.\par \par \uc2 "The BMW group is taking part in Johannesburg because we firmly believe that sustainability is more than just a vision of a distant future. Sustainability is the core of our corporate strategy," says Norbert Reithofer, a BMW director.\par \par \uc2 Business has descended on the summit in force. About 700 companies are represented, while some 50 chief executives are floating around its corridors. Tomorrow, the business delegation spearheaded by the Paris-based Business Action for Sustainable Development (BASD), a grouping of international chambers of commerce, is hosting an exhibition. Kofi Annan, United Nations secretary-general, and summit host President Thabo Mbeki will join chief executives to celebrate business's contribution to development and a clean \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . multinational companies, largely absent from the 1992 Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro, have adopted a higher profile in order to head off criticism from environmentalists. Business leaders believe the corporate sector has to speak up about protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and spurring development.\par \par \uc2 "If we weren't here we would be hammered," says Sir Mark Moody-Stuart, the former chairman of Shell who now heads BASD. He is joined by Lord Richard Holme, former executive chairman of mining group Rio Tinto, and Bjorn Stigson, former vice-president of ABB, as the summit's private sector champions.\par \par \uc2 From the sidelines, this triumvirate has urged world leaders to show greater resolve in meeting the Millennium Development Goals, which aim to halve the number of the world's poor by 2015. To help achieve them, business leaders have promised to persuade large corporations to invest more in the world's 50 poorest countries. They have also offered an advisory council of business leaders to the New Partnership for Africa's Development, an African action plan to promote good governance in return for more aid and investment.\par \par \uc2 But the presence of business is not just altruistic. Sir Mark is lobbying for global leaders to disregard calls by NGOs to introduce multilateral rules governing business conduct.\par \par \uc2 "The summit is taking place just as massive corporate scandals are undermining economic growth and confidence throughout the world. There is widespread recognition that self-regulation has failed," says Daniel Graymore, a campaigner for Christian Aid, the UK charity.\par \par \uc2 Sir Mark concedes that greater corporate accountability is needed. But he argues that standards for business should be enforced at a national rather than global level. More regulation, he says, will discourage investment in the developing world and exclude smaller business and could be used by Europe and the US to protect their markets.\par \par \uc2 Business has not entirely escaped condemnation by NGOs over its environmental record. Friends of the Earth has complained that oil companies spend more on green marketing campaigns than on cleaning up their operations. Greenpeace attacked Dow Chemical over toxic discharges from its Midrand plant north of Johannesburg, branding it a corporate criminal.\par \par \uc2 However, while some NGOs remain openly hostile to business, others are keen to work with it. BASD is promoting 230 partnerships between business and NGOs at the summit. They include the secondment of staff from HSBC, the banking group, to Earthwatch environmental projects, carmaker Fiat's development of gas-powered cars and the treatment of sleeping sickness in Africa by Aventis, the pharmaceuticals group.\par \par \uc2 Some companies are guilty of using these projects to polish their image. But well resourced practical activities of this sort have helped to transform the debate about how to provide sustainable development for impoverished countries.\par \par \uc2 The UN is appealing to multinationals to take a bigger role in helping the world's poor.Gro Harlem Brundtland, director-general of the UN's World Health Organisation, wants businesses to take on more responsibility for looking after the health of their workers.\par \par \uc2 The UN is promoting small-scale links between business, governments, NGOs and local communities to stimulate development. Where the UN has been unable to pressurise governments to implement agreed development and environmental targets, it hopes that the resources of the private sector may speed provision of basic public services, particularly access to clean water.\par \par \uc2 "These partnerships are in no way a sell-out to commercial interests. Rather they are an acknowledgement that we need to engage the expertise and resources required for positive action," says Nitin Desai, the UN's undersecretary-general.\par \par \uc2 Such partnerships with business lie at the centre of US development policy. But US officials agree that sustainable development is still new to many companies. Holly Wise, a senior diplomat at the US Agency for International Development, says companies have mixed motives. Some are strongly committed to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  while others see an opportunity to tap new markets. "Others are there to listen and learn. They know they will be asked about their contribution to sustainable development. They see this as a forum for getting smart and getting on board with governments to see what should be done," she says.\par \par \uc2 London Edition 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | genv : \uc2 Environmental News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nedc : \uc2 Commentary/Opinion\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 africaz : \uc2 Africa | devgcoz : \uc2 Emerging Market Countries | safr : \uc2 South Africa | souafrz : \uc2 Southern Africa\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 London Edition 1 | COMMENT &ANALYSIS | Company News | Environment | Government News | International Affairs | Marketing | Pollution &Waste | Summits &Talks | South Africa | Afric