lt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A good plan, poorly implemented - that is how the United Nations now judges the 1992 Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro. Ten years later, there is disillusion over the ability of governments to promote economic development while protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Hopes for progress at the World Summit on Sustainable Development in Johannesburg are therefore pinned firmly on the private sector, encouraged by representatives of 700 companies.\par \par \uc2 It is easy to see why. Rio's Agenda 21 action plan was all about what governments could do, with the emphasis on treaties and regulation. A decade later, targets for reducing carbon dioxide emissions have been missed and biodiversity diminishes. Governments have focused on their pet policy areas and avoided difficult trade-offs between environmental protection and economic growth.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Meanwhile, western companies have introduced environmental reporting, sustainability programmes and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  commitments. Direct investment by the private sector in developing countries exceeds UN targets for official aid (which have, in any case, been missed). Business can claim to have outperformed governments.\par \par \uc2 More to the point, global companies are prepared to make such claims publicly - unlike at Rio where they were largely absent. With a growing groundswell against globalisation, the private sector is now prepared to turn up and face its critics. Companies rightly fear a wave of international regulation if they do not stand up for their interests.\par \par \uc2 Setting goals\par \par \uc2 Their presence has been welcomed by officials in the UN and development bodies and by many activists in non-governmental organisations (NGOs). Whatever the shortcomings of the private sector, it is usually much more effective than the public sector in setting goals and meeting them. The big idea at Johannesburg is on promoting collaboration between companies, governments and NGOs rather than sterile action plans for governments.\par \par \uc2 Thus Vivendi Water, the French utility, is working with South African cities to improve water quality and sanitation services. Anglo-American, the mining group, offers its African workers free Aids drugs. Oil companies clean up the areas where they extract oil and improve the lives of their local workforce.\par \par \uc2 Yet there is a danger that too much weight is being placed on such collaborative efforts. In many cases, they are little more than prudent business practice - a slash and burn approach to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is unlikely to be profitable in the longer term.\par \par \uc2 Valuable contribution\par \par \uc2 And most of these projects are, by their nature, small-scale and local. They can make a valuable contribution towards dealing with big environmental challenges such as global warming. It takes government action to make a big impact on such problems.\par \par \uc2 The danger for the private sector is that unrealistic expectations are raised about what it can achieve. Many of the companies represented in Johannesburg are there to showcase existing projects. The summit's organisers may have unreasonable expectations about how much more they are prepared to do.\par \par \uc2 And the private sector is rightly reluctant to take responsibility for issues such as healthcare that are more properly handled by the public sector. Companies come and go, and are accountable in the final resort only to their shareholders. Governments must bear the continuing burden of such programmes and can be held accountable by their peoples. They are also the only bodies that can make the trade-offs necessary to balance economic growth against environmental protection.\par \par \uc2 None of this is to disparage the efforts of companies making a genuine contribution to sustainable development. A journey of a thousand miles must begin with a single step, as the Chinese philosopher Lao-Tzu said. But while business has a role to play, it is - in the end - governments that must play the leading role. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | e11 : \uc2 Economic Performance/Indicators | ecat : \uc2 Economic News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 africaz : \uc2 Africa | devgcoz : \uc2 Emerging Market Countries | safr : \uc2 South Africa | souafrz : \uc2 Southern Africa\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvert