djustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  (Copyright (c) 2002, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  HANOVER, N.H. -- Kristine Laca has spent most of her career marketing products, from Nike sneakers to Betty Crocker side dishes to Comet cleanser. Her latest challenge: the Tuck brand. \par \par \uc2  As the new admissions director at Dartmouth College's Tuck School of Business, she sees a brand with a rich identity and plenty of potential. To her, the picturesque New England campus evokes images of scholars and skiers and feelings of "community and fervent loyalty." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2  "Promoting Tuck to prospective students will be a lot like marketing Nike to young people," she says. "You're trying to connect emotionally with consumers, and both Nike and Tuck are selling hopes and dreams and a sense of empowerment." \par \par \uc2  That doesn't mean you'll be seeing the advertising slogan "Just Do It -- at Tuck." But Tuck is becoming much more marketing-minded as it expands its student enrollment and tries to woo new faculty members and blue-chip corporate recruiters to its small campus on the Vermont-New Hampshire border. \par \par \uc2  Dartmouth already boasts a strong reputation with recruiters who rated its M.B.A. program the best in the world in the second annual Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive business-school survey. But the Ivy League school wants to become even more competitive against its bigger rivals. A member of Tuck's Board of Overseers confides that he tracks how many Tuck students have turned down admission offers from other elite schools like Harvard and Wharton -- and would like to see the tally grow. \par \par \uc2  "The M.B.A. world is hypercompetitive, and we must get better at branding and marketing ourselves," says James Danko, associate dean for strategy and operations. "We need to position and sell Tuck better than we have in the past." \par \par \uc2  Among business schools, even the price of admission is a measure of status. This year, Tuck boosted its annual tuition about 7% to $32,490, partly to cover rising expenses but also to move from the low end to the midpoint among its "peer" schools. "The price of an M.B.A. education is an indication of its quality," Mr. Danko says, "so we don't want to be the lowest of the top schools." \par \par \uc2  In the Journal survey, Tuck graduates got high marks for many attributes, including strategic thinking, communication and interpersonal skills, and ability to work well in teams. Recruiters rated Tuck high on "chemistry," or general good feelings about the school and its students. \par \par \uc2  Liam Donohue, a partner in the Boston venture-capital firm, Arcadia Partners, is partial to Tuck graduates because of their "cult-like" personal loyalty to companies. "Tuckies are a good cultural fit for most of the companies we have invested in because they're not prima donnas," he says. "They're willing to roll up their sleeves and do what's needed for a company that's struggling to make ends meet." \par \par \uc2  But Tuck's program is sometimes dubbed "the happy M.B.A." and criticized for being too "touch-feely." Some recruiters wonder whether Tuck goes overboard with its teamwork focus. "I'm not sure how decisive Tuck students are because they work so much in teams," says Joe Koch, a recruiter at Arch Chemicals Inc. in Atlanta. "They always want consensus, but sometimes you need to make a decision fast and on your own." \par \par \uc2  Founded in 1900 as America's first graduate school of business, Tuck offers a general-management curriculum and is perhaps the most single-minded of all the top business schools. Even as executive M.B.A. and online degree programs proliferate, Tuck still awards only a full-time M.B.A. degree. \par \par \uc2  The curriculum was revised in 2000 to put more emphasis on entrepreneurship, technology and global business. But recruiters still give Tuck low scores for its students' international perspective. \par \par \uc2  Now, Tuck is refining the new curriculum again. For example, it is responding to the wave of corporate scandals by increasing ethics training. This year, first-year students will be required to participate in four ethics panels, on accounting, capital markets, marketing and operations. Second-year students can take an elective course that deals with such issues as bribery and executive pay. \par \par \uc2  Management consulting and financial-services have traditionally been the main career routes for Tuck students. In the Journal survey, recruiters named Tuck the second-best school for both strategy and general management and ninth-best for finance. \par \par \uc2  But students this year had to broaden their job searches to include more robust industries like pharmaceuticals, energy production and retailing. Even so, many graduated jobless. As of August, only 75% of the class of 2002 had received job offers, down from 90% or more in previous summers. Consulting accounted for about a third of jobs this year, down from 51% last year, while the financial-services share of jobs fell to 26% from 38%. \par \par \uc2  The school's biggest asset is the allegiance of its alumni network of more than 7,500 Tuckies. Matthew Allen, a second-year student, attended information sessions in California for Harvard, the University of Michigan and Carnegie Mellon University, as well as Tuck, and came away much more impressed with Tuck alumni. "The alumni at the other schools were out of there after the question-and-answer session," he says, "but the Tuck alumni hung around for over an hour afterward talking up their alma mater. It was very revealing and helped clinch my decision to come to Tuck." \par \par \uc2  Tuck alumni always account for a large percentage of campus recruiters, but their involvement in the job search was never greater than this past school year. The career-services office even collared some alumni attending Tuck's reunion weekend in May and asked them to forgo some of the social events to interview students. "We figured it was our last big chance to shake the tree," says Erin Cochrane, a Tuck official. The ploy shook loose 10 job offers. \par \par \uc2  Although they like Tuck graduates for their personal traits and academic skills, recruiters still complain that the pickings are too slim at such a small program. In response, Tuck is adding more students and expects enrollment to reach 480 soon, a big jump from 375 in 2000. \par \par \uc2  In addition to more "critical mass," Tuck is struggling to achieve greater diversity. The share of women students is only about 25% in the class of 2003, down from 32% in this year's graduating class and less than that at some of its peer schools such as Columbia and Harvard. But Tuck expects the number to rebound with the class of 2004. Tuck is awarding more scholarships to minorities and has seen the African-American share of applicants jump to 8.7% from 1.1% in 1999 and the Hispanic share grow to 6% from 1.7%. On the international front, about a third of Tuck students now come from foreign countries, mostly in Asia and Latin America, but the school wants to attract more European students. \par \par \uc2  Increasing Tuck's enrollment will be a delicate balancing act if the school is to maintain its trademark collegiality. "It's something we talk about all the time," says Renny Smith, co-chairman of a newly formed M.B.A. advisory board of 1980s-era alumni. "If we grow, we have told the dean we have to do it in a fashion that maintains camaraderie." Mr. Smith believes the creation of several new associate and assistant dean positions will spread administrative responsibilities among more people "so the dean doesn't lose touch with the pulse of the place." \par \par \uc2  Still, some students expect overcrowding in the cafeteria and study rooms and less "Tuck family" unity. "You'll see an erosion of community spirit if some first-year students have to live 20 minutes away from campus," says Eric Knapp, who graduated from Tuck this year and was hired as a strategy consultant for International Business Machines Corp. \par \par \uc2  Tuck does plan new residential and classroom facilities, but they won't be completed for nearly five years. The school also will try to prevent the dilution of its close-knit culture through tighter enrollment management. To ensure that all admitted students want to become "an active part of the Tuck community," the admissions office now requires that all applicants request an interview with college officials, alumni or current students. "Tuck certainly isn't for everyone, so it's important that we meet with applicants to get a better sense of what they're about," says Ms. Laca, the admissions director. "We don't want people who just head right home after classes." \par \par \uc2  Mr. Knapp says Tuck's collegiality was especially important for him because he was an undergraduate psychology major and classmates helped him get up to speed in quantitative courses. "I never felt put out to pasture by myself," he says. "My wife and I moved to Hanover [from Boston] without knowing a soul, and now we're leaving with lifetime friends." \par \par \uc2  Other students also like the esprit de corps but at times find the closeness a bit intense. "There's no backstabbing and very little cliquishness, but the drawback is that everyone always knows what everyone else is doing," says Dane Rasmussen, a second-year student. "There are times you'd like to escape a little, but it's hard to do." He also found snowy Hanover "taxing in the middle of winter," but on the plus side, he did learn to ski. \par \par \uc2  Tuck's biggest image problem clearly is its remote location. Ms. Laca hopes to persuade more applicants to visit Hanover before ruling Tuck out. "If you're living in an urban area and hear about Tuck, you think of cows," she says. "I need to get them up here to see what it's really like." She is even considering covering part of the travel expenses if the applicant is a hot prospect. \par \par \uc2  Tuck's location is also a barrier to the school's mission to increase its faculty's stature. "We'd like Tuck to have a little more of a star system, but the best brains aren't easily lured to Hanover," says Fred Whittemore, a member of Tuck's Board of Overseers. \par \par \uc2  Tuck has added 12 full-time faculty members in the past five years, giving it a total of 50 teachers, and is conducting five more professor searches this year. \par \par \uc2  But these days the stakes are high as schools bid up salaries vying for a small pool of top-flight professors. Demand is particularly strong for professors of finance and banking, with salaries averaging about $130,000 a year for new hires in those fields in 2001. Even newly minted Ph.D.s commanded salaries averaging $87,500 in 2001, nearly 12% higher than the year before, according to AACSB International, the organization that accredits business schools. \par \par \uc2  Besides a comfortable salary, research support is critical to attract the most renowned professors -- what Dean Paul Danos calls "thought leaders." He has made faculty excellence a top goal of Tuck's new fund-raising campaign. More than half of the target amount of $110 million would provide faculty with research scientists, editorial assistants, data analysts and other support. \par \par \uc2  But Tuck's timing isn't ideal. "The stock market has a big influence on our fund raising," says Phyllis Tremaine, director of development and corporate giving. "We're trying to keep a low profile now because people have other things on their mind besides philanthropy." \par \par \uc2  Tuck's last major campaign set a goal of $35 million and raised $56 million because of the bull market. "We don't expect to beat our goal like that again," Ms. Tremaine says wistfully, "but we can always hope." \par \par \uc2  --- \par \par \uc2  Journal Link: For more information on these and other M.B.A. programs, see "The Wall Street Journal Guide to the Top Business Schools 2003," available at WSJBooks.com \par \par \uc2 \f2 \par ---\par   1 Dartmouth College\par   The Recruiters Speak\par   -- The first thing that comes to mind about Dartmouth\par   "Hard work and hard play"\par   "Great general managers and leaders"\par   "Salt-of-the-earth people; a little out of touch, though"\par   -- How Dartmouth could improve its reputation\par   "Greater student diversity"\par   "Improve ease of traveling to the school"\par   "Increase international focus"\par   Dartmouth on Dartmouth\par   (Data provided by the Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth College