0 \highlight\uc2 , the real power for change sits with businesses. Unless companies report fully their environmental risks and take steps to minimise these risks, there will be no hope of real change.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps many businesses still feel that environmental issues and capitalism do not sit well together - that ethical considerations are all very well but they shouldn't get in the way of business. In reality, these companies will soon discover that sustainability is becoming inexorably linked to profits and the cost of capital.\par \par \uc2 It is no coincidence that those companies putting \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the map now are those who have been targeted in anti-capitalist riots and media campaigns in the past: Shell after negative publicity surrounding Nigeria and Brent Spar; Nike after the NoLogo campaign and the Seattle riots.\par \par \uc2 The point is that environmental responsibility is not a matter of benevolence or social responsibility; it is simply good business sense. The recent spate of corporate collapses in the US has focused our minds on risk assessment and management, and no board can make a decision on a new project without assessing all the risks including the environmental ones. Reporting risks is the first step, and companies such as Shell and Marks and Spencer are rising to the challenge with highly publicised pledges to sustainability and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But reporting is only effective if it reveals the whole story. In many cases, corporate environmental reporting is ineffective.\par \par \uc2 Post-Enron, the pressure is on to present all relevant information to shareholders, including non-financial information such as risks and issues of reputation. We have seen what happens when companies are less than open, and CIMA has been at the forefront of the call for stronger corporate governance and transparency.\par \par \uc2 The reason is simple: if investors do not trust the information they are given, they will not invest. If you are in any doubt as to the truth of this statement, consider the fact that this summer more than 30 investment institutions, including Merrill Lynch and Henderson Global Investors, wrote to the world's largest 500 companies, demanding that they reveal how they are tackling environmental and ethical issues.\par \par \uc2 This initiative follows a report published in the spring by the Coalition for Environmentally Responsible Economies in the US, Value at risk: climate change and the future of governance, that argues that the risks posed by climate change could result in multibillion-dollar losses for US businesses and investment portfolios. According to James Martin, a former chief investment officer at TIAA-CREFC, one of the largest pension funds in the US, "the evidence is compelling that companies' performance on environmental issues does indeed affect their competitiveness, profitability, and share price performance".\par \par \uc2 Investors want to see a return on their money. And companies that don't report on ethical and environmental issues are simply not going to be worth the risk to investors who are already switching to ethical investment funds in their droves. According to the Ethical Investment Research Service, there are about 60 ethical funds in the UK fund universe, with 469,000 unit holders and policyholders and \u163\'00\'A33.8bn in funds under management, and the numbers are growing.\par \par \uc2 A recent Mori poll found that 92 per cent of the British public believes multinational companies should meet the highest human health, animal welfare and environmental standards wherever they operate. Customers are only too happy to vote with their feet, as many companies learned during the anti-globalisation riots.\par \par \uc2 The Co-operative Bank's ethical and environmental positioning contributed more than \u163\'00\'A320m, or 20 per cent, of its pre-tax profit last year, according to its research that found nearly a third of its current-account customers chose to bank with the organisation primarily because of its ethical policy.\par \par \uc2 The truth is, however, that voluntary reporting is not enough. The Operating and Financial Review will require public companies to report their environmental risks, a measure that is essential to protect shareholders and focus the attention of management on these important risks, but we are also confident that adopting an ethical approach will highlight potential efficiencies for companies.\par \par \uc2 A report out today from CIMA, in association with Forum for the Future, explores the current approaches to the difficult task of identifying key risks and looking at the costs of restoring or avoiding environmental damage to organisations. It makes the crucial link between environmental and financial performance more visible, explaining how environmental costs and savings can be identified and reported. Baxter Healthcare Corporation, a US-based company that spent several years developing the environmental financial statement methodology, now sees savings and avoided costs from environmental investments actually exceeding its environmental related expenditure.\par \par \uc2 More than ever, investors need comfort and reassurance: if risks aren't assessed and reported fully, it isn't just the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  that's in trouble.\par \par \uc2 Environmental cost accounting, published by CIMA in association with Forum for the Future, is available from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.cimaglobal.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.cimaglobal.com}}}\par \par \uc2 The author is chief executive of the Chartered Institute of Management Accountants\par \par \uc2 3. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl1