faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Lesley Roberts, 55, is a campaigner turned corporate conscience. A former director of Anti-Slavery International, she is group business standards manager for Pentland, the private company that owns Lacoste, Speedo, Berghaus, Kickers, Mitre, Ted Baker and other clothing and sports brands.\par \par \uc2 Most of the goods are made in Asia and Ms Roberts is responsible for developing programmes to tackle the causes of poor working conditions, including child labour, hazardous chemicals and excessive overtime. With her team of four, three of whom are based in Asia, she advises the operating companies on ethical and environmental sourcing of products and monitors performance.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 With a degree in economics and statistics, Ms Roberts began her career with UBS and Royal Bank of Canada, moving to Mexico with Lloyds Bank and Mellon Bank. She joined Oxfam, working in Central and South America and the Caribbean, then with Anti-Slavery International. She moved to Pentland in 1996.\par \par \uc2 Pentland was a challenge because it was a totally different sector. I'd left Anti-Slavery because I'd had six years and that was enough. The area that really upset me was forced prostitution and trafficking.\par \par \uc2 I got a call from Stephen [Rubin, chairman of Pentland], who said: "Would you like a job?" I said: "No, I want some time off." They kept calling me. Then I thought: This is quite an interesting area. Here we are as campaigners always telling people they should do something about a problem but we're not very good at telling them how. Here was a chance to work with a company that seemed to want to do something about it.\par \par \uc2 Pentland is not big like Nike. We rarely take anything like 100 per cent of a factory; it's more like 5-10 per cent. If you are designing, sourcing and marketing, and you are quite small, and you have 11 different brands, how do you begin to influence health and safety and labour contracts?\par \par \uc2 Stephen has always been very supportive of doing something slightly different. A lot of other companies have gone down the road of compliance - you have a code of conduct, which we do, and you say that your factories are complying with your code. Well, I know and he knows that most of the time they're not.\par \par \uc2 We identified fairly early on that there were quite serious problems in certain countries. He said: "Now we know the situation and we know it's not going to be easy to fix. How can we have a sustainable impact?"\par \par \uc2 By tackling child labour head-on, you're unlikely to get the good result. We've had a couple of examples where the factories have just pushed the kids out of the back door. I didn't know where those kids had gone; and we'd possibly made their lives infinitely worse.\par \par \uc2 The initial industry response in Pakistan to children being involved in football-stitching, mainly in their homes, was to bring [all the workers] in and put a wall around them to make sure children weren't there. It's a big expense - but you haven't changed the lives of the children. They're not working on footballs but there are other things that are far worse - surgical instruments, tanning, carpets.\par \par \uc2 Also, half the workforce were women; but when you brought the workers into the stitching centres, the women weren't there. Either they weren't allowed to come in because of the culture or they didn't want to because of their other responsibilities at home. There were about 30,000 women working in the industry. Four or five years later, having realised the problem, we're back to about 10,000. You can imagine what happened to family income.\par \par \uc2 So we don't do it like that. If we have any inkling that there are under-age workers in the factory, our guys are supposed to do absolutely nothing. They refer it to us and we do some research with a local organisation to see whether we do really have a problem.\par \par \uc2 We do a lot of training within the different brands. One of the courses is [looking at] what is expected of you - as a Mitre or Kangaroos or Speedo - by society. People will say: "My kid's got a project at school on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ". So we say: "What can we do as business standards to help you come back with replies on that project?" Having broadened the discussion out, you're trying to bring it into how the business can change things.\par \par \uc2 We try to alert people to the possible areas where we could come unstuck. There's a Buddha Beach in Thailand and the designers wanted to put a Buddha on a T-shirt. Somebody said: "Let's ask business standards first." There's that sensitivity that quite a lot of people might be very upset. That's fine. The problem comes if you've manufactured 50,000 of them and they're sitting at the docks and all of a sudden somebody says: "Let's call business standards."\par \par \uc2 I would not be part of a damage limitation exercise, I would hope. I think we've made it quite clear that we are not the public relations department. If it's damage limitation, we've already lost it from the business standards point of view.\par \par \uc2 If you're really wanting to do \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , you need to work with other people. We were quite a big buyer of shoes in a town in India, yet I couldn't get anything going on the child labour problem because other buyers were not interested. That was a failure. The local government were not going to do anything unless there was that economic imperative from the other buyers.\par \par \uc2 In the footwear sector in Vietnam, we have mobilised not only government departments but also the industry to say: "Together we can make the situation in the whole sector better." But it's going to take a while.\par \par \uc2 I haven't regretted the move into the private sector. I can make people very uncomfortable - I don't think I've lost that. I don't go away. When I first went to the factories, people said: "It's all right, she'll soon be on her way back to London." Then I'd turn up another year and they'd say: "Oh God, she's back again." The third time, they'd say: "You're here, this is what we've done." Great! You're no longer seen as the police. They begin to see that we're here not to find them out but to help them to make conditions better.\par \par \uc2 Every [job I have had] has been a bit of a surprise - and this one was, too. When I was growing up, it wasn't expected that girls would have a career. One just waltzed from one thing to another.\par \par \uc2 I got a taste for travel when I was sent by my parents on one of these atrocious French exchanges. Luckily I dropped into Nice. There was still [postwar] rationing at home and here were peppers, aubergines, garlic, olive oil and sun. Compared with grey 1950s Birmingham, the south of France was so different.\par \par \uc2 My parents were very conservative and very provincial and I think they went to their deaths thinking they'd got something wrong. Here I was cavorting round the world, marrying a guy from the Caribbean - and my brother married a Jewess from New York and became a Buddhist organic farmer in Nova Scotia. I think my parents did a fantastic job but I'm not sure how.\par \par \uc2 I do want things to change. In the Oxfam and Anti-Slavery jobs, and this one, there was an amazing opportunity to find out how one could make lives better in a rather fundamental way. I'm still not convinced that one can do it. Nevertheless I feel one has to try. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ptld : \uc2 Pentland Brands PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i453 : \uc2 Clothing | iclt : \uc2 Clothing/Textiles\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\int