-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 INSIDE TRACK - Truants, nerds and supersonics - \b \highlight22\uc2 CORPORATE SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY\b0 \highlight\uc2  - More companies are producing non-financial reports. A league table reveals how good their efforts are, writes A.\par \par \uc2 When it comes to social and environmental reporting, is your company a truant, a cosmetic, a nerd or a virtuoso? Despite theenormous increase in non-financial reporting in the past two years, most companies still fit the first category, reporting little, if anything, about their impact on society.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The cosmetics produceglossy reports that are more about style than substance. The nerds, on the other hand, are eagerly publishing ever-greater quantities of information about their activities. The virtuosos,a rare bunch, extract what really matters from the mass of data available, communicate avidly with stakeholders and match their words with strong performance.\par \par \uc2 The virtuosos head the high-profile Global Reporters survey of 50 companies, to be launched in New York today by SustainAbility, the consultancy and think-tank, in conjunction with the United Nations \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Programme. In this latest in nearly a decade of international benchmarking exercises by SustainAbility, UK and other European companies dominate the top seven, with scores of over 50 per cent (see chart).\par \par \uc2 North American companies are catching up though. Their average score has risen from 38 per cent two years ago to 45 per cent, overtaking the European average, which has slipped from 45 per cent to 43 per cent. There are strong performers from other parts of the world, led by South African Breweries (SAB).\par \par \uc2 "As trust in capitalism and in companies has hit new lows, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  reporting potentially offers real opportunities for companies to rebuild that trust," says John Elkington, chairman of Sustain-Ability. "The companies in this survey are demonstrating leadership in how to do that."\par \par \uc2 The league table illustrates emerging best practice in reporting on the triple bottom line - a company's environmental, social and economic impact. Today several thousand companies produce non-financial reports compared with only a few dozen a decade ago. SustainAbility spent six months choosing the most promising 100 from a field of more than 200 and rating the best of these against 49 criteria to assess their commitment to sustainable development, their current and future performance and impact, and the integrity of their reporting process. Scores for each criterion range from zero, for no relevant coverage, to four for serious, systematic and extensive reporting that is clearly linked to business decisions.\par \par \uc2 While these are the best performers, the findings are far from rosy. First, despite the improvement in North America, the average score of the 50 companies is little changed from two years ago. "Corporate sustainability reporting is in danger of hitting a quality plateau," say the authors of the survey.\par \par \uc2 Nerds seem to have the upper hand. The average page-length of printed reports has jumped from 59 to 86 pages in the past two years. SustainAbility calls this "carpet-bombing" - bombarding readers with increasing amounts of information without explaining its relevance. The Co-operative Bank and BAA, for example, are virtuoso companies with nerdish tendencies. SustainAbility accepts some of the blame for the data blitz because its methodology rewards coverage of a range of issues. It notes that companies that follow the Global Reporting Initiative guidelines, which contain nearly 100 indicators, tend to score more highly.\par \par \uc2 "Lo and behold, sometimes we get what we ask for," say the authors. "But in light of the growth in the sheer volume of information, it is critical to ask some intelligent questions: what issues or performance areas are truly important? Are these the same in all cases? The relevance of sustainability reporting will decrease if companies continue to fail to make this evaluation."\par \par \uc2 This is the biggest challenge facing corporate reporters, especially if they are to persuade mainstream investors of the importance of the triple bottom line, the authors argue. The language of most reports is not yet tuned to financial markets, nor are there enough links between triple bottom line and financial reporting.\par \par \uc2 Given the all-too-obvious risks companies face to their reputation, it is significant that some are now making the link between \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and corporate governance. SAB's report says governance is about efficient, honest, accountable leadership. "It makes sense from a corporate perspective that governance is the lead agent, not only in consolidating aspects of corporate citizenship, CSR and sustainable development, but also in integrating these agendas into mainstream business activities."\par \par \uc2 Most companies, however, are not yet linking sustainability directly with governance, or with brand management, two areas that the authors believe are crucial. On branding, compare the Co-op's "customer led, ethically guided" slogan with Procter &Gamble's report which "rarely, if at all, links its triple bottom line activities directly with individual brands".\par \par \uc2 This year's reports give greater prominence to social issues than before, apparently at the expense of longer-established environmental reporting. The authors say this is potentially worrying. "It cannot be assumed that environmental reporting, let alone sustainability reporting, is firmly established."\par \par \uc2 Coverage of economic issues, though increasing, is largely cosmetic. Corporate philanthropy and bland balance sheets are the norm. To achieve better scores, reports need to consider the broader economic effects of companies' activities, the impact of plant closures, of competition with small local businesses, of payments made to developing world governments.\par \par \uc2 So what constitutes current best practice? The Co-operative Bank is expert at stakeholder engagement, it sets targets and is clear about how it has performed against previous ones, and its discussion of financial exclusion "is a good example of economic impacts well beyond the traditional understanding".\par \par \uc2 Novo Nordisk gets to the heart of the debate about access to drugs. BAA is praised for its dialogue with stakeholders and for addressing difficult issues, such as aircraft noise. SAB covers often neglected areas. It sets out the terms, including corporate citizenship, on which it enters joint ventures and franchise agreements. Chiquita gets to the point with its assessment of its farms in Latin America, using rigorous environmental standards. Its coverage of its failures is "some of the most candid and honest reporting we have seen".\par \par \uc2 BT Group scores full marks for the detail on its supply chain efforts, including ethical purchasing, awards for suppliers and a strong business case. "The company's performance information links to supplier web pages, demonstrating a real connection to normal business objectives."\par \par \uc2 So much for the present. SustainAbility has invented a fifth category of corporate reporters called "supersonics". These companies are accountable, transparent, smart and successful. "The next three to five years are likely to see the supersonics breaking through the barriers that are holding back even the best of today's reporters, establishing new benchmarks and, in the process, potentially transforming markets." At the moment, however, it admits that the supersonics are a figment of its imagination.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.sustainability.com/trust-us"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.sustainability.com/trust-us}}}\par \par \uc2 London Edition 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\asp