faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FT REPORT - UNDERSTANDING RISK MANAGEMENT - Reaping the benefits of responsibility The need to address social and environmental risk issues is rising on the corporate agenada.\par \par \uc2 Social and environmental issues are having an increasing impact on companies immediate operational risk.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 However, they are also becoming a strategic issue, as shareholders consider environmental and social risk in their investment decisions.\par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not just about managing, reducing and avoiding risk,' says Sunil Misser. head of the global sustainability practice at PriceWaterhouseCoopers, the accountants. "It is about creating opportunities, generating improved performance, making money and leaving the risks far behind." At the operational level, there is risk that regulation or litigation will create an unexpected liability that is out of all proportion to the size of the transaction that has caused it. Michael Kelly, director of environmental management at KPMG, the accountants, tells of a bank that took possession of a farm for a \u163\'00\'A350,000 loan, but had to pay \u163\'00\'A3250,000 environmental clean-up costs for an illegal tyre dump on the land. "In financial terms, the size of the hazard is a completely independent variable," he says.\par \par \uc2 At the strategic level, environmental and social risks are an important factor for shareholders when making investment decisions.\par \par \uc2 There is increasing pressure for large companies to qualify to join FTSE4Good, an index designed to facilitate investment in companies with good records of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Pension fund managers are now required to publish their investment criteria, including their policy on social and environmental issues. Even individual small shareholders are concerned.\par \par \uc2 The Millennium survey carried out by PriceWaterhouseCoopers interviewed 25,000 citizens in 23 countries. It showed that two-thirds of respondents want companies to go beyond their historical role of making money. They want them to contribute towards the broader societal goals as well. "They ranked \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of brand, reputation or financial factors," says Mr Misser. "That is not what chief executive officers think!" Reducing social and environmental risk can cost relatively little. In fact, it is much more likely to result in reduced costs and increased competitiveness. "We believe that there is clear business value in being environmentally and socially responsible," says Andrew Vickerman, head of external affairs at Rio Tinto, the mineral extraction company. "We can't create long-term value for our shareholders without being environmentally and socially responsible. We want to be seen as a responsible company so that people will want us operating in their locations." Rio Pinto operates long-term assets. often in remote locations, surrounded by indigenous people and in fragile environments. The most important risk is that if the company is not environmentally responsible, inappropriate behaviour could cause it to lose a licence to operate.\par \par \uc2 This is a risk that any company faces to a greater or lesser extent. Working with local communities ensures meaningful long-term relationships, makes it more attractive to investors and speeds up the granting of permits.\par \par \uc2 Carole Arumainayagam, director for socially responsible investment research at Societe Generale Asset Management, sees environmental and social issues having an impact on long-term strategic thinking. "Companies are trying to position themselves so they don't get exposed by any material tightening in regulations," she says.\par \par \uc2 "Insurance companies have been trying to either get rid of part of their book or include getout clauses when they are underwriting. Oil and gas companies are trying to lighten the carbon element of their portfolios by disposing of coal interests and moving away from oil to gas." Value at Risk: Climate Change and the Future of Governance is a recent report from the Coalition for Environmentally Responsible Economies (CERES), a coalition of investor and environmental groups. It explains that the risks of climate change stem from rising sea levels, weather extremes, temperature and precipitation changes.\par \par \uc2 The report says that in the absence of preventative and adaptive measures, multi-billion dollar losses are distinctly possible, if not probable. "Climate risk is not limited to any one sector," says Robert Massie, executive director of CERES. "The question is no longer whether any given portfolio contains climate risk, but how much."\par \par \uc2 Environmental impact can be expressed in terms of production of greenhouse gases. These can be reduced through programmes to lower consumption of gas, electricity and water and to reduce waste through recycling. They can also be reduced by encouraging more environmentally friendly travel and use of video conferencing.\par \par \uc2 For instance, KPMG, the accountants and financial advisors, is responsible for releasing 20,000 tonnes of carbon dioxide gas into the atmosphere through business travel and 10,000 tonnes from occupation of its buildings. 'You can purchase 'green' energy from renewable resources that does not add to global warming" says Mr Kelly. "However, because it is a scarce resource, you cannot be profligate with it. We are reducing our consumption by 30 per cent and are already saving \u163\'00\'A3500,000 per year."\par \par \uc2 Reducing social risk is largely a matter of drawing up policies to cover a wide range of issues relating to stakeholders. For employees. it includes equal opportunities. covering age, sex and ethnic origin; flexible employee benefits; health and safety; training and development; and trade union recognition. Companies should commit to the International Labour Organisation's core labour standards, the United Nations Global Compact and others.\par \par \uc2 For the community, it includes policies on charitable donations; community projects; fair trading; harvesting of natural resources; use of chemicals that persist in the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  or are linked to long-term health concerns; child labour; and animal welfare, including animal testing, intensive farming and blood sports.\par \par \uc2 An ethical policy is required on matters such as the arms trade, torture equipment, tobacco and corrupt practices. Human rights policies are especially important for companies operating in areas of strategic importance in countries with poor human rights records or that support oppressive regimes.\par \par \uc2 Mr Misser warns that long-term sustainable performance does not come from proclaiming values and codes, but from consistently putting them into daily action. "It is not about putting it down on paper,' he says. "It is about living your values."\par \par \uc2 Freer Spreckley is director of consultancy Social Enterprise Partnership and author of the Social Audit Toolkit, first published in 1978.\par \par \uc2 "Things like this take an entire generation to introduce," he warns. "We are very much at the beginning of a big long-term change."\par \par \uc2 4. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gclimt : \uc2 Climate Change | genv : \uc2 Environmental News | gglobe : \uc2 Global/World Issues | gwea : \uc2 Weather | nrgn : \uc2 Routine General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\in