5\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Daniel Edelman is the nearest thing to a living legend that the PR industry has produced. Like his contemporary Harold Burson, founder of Burson-Marsteller, he built up an international agency and is still involved long after most entrepreneurs have retired to enjoy the fruits of their labours.\par \par \uc2 But whereas Burson sold his business long ago to Young &Rubicam, which was itself later swallowed up by WPP, Edelman's eponymous agency remains resolutely in private hands. It is the only independently-owned PR business among the world's top 10. And this year is its 50th anniversary.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 At 82, Edelman still works a five-day week and his passion for the PR business is undimmed. Now chairman, having stepped aside as chief executive in 1996 to allow his eldest son, Richard, to take the reins, he remains enthusiastic about the prospects for the company and his role within it.\par \par \uc2 "The most important part of a CEO's job is to find your successor, and fortunately I had one in the family," says Edelman. "The way I work is different to what it used to be. I pick my spots. I don't go to meetings with 28-year-old brand managers, but if the CEO of a company with problems wants my advice, I make myself available."\par \par \uc2 Although he has eased up in recent years, it would be wrong to assume that Edelman has become a peripheral figure at the company he founded in Chicago in 1952. When we meet at his company's office in London's West End, he is in the middle of a hectic schedule of meetings across Europe that would be punishing for many men half his age.\par \par \uc2 Sprightly, spruce and sharp-witted despite a head cold, he is fully conversant with the day's news stories and admits to being a fanatical "clipper" of newspapers and hoarder of cuttings. He still reads and comments on internal account win-and-loss reports from around the world - Edelman has 2,000 staff in 38 offices - and keeps a gimlet eye on cash flow. His numerous, elegantly-constructed memos, which have come rather sweetly to be known as "Dan-ograms", ensure that the agency remains imbued with its founding father's personality.\par \par \uc2 However, not everything in the garden is rosy. In common with its rivals, Edelman has been hit by the global squeeze on financial and marketing communications spending by clients. It has shed about 40 staff, and last year saw its margins fall to about 5 per cent. For the quarter to September 2002, margins have risen back above 10 per cent, though they are still below the company's 15 per cent target. In the year to the end of 2001, Edelman's revenues were $226m ( \u163\'00\'A3144m), down 5 per cent on the previous year.\par \par \uc2 Despite the tough economic climate, Edelman argues that the business is in good shape. "We have built up retained earnings, so we can pay salaries and buy new equipment." He says being private takes the pressure off hitting performance targets, allowing the business to concentrate on client service.\par \par \uc2 David Davis, now chairman of training company PMA, worked at Edelman for 24 years, rising to the position of vice-chairman worldwide before leaving in 1992. He argues that its ethos of independence is a major factor in its success. "The commitment to independence has been one of the strengths of the firm, and it is a business that is very strongly managed financially. If you ask around, most people will say Edelman is a sweatshop. However, most people would love to have Edelman on their CV. Of course they work hard, but it's not just the troops. The bosses work even harder, they set the pace."\par \par \uc2 Only twice in the past 50 years has Edelman flirted with relinquishing its family-owned status. In the late 1990s, an IPO was tentatively considered but ultimately rejected, partly because it was felt the business was too small to prosper on the equity markets but mainly because its culture of independence is so deeply ingrained. Before that, in the early 1980s, Interpublic Group took a 5 per cent stake in the company - but Edelman cannily inserted a clause that this holding could be bought back after a year, which is what happened.\par \par \uc2 "We were very unhappy," says Edelman. "We just weren't comfortable in the advertising \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . I don't like it when PR becomes a small operation within these mammoth advertising conglomerates."\par \par \uc2 When PR agency Fleishman-Hillard was snapped up by Omnicom, Edelman bought a few shares in the new parent company to keep tabs on what was happening. On receiving the Omnicom annual report he was appalled to see PR lumped in with a ragbag of other non-advertising disciplines.\par \par \uc2 The Edelman credo is that PR should never be overshadowed by advertising. At a time of increasing media fragmentation, which makes it harder than ever for advertisers to achieve the reach and stand-out they would like, there are undeniably big opportunities for PR agencies.\par \par \uc2 Rising demand for services in areas such as reputation management and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  illustrate the growing maturity of PR. Yet this is a discipline that is by no means recession-proof.\par \par \uc2 Edelman, though, is sanguine. He has high hopes for the future of PR, taking the view that clients are still discovering its values and the impact it can deliver. "We feel that public relations will increasingly be important because our business is based on establishing relationships with stakeholders, whether they are customers, employees, shareholders, the financial community or regulators."\par \par \uc2 Edelman's PR career began in the second world war, after graduating from Columbia University in 1941 with a masters degree in journalism. He put his communications skills to use in the US army in Europe, working in the psychological warfare and information control divisions, where he analysed Nazi propaganda and scripted loudhailer announcements and leaflets to demoralise the enemy.\par \par \uc2 The experience taught him the power of words to influence behaviour.\par \par \uc2 After the war, Edelman was the in-house PR director for Gillette subsidiary Toni, where he created the media tour, taking six sets of "Toni Twins" - women who were the public face of the hair products brand - to 86 US cities. Toni became the first of many clients when Edelman launched his agency in 1952.\par \par \uc2 Though it is the sixth-ranked PR agency in the world, two-thirds of Edelman's revenues are generated by the US (UK income for 2001 was \u163\'00\'A312.5m).\par \par \uc2 It has established a presence in most of the world's top PR markets, but has failed to establish a foothold in Japan - although Edelman pugnaciously insists his agency will succeed there eventually.\par \par \uc2 Driving up international revenues is a prime objective, evidenced by the acquisition last year of boutique agency First&42nd which was bought as much to secure the services of top-flight PR strategist Alison Canning as to tap into its client base. Canning is president of international operations and has set ambitious targets to double international revenue over the next three years.\par \par \uc2 If she achieves her goal, Dan Edelman will surely celebrate - assuming he can make time in his busy schedule.\par \par \uc2 robert.gray@lineone.net\par \par \uc2 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 wirp : \uc2 WPP PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i83952 : \uc2 Market Research/Public Relations | i8395205 : \uc2 Public Relations | iadv : \uc2 Advertising/Public Relations/Marketing\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widct