 of Afnor, the French national standards institute, is to become secretary-general of the Geneva-based International Organisation for Standardisation from March.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Bryden, 57, who has dual French and British nationality, was the unanimous choice of ISO's governing council to replace Lawrence Eicher of the US who died last March.\par \par \uc2 ISO, which groups national standards institutes of 145 countries around the world, has developed nearly 14,000 international standards covering everything from screws to tea and management quality.\par \par \uc2 Bryden's biggest challenge is to ensure that poorer countries, and consumer groups, are able to play a bigger part in international standard-setting, which traditionally has been dominated by the relevant industries in a few industrialised countries. Though ISO standards are not binding, countries are under pressure to adopt them because they facilitate trade and simplify everyday life. They ensure that items bought in one country work in another.\par \par \uc2 The World Trade Organisation also encourages its members to endorse them. But developing nations say they are often forced to accept unsuitable standards that they have not helped to decide.\par \par \uc2 Bryden is a standards man to the core. He began his career in metrology, notably with the US National Institute of Standards and Technology, and later went on to head the French national testing laboratory before joining Afnor. At Afnor, he is credited with modernising the organisation by extending its standard-setting and certification roles, increasing the participation in international standardisation, and putting all its business activities online.\par \par \uc2 This experience will be useful in running ISO, now almost a virtual organisation with most of the work being done away from headquarters. But for all countries to have a say in standard-setting, Bryden will have to be a diplomat as well as a technician.\par \par \uc2 Frances Williams\par \par \uc2 More changes at Kingfisher\par \par \uc2 Ian Harding has been appointed head of financial communications at Kingfisher, the retail group currently demerging its electrical business to focus on do-it-yourself.\par \par \uc2 The move is the latest in a string of changes at Kingfisher under Francis Mackay, the chairman who joined the group a year ago. Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy, chief executive, left Kingfisher last month after 20 years with the group. His replacement, Gerry Murphy, takes up the reins in February.\par \par \uc2 Harding, previously group head of investor relations, is moving to take a wider role that will cover all areas of communication for the group, including investor relations, public relations and internal communications. He replaces Andrew Mills, who is moving to other duties within the group.\par \par \uc2 Susanna Voyle\par \par \uc2 Welton for JP Morgan arm\par \par \uc2 JP Morgan Partners, the private equity arm of JP Morgan Chase, has taken on Stephen Welton in London as it focuses on middle market buy-out opportunities in the European industrial sector. Welton was previously chief executive of TV Travel Shop, an interactive television-based business which he joined in 1999 after leading a buy-out by Barclays Private Equity.\par \par \uc2 FTSE Group's role expands\par \par \uc2 FTSE Group, the global index provider, has appointed Jayn Harding to the new role of head of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . She will lead the development of FTSE's socially responsible investment index series, FTSE4Good and will manage the group's \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies.\par \par \uc2 David Harris, another newly appointed executive, will help Harding. The appointments show that the group's "role in the socially responsible investment debate has continued to grow", says Will Oulton, deputy chief executive.\par \par \uc2 Harding was previously environmental manager at Sainsbury's, the food retailer, where she managed environmental issues, socially responsible sourcing and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Harris joins from Arthur D. Little's global \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and risk practice where he worked on its \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainable development team. He has also worked with PwC's climate change team.\par \par \uc2 Moving places\par \par \uc2 Bradford and Bingley has named Steven Crawshaw an executive director of the group and managing director of lending. Crawshaw, 41, succeeds Keith Greenough, who retires at the end of the year.\par \par \uc2 In an additional move Robert Dickie joins the group's senior management team as operations director in January. Dickie, 43, will be responsible for the group's information technology, telephony and customer services operations. He joins from Zurich Financial Services Group (UK).\par \par \uc2 AT Kearney, the management consulting subsidiary of EDS, has appointed Tony Marshall vice-president of its executive search and financial services division.\par \par \uc2 Peter Giblin has been named chairman of Norman Broadbent, the executive search arm of BNB Resources. He worked as managing director of administration for Samuel Montagu and later became president of Carre, Orban and Nicholson International.\par \par \uc2 Gavin Stewart has been appointed chief operation officer of Britannic Asset Management. He was previously group development director at Aegon UK. In his new role Stewart will be responsible for finance, legal and information systems, corporate development, investment trusts and product development.\par \par \uc2 Ruth Sullivan\par \par \uc2 ruth.sullivan@ft.com. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | c132 : \uc2 Standards/Standardization | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | fra : \uc2 France | medz : \uc2 Mediterranean | switz : \uc2 Switzerland | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \p