rqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 From Ms Ella Joseph.\par \par \uc2 Sir, Your article "IoD hits back at criticism of company social policies" (December 4) was a fair representation of the differing views of the Institute for Public Policy Research and the Institute of Directors on the results of the IoD's survey of its members. Directors' interest in social and environmental issues pleasantly surprised the IoD. The IPPR was concerned that this awareness was not underpinned by effective policies to promote the welfare of employees and protect the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Your comment, however, implies that the IPPR's concerns over the gap between the rhetoric and reality of voluntary action means that its public policy agenda is to push for new legislation on "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ". On the contrary, the IPPR agrees that "as long as a company is acting within the law, its approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be its own business" (Lombard, same edition). Indeed, CSR is inherently voluntary. It is action taken by companies beyond their legal obligations. The policy agenda can only seek to set in train a convergence between rhetoric and reality of responsible corporate action. This is the focus of the IPPR's project exploring how "soft" forms of intervention and market drivers can change corporate attitudes to society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The results of the survey also show that business representative groups such as the IoD are seen by their members as more important than the government in changing corporate attitudes. Perhaps the IoD's own corporate responsibility is to turn goodwill into tangible action.\par \par \uc2 Ella Joseph, Research Fellow, Institute for Public Policy Research, London WC2E 7RA\par \par \uc2 London Edition 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nlet : \uc2 Letter | nrgn : \uc2 Routine Ge