uto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2002 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FT REPORT - FT MANAGEMENT - Moving on beyond plain philanthropy - US VIEWPOINT by Sarah Murray - In CSR, the US has led the way in shareholder initiatives.\par \par \uc2 "You are not here merely to make a living," Woodrow Wilson, 28th president of the US, once said. "You are here to enrich the world - and you impoverish yourself if you forget the errand."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 For many Americans, this concept of "giving back" to society is a powerful one - and it has long shaped ideas of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But while US companies are beginning to recognise CSR as something distinct from philanthropy, and many are starting to incorporate its principles into their business practices, some argue that US policy does not support such developments.\par \par \uc2 The story is rather different to that of CSR in Europe. A study conducted earlier this year by the National Policy Association (NPA), a Washington-based non-profit public policy organisation, found that in recent years, European policymakers had taken a wide range of measures to promote CSR.\par \par \uc2 UK law, for example, now requires pension funds to disclose how they view social, ethical and environmental issues in their investment decisions.\par \par \uc2 Andrew Wilson, director of the Centre for Business and Society, Ashridge College, says different cultures have shaped CSR developments on either side of the Atlantic. "In the US, you go out and break legs and make lots of money, and then at the end of your career, you realise what price you've had to pay to generate that wealth so you give something back," he says.\par \par \uc2 "In Europe, it's more of a social welfare model; about the needs of society being met by government and business working in partnership."\par \par \uc2 Many such partnerships have emerged in Europe in recent years. The Danish government set up the Copenhagen Centre to encourage social partnerships between business, government and non-government bodies. The UK government-backed Ethical Trading Initiative has brought together trade unions, companies and NGOs to draw up codes of conduct governing labour rights and to ensure the codes are implemented in ways that improve people's lives.\par \par \uc2 Few such initiatives have been taken by the US government. "What you have is a notion that the market will take care of this problem," says Susan Aaronson, co-author of the NPA report and senior fellow of the NPA.\par \par \uc2 Where the US has led the way, however, has been in shareholder initiatives. Funds such as Domini Social Investments, which manages more than $1.5bn in assets for individual and institutional investors, seek to influence corporate policy by integrating social and environmental values into their investment decisions and by filing shareholder resolutions.\par \par \uc2 Big fund managers such as the California Public Employees Retirement System, the US's largest pension fund and one of the leading proponents of corporate activism, are also starting to take socially responsible investing seriously.\par \par \uc2 In October 2000, for example, Calpers announced it would sell its tobacco holdings while earlier this year it decided to pull out of four Asian emerging markets - Malaysia, the Philippines and Thailand - on mainly ethical grounds. While many question whether or not this will lead to more responsible business practices in these countries, with more than $150bn of managed assets, the institution clearly has enormous power to influence corporate behaviour.\par \par \uc2 "Activists in the US have effectively made the case that to be consistent in articulating their values, they need to reflect those values in the role they play as investors," says Bob Dunn, chief executive of Business for Social Responsibility, an organisation that works with businesses interested in ethical conduct and policies that allow commercial success.\par \par \uc2 Bob Massie, executive director of the Coalition for Environmentally Responsible Economies (Ceres), which brings together environmental organisations and corporations, argues that US businesses have advanced dramatically in their approach to CSR.\par \par \uc2 "Ten years ago, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (in the US) was confused with corporate philanthropy and seen as a peripheral part of corporate life," he says. "Five years ago, companies were beginning to understand that their financial health depended on more relationships than they were used to. Now it's the rare company that states it doesn't have any policy, and many are taking it very seriously as a key component of their strategy and planning."\par \par \uc2 To some degree, attention has shifted this year as, in the wake of corporate scandals, companies are focusing more on corporate governance and ethical behaviour with regard to their own business practices.\par \par \uc2 Even this may have a beneficial effect on the evolution of CSR in the US, however. "One of the proxies for all of this is the corporate rush towards open disclosure," says Mr Massie, whose organisation set up the Global Reporting Initiative, an initiative that aims to harmonise the way businesses report their impact on society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Corporate scandals have put a tremendous new burden on companies to demonstrate their good faith in all areas - not only in financial disclosure, but also their environmental and social performance," Mr Massie says.\par \par \uc2 For Ms Aaronson, however, such developments still need to be backed up by policymaking. "In terms of triple bottom-line policies, the US government has none in place, whereas other governments are moving that way," she says. "British, Belgian, French, German laws encourage environmental and social reporting."\par \par \uc2 European governments, she says, are debating the best means of achieving this - whether it should be done by getting pension funds to disclose their investment policies or by directly requiring corporations to report on these areas. "But the US hasn't even had that discussion."\par \par \uc2 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \