to\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Nelson Mandela, South Africa's former president, makes a habit of taking his country's business leaders by surprise. Many of them - from Roy Andersen, chief executive of assurer Liberty Life, to Eugene van As, the executive chairman of paper and pulp producer Sappi - recount stories about the day they received a telephone call out of the blue from Mr Mandela.\par \par \uc2 The reason for the call: to ask them to put their shoulders behind the wheel of South Africa's post-apartheid reconstruction.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Their tales follow a similar pattern. A one-sided conversation with a request from Mr Mandela to build new school premises in rural South Africa, followed by a trip to the local community where a new school or clinic will be. And, eventually, large crowds, speeches - and a cheque for a few million rand.\par \par \uc2 Mr Mandela boasts that he has "a 100 per cent success rate in raising money from the private sector". Few chief executives could refuse his saintly overtures. In return, he has used the generosity of the country's corporate sector as a sign that it has the country's social development at heart. For the country's business leaders, building a school has become a \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  rite of passage.\par \par \uc2 In the case of mining group Anglo American, Nicky Oppenheimer, the chairman of diamond miner De Beers and head of the country's most celebrated industrialist family, took the telephone call. Anglo American and De Beers responded by jointly funding the building of a maternity wing at the Catherine Booth hospital in KwaZulu-Natal.\par \par \uc2 When Nicky's late father, Harry, headed Anglo American, acts of generosity were made discreetly. Philanthropy was an unsung practice in the group's headquarters in Johannesburg. The Chairman's Fund, established almost 30 years ago, today gives about R35m to more than 600 projects a year. In the first six months of this year, the bulk of its grants were directed towards education projects.\par \par \uc2 As South Africa's largest industrial and mining group, Anglo American has traditionally been involved in social and business activities now considered well outside its core operations. Cyril Ramaphosa, the African National Congress political activist-turned-businessman, once remarked, the group was the cradle-to-grave fabric of South African society: the bed you slept in was made by Anglo American, so was the car you drove.\par \par \uc2 But Anglo American's approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is changing - not in terms of its size, but its tenor - as it sharpens its international focus on resources. The mining group wants to be a little less discreet about the $20m it gave to charitable and community work last year so as to enhance its corporate reputation as a global company.\par \par \uc2 For so long, the dominant mining group in southern Africa, the group is widening its focus to other parts of the world. It helps farmers rehabilitate land in Brazil, runs an environmental education programme in Canada, strikes agreements with aboriginal communities in Australia and is involved in the "Back to Purple" restoration of heathlands in England. The group also supports small businesses and puts people through universities.\par \par \uc2 The geographical diversification is not to everyone's liking, especially on its home turf in Africa. The Zambian government was devastated earlier this year when Anglo American withdrew from its Konkola copper mining investments on the grounds that costs were far higher than first expected.\par \par \uc2 Levy Mwanawasa, the country's president, launched an emotional invective against the company calling it a "fairweather investor" and accusing it of deserting Africa.\par \par \uc2 The mining group's re-entry into Zambia as an anchor investor had held the promise of jobs, but also roads, schools and hospitals to the communities on the Copperbelt.\par \par \uc2 The pressures on a London-listed mining company to prove itself a good corporate citizen are immense. Multinationals are expected to safeguard the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and bring development to the communities in which they work. Non-governmental organisations, such as Friends of the Earth and Greenpeace, are pushing for multilateral rules to enforce labour and environmental standards of companies operating in the developing world. They also criticise multinational companies, such as BP and ExxonMobil, of "greenwash" - polishing up their images with brochures and advertising campaigns.\par \par \uc2 "The sustainability agenda is fundamental to our industry's acceptability and to our licence to operate. Engagement with our principal stakeholders, and especially local communities, is an essential part of the process," says Tony Trahar, Anglo American's chief executive.\par \par \uc2 "Companies must continue to regard their primary responsibility as being to secure a return for investors. Nevertheless, I am also sure that no company which pursues the shareholder interest blind to the context in which it operates will prosper."\par \par \uc2 At the United Nations' World Summit for Sustainable Development in Johannesburg this year, Kofi Annan, UN secretary general, called on companies to join forces with governments, non-governmental organisations and local communities. The private sector, led by Business Action for Sustainable Development, an alliance between international chambers of commerce, responded by presenting 230 partnerships promoting small-scale sustainable development including the likes of banking group HSBC, consumer products group Unilever and beer producer SABMiller.\par \par \uc2 In South Africa, the corporate sector is expected to play a part in the country's development as it recovers from its racially-divided past and faces its new challenges, such as HIV/Aids. Most companies are under pressure to empower the previously disadvantaged black majority by widening their ownership or investing in the communities they employ and serve.\par \par \uc2 Anglo American has taken strong leadership in the treatment of HIV/Aids, which infects about 23 per cent of its 134,000-strong southern African workforce. It has offered to make costly anti-retroviral treatments, which prolong HIV/Aids sufferers' lives, available to all employees who need them, and their dependants.\par \par \uc2 The move is a bold one. The government does not support the wide distribution of anti-retroviral treatments through the country's public health service. It has restricted their use to pregnant mothers and rape victims. Unless the company secures the co-operation of the government, extending treatments beyond mine premises will be difficult.\par \par \uc2 Anglo American has also turned to job creation through the support of small-and medium-sized enterprises in a country with a 40 per cent unemployment rate. Through its venture capital initiative, Zimele, the group has invested in 21 small companies.\par \par \uc2 With South Africa's social agenda so pressing, it would be easy to shy away from more rarefied arts and culture projects. But the group has maintained support in areas where state and private support has been lacking.\par \par \uc2 Although much corporate responsibility is undertaken at community level, leadership at the top determines the level of the commitment. Anglo American's corporate responsibility record is likely to be considerably strengthened by Sir Mark Moody-Stuart.\par \par \uc2 Sir Mark, the former chairman of international oil group Shell, took up Anglo American's chairmanship last month. He has embarked on something of a crusade to integrate international business more firmly with the world development agenda and to encourage investments in the least developed countries. He is likely to insist that Anglo American follow his lead.\par \par \uc2 * A longer version of this report appears on the web at FT.com, together with a special report on South Africa's National Business Initiative. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \