\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Metaphorically, if not physically, hair shirts will be the costume of choice for the global business leaders heading for next week's World Economic Forum in Davos. While they may flinch from actual penitence, many are experiencing unaccustomed humility and remorse. And for good reason.\par \par \uc2 Gone is the mood of arrogant triumphalism that characterised Davos meetings of a few years ago. Chief executives who were acclaimed then as the new masters of the universe, lofted upwards on buoyant markets and visions of endless growth, have been brought abruptly down to earth. Most have been severely shaken by the impact. Some have been crushed by it.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The cult of CEO as superman has been shattered by broken promises, personal greed, collapsing profits and share prices and a wave of corporate scandals, chiefly - but not exclusively - in the US. Nemesis has swiftly followed hubris, as boardrooms struggle with excess capacity, weak demand, strained balance sheets and ballooning pensions and healthcare costs.\par \par \uc2 The theme of this year's Davos, building trust, is well chosen. However, companies should not interpret it, as too many have in the past, as a pretext for engaging in misguided public relations exercises in the name of "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ". If business is fully to play its essential role as wealth creator, the trust that needs to be rebuilt most urgently is between managers and investors.\par \par \uc2 That means two things. The first is tightening up corporate governance, to ensure companies' operations are transparent and their managements properly accountable. A start has been made in the US, with the introduction of new regulations, notably the Sarbanes-Oxley Act. Some companies, such as General Electric and Coca-Cola, are also making reforms of their own. But more needs to be done before investors' confidence is fully restored.\par \par \uc2 Second, top managers must get back to basics. This is no time for grandiose strategising and empire-building. The priority must be to manage existing assets as efficiently as possible, trimming costs and focusing on clear and realistic objectives. Purging the excesses of the boom years is a pre-requisite of profitable recovery.\par \par \uc2 However, business is also acutely sensitive to external conditions that are beyond its capacity to control. And the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  it currently faces is unpromising, even grim. Growth is faltering almost everywhere, consumer confidence is weakening, Wall Street is gripped by the worst bear market since the Depression and global financial stability is threatened by mounting external imbalances. The economic outlook is overlaid with acute political uncertainties arising from global terrorism, the threat of an Iraq war, the North Korean crisis, Arab-Israeli conflict and strains in transatlantic relations.\par \par \uc2 Some of these problems, such as terrorism, challenge the resources of even the most powerful governments. But others are amenable to resolute and decisive action. One is the economic stagnation in Japan and continental Europe, particularly Germany, which must be tackled by sweeping and sustained reforms. Another is confusion about the direction of US foreign policy and its apparent predilection for "hard" military power at the expense of "soft" diplomatic influence.\par \par \uc2 These issues will not, of course, be decided at Davos, any more than discussions there will heal the ills of the corporate sector. But the meeting offers business and government leaders an opportunity to clarify priorities and show the world they are determined to tackle them. It is important that they seize it. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ocat : \uc2 International Pol-Econ Organizations | weconf : \uc2 World Economic Forum\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Company News | Economic News | Global &International Economics | Government News | Meetings | Summits &Talks | World Economic Forum\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\wi