\uc2 In these companies, bonuses and share allocations depend partlyon how well executives perform on various measures of "corporate citizenship" that are seen as essential to protecting or enhancing the reputation of the business.\par \par \uc2 Olav Fjell, chief executive of Statoil, Norway's largest oil company, explains how such measuresaffect his remuneration package. "Indicators related to health, safety, \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and employee satisfaction are included, among others, in my performance contract and are thus used for determining my bonus and form part of my performance review," he says. "So far, there are no indicators covering bribery and corruption, security and human rights and community development - but these topics are on the board's agenda and are thus indirectly part of the review of the CEO."\par \par \uc2 The cases of Statoil and others are documented in a survey of chief executives to be published at the World Economic Forum's annual meeting later this week in Davos, where the theme will be building trust after the wave of corporate scandals.\par \par \uc2 The 31 chief executives questioned for the survey represent 16 countries and 18 industry sectors and are all founder members of the WEF's global corporate citizenship initiative launched a year ago.\par \par \uc2 The heads of Anglo American, Electricite de France, Diageo, McDonald's, Merck, UBS and WMC Resources are among those who say they are starting to develop specific measures and targets for their leadership teams on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  or citizenship.\par \par \uc2 Employee safety and diversity are the non-financial issues against which performance is most commonly assessed, followed by ethics and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Some companies are attempting to include broader measures of "corporate citizenship". At Coca-Cola, for example, executives are judged on how well they manage people and look after the company's reputation, as well as on environmental and diversity matters, according to Douglas Daft, chief executive.\par \par \uc2 This is a difficult feat for companies, says the report, Responding to the Leadership Challenge. "There are obvious challenges with identifying and then measuring appropriate performance indicators for non-tangible criteria. Although the field is growing in terms of tools and sophistication, it is at an early stage."\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, says co-author Jane Nelson, director of business leadership and strategy at the Inter-national Business Leaders Forum, "it is encouraging that these issues are being taken on board". She cites research into 1,336 companies carried out by Sustainable Assets Management (SAM) for the Dow Jones sustainability indices. Of these companies, 120 report that more than 3 per cent of their workforce receives remuneration based partly on their environmental and corporate responsibility performance.\par \par \uc2 Another sign of companies' efforts to integrate socially responsible behaviour into their strategy and operations is the seriousness with which some boards are dealing with the issue. "Assessing if a company is integrating these issues into its formal governance structures offers one of the best 'quick tests' of whether it takes corporate citizenship seriously," says the report.\par \par \uc2 Dedicated board sub-committees are increasingly common. Merck's board has a committee on public policy and social responsibility while Rio Tinto's has a social and environmental accountability committee.\par \par \uc2 Other companies use a senior executive committee that reports to the main board. Paul Walsh, chief executive, chairs Diageo's corporate citizenship committee. Renault has a sustainable development committee chaired by a member of the company's executive committee.\par \par \uc2 A majority of the chief executives surveyed point to a merging of the corporate citizenship and corporate governance agendas in their companies - not surprising in the light of disasters such as that of Andersen. Jim Copeland, chief executive of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, says: "The most urgent corporate citizenship issue for our firm is good corporate governance and ethical conduct as it relates to our contribution to public confidence in the capital markets."\par \par \uc2 Some of the chief executives have played leading external roles in establishing new standards of corporate governance for their countries and industries. Many are also devoting their own time and energy to promoting corporate citizenship, both inside and outside the company, as central to the way they do business.\par \par \uc2 Sir Robert Wilson, Rio Tinto's executive chairman, has hosted a seminar for institutional investors in London focusing specifically on corporate responsibility issues. At Statoil, Mr Fjell emphasises his regular contact, both formal and informal, with trade union and works council representatives. Ewald Kist, head of ING, the Dutch financial group, has made joint presentations with Royal Dutch/Shell on their corporate citizenship policies to the media, to members of parliament and to non-government organisations.\par \par \uc2 But it is not NGO pressure or media reporting that emerge as the main drivers of all this top-level attention to corporate citizenship. The most important constituency for these chief executives is their own workforce, followed by government and then customers. As the report puts it: "The fact that Time magazine nominated three whistleblowers as its 'Person of the Year' in 2002 highlights the growing pressure from employees on their leaders to be values-and value-driven."\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.weforum.org/corporatecitizen"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.weforum.org/corporatecitizen}}}\uc2  ship\par \par \uc2 London Edition 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 { 