\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Angel Cabrera, dean of Instituto de Empresa, freely admits that the Madrid business school is a peculiar one. "And," he says proudly, "we will continue to work on this to make sure that we look as different as possible."\par \par \uc2 Unlike other leading Spanish schools, IE has no religious affiliation. It was founded almost 30 years ago by academics and business leaders with an independent and liberal approach to education: philosophies that remain in evidence today.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 From what was once a somewhat insular city that played second fiddle to the more cosmopolitan Barcelona, Madrid has over the past few years been transformed into a vibrant and outward looking city, with industry, commerce and multinationals choosing to site their headquarters there.\par \par \uc2 IE has undoubtedly reaped the benefit from this shift in perspective and has been able to capitalise on its strong existing links with the business community. Its MBA programmes have grown in size and the school now spans 19 buildings in the heart of the financial district, 15 minutes from the airport. As Madrid gained in stature, schools elsewhere in Spain have been compelled to open satellite campuses in the city.\par \par \uc2 The city's dynamism is reflected in both the school and its dean.\par \par \uc2 Prof Cabrera, who took the helm in January 2001, was recently named one of the 100 global leaders of tomorrow by the World Economic Forum. Still only 35 years old, Prof Cabrera is determined IE should blaze a trail.\par \par \uc2 The school has a strong focus on entrepreneurship, with 10 per cent of MBA graduates from IE setting up their own companies.\par \par \uc2 "It is part of our mission to be producing future entrepreneurs," says Prof Cabrera. "We are creating value in society, and that is how we see ourselves... an international centre for developing entrepreneurs."\par \par \uc2 The school takes its role in helping to develop tomorrow's leaders seriously and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a topic close to the dean's heart.\par \par \uc2 "What your company does affects the lives of others," states Prof Cabrera.\par \par \uc2 If a company appreciates how it serves society, that in turn may make the venture more successful. But business schools, he adds, have a responsibility that exceeds merely teaching how to maximise profits.\par \par \uc2 "If we are responsible for training the people who will run companies, we have a big responsibility and that is a huge concern for us."\par \par \uc2 Prof Cabrera believes that business schools as a sector have not done enough in the field of CSR.\par \par \uc2 "We are trying to bring the social issues to all the things we do, social marketing, social cases. The world has changed and we need to acknowledge that we are making a big effort in that direction, that we are trying as much as we can."\par \par \uc2 The school offers a broad portfolio of programmes: a full-time and an international full-time MBA with 140 and 150 participants on each programme respectively, a part-time MBA, an EMBA, an international EMBA and an online EMBA.\par \par \uc2 The full-time MBA programmes are currently under review and it is probable that they will be merged in the near future, although there will be separate language tracks.\par \par \uc2 Prof Cabrera says that with 82 per cent of students on the international MBA coming from overseas, the school can no longer be considered as Spanish.\par \par \uc2 Increasing numbers of students from both the US and UK are applying to the school. Camino de Paz, director of the international MBA, believes part of the appeal lies in the language. Participants on the international programmes have the opportunity to learn Spanish. "It is added value," she says.\par \par \uc2 A further aspect of its internationalisation is IE's ties with Latin America. The school is a member of the Sumaq alliance of eight business schools, the other seven in Latin America, that aims to provide executive education to the international business community, as well as establishing a community of knowledge and creating a joint research base.\par \par \uc2 IE has devoted much time in developing these links and the school's strategy, says Prof Cabrera, is to act as a bridge between Europe and the Americas.\par \par \uc2 As for other alliances, he does not rule these out, but states that in the foreseeable future they will be within the field of executive education.\par \par \uc2 "Bringing schools together for a degree programme is tricky. You are mixing things that might not mix very well.\par \par \uc2 "However, for executive education it is an area where pooling resources will work much better.\par \par \uc2 "Having resources in different subjects is a clear advantage because multinational firms will demand it and that is our current strategy in terms of an international alliance."\par \par \uc2 As for new technology, IE has nailed its colours to the mast and made a significant commitment to online training with a Euros 12m investment in IE Learning, the school's e-learning unit.\par \par \uc2 Joaquin Uribarri, director of IE Learning, believes the money has been well spent.\par \par \uc2 "E-learning is a strategy of the business school. We think that the numbers of e-learning models will grow and become more important."\par \par \uc2 The main focus of the unit is tailor-made programmes for companies, but the online executive MBA is also managed from this unit. IE Learning has developed a wide range of multi-media materials and Mr Uribarri says the response from companies has been very positive.\par \par \uc2 Prof Cabrera believes the future of the school is closely aligned with e-learning.\par \par \uc2 The vast opportunity costs of full-time programmes, the blurring of the lines between learning and the work \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , coupled with tremendous improvements in technology mean that, especially within the arena of executive education, a blended online solution will become the preferred method of learning.\par \par \uc2 The traditional executive model, he says, is unlikely to grow further, whereas online training is ripe for expansion.\par \par \uc2 IE, in the heart of Spain, will be ready to respond.\par \par \uc2 Linda Anderson\par \par \uc2 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \