spalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 What makes these companies stand out in contrast to the disgraced and fallen former corporate giants around them? First, CEOs equate great companies with integrity - General Electric, Toyota, Microsoft, IBM, Wal-Mart, Coca-Cola and General Motors share top slots both here and in the league of most respected companies.\par \par \uc2 GE and Toyota get most of their "integrity votes" for their financial performance and the quality of their leaders. But the definition of integrity is more complex. Another necessary ingredient is working within the law and being untainted by scandal. Companies that have been successful in protecting and managing their reputation score highly.\par \par \uc2 General Motors, for example, is said to be "honest, straightforward, no corruption or fraud". Microsoft does well because there is "no negative news" about it.\par \par \uc2 Reputation depends on the ability to prevent mistakes or setbacks from turning into public relations disasters. GM and Volkswagen, for example, win praise for having taken responsibility for defects by recalling and rectifying vehicles.\par \par \uc2 Honesty and transparency are words that crop up time and again. Fairness and openness in dealings with customers, partners, suppliers and employees symbolise integrity for some CEOs. With Johnson & Johnson, "everything is available for scrutiny", says one.\par \par \uc2 As for being "ethical" or "responsible", Unilever, VW, BMW and General Motors all score highly with chief executives. Citigroup, Exxon Mobil and Procter &Gamble have low scores in this category, as compared with their scores for financial performance.\par \par \uc2 Despite the overlap between companies that are most respected and those with the most integrity, 15 companies in the integrity league do not feature among the world's 50 most respected. They include PwC, Johnson &Johnson, HSBC and Body Shop.\par \par \uc2 For a few respondents, integrity is closely linked with a company's record for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  or citizenship. Toyota wins admiration for being "employee-friendly, with few dismissals" and Daimler-Chrysler for social commitment and treating staff well. But these factors come across less strongly in the comments than other attributes of integrity.\par \par \uc2 In the year of the World Summit on Sustainable Development in Johannesburg, the survey also asked chief executives and media and non-governmental organisations for their views on which companies would have the most economic and social impact on emerging markets over the next five to 10 years.\par \par \uc2 The CEOs and the non-corporate commentators agree on Microsoft, GE, BP, VW, Nestle and P&G. However, a number of companies receive high rankings from their peers but do not feature in the top 20 chosen by media and NGO commentators. They include McDonald's, GM, Royal Dutch/Shell, Ford, Coca-Cola and Wal-Mart.\par \par \uc2 The comments suggest that respondents were at least as interested in market opportunities for the companies themselves as in the potential benefits or drawbacks for consumers in the developing world.\par \par \uc2 Companies score highly for technology, innovation, vision and research and development, which respondents believe will open vast new markets for them in the developing world.\par \par \uc2 Microsoft performs well because of the potential of information technology to drive development and because the company "will lead the IT revolution in the world".\par \par \uc2 Nestle and P&G win backing because their brands are already so well-established, or simply because developing country populations need food and washing powder.\par \par \uc2 Some see a gap in the market for confectionery, and others point to Nestle's importance in coffee and cocoa trading. It is a company with great power. "Food has to be distributed better and Nestle has got the potential", says one respondent. Another hopes that there will be "a new policy of food to sustain underdeveloped countries."\par \par \uc2 McDonald's is high on the CEOs' list because of its global reach, because it employs large numbers of young people and because emerging market populations are expected to embrace fast food.\par \par \uc2 As with the question on integrity, profitability and growth are important factors for respondents in scoring companies highly on their likely impact on emerging markets. This, together with market dominance, appears to carry greater weight than whether a company is "investing in social and economic issues".\par \par \uc2 However, being big and successful may go hand-in-hand with making such investments in companies with integrity. GE, for example, has "huge opportunities to invest in social facilities such as roads, drains and power plants", says one respondent.\par \par \uc2 An element of BP's influence is its work on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and renewable energy. And Ford is expected to have a big impact in the developing world in part because of the jobs it is creating.\par \par \uc2 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nsur : \uc2 Survey/Poll\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-