tlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This may be the year when big-name corporate bosses opt for less publicity?\par \par \uc2 There is little new in the notion of the chief executive as a celebrity. Swashbuckling entrepreneurs, people such as John D. Rockefeller and Cecil John Rhodes, have been with us for more than a century.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In our own time, Jack Welch, Bill Gates and Sir Richard Branson are as well-known to the general public as any television 'soap' star.\par \par \uc2 There are good reasons for business celebrity. In the 1990s, many more people became shareholders.\par \par \uc2 There was a huge increase in press and magazine coverage of business and much of it was personal: Jack Welch, even after his retirement, is seen as the embodiment of General Electric; Bill Gates is the face of Microsoft; and Sir Richard has always stood for the youth and verve of Virgin. Books such as Mr Welch's autobiography have become bestsellers.\par \par \uc2 This personalisation of business has served a useful function, giving companies a human face and business magazines corporate stars to put on their covers.\par \par \uc2 But 2003 looks like being the year when business becomes less personal and when chief executives look for less publicity rather than more.\par \par \uc2 Some commentators have been plugging away at this theme for some time. The most prominent is Jim Collins, former Stanford business school faculty member and author of an influential book called Good to Great.\par \par \uc2 Mr Collins looked at some of America's best stock market performers and discovered something remarkable about them: their chief executives were people who almost never appeared in the business press.\par \par \uc2 They were largely unknown to financial journalists and the general public had never heard of them. They wrote no books and gave very few interviews. While they often changed their companies dramatically, they did not talk about it outside.\par \par \uc2 Mr Collins was not the only academic to discover the virtues of quiet leadership. Rakesh Khurana, an assistant professor at Harvard Business School, was also examining the rise of the celebrity chief executive.\par \par \uc2 In his book, Searching for a Corporate Saviour: the Irrational Quest for Charismatic CEOs, Prof Khurana examined the process companies go through when they find themselves in difficulties, get rid of their chief executive and set about finding a new one.\par \par \uc2 "The entire search process is orchestrated to produce a corporate 'saviour', to find a new CEO whom investors and the business media regard as a star ... Not only is the new executive now expected to be the solution to the company's problems, but his very presence is interpreted by the financial markets and the business media as a vote of confidence by the directors that these problems can and will be solved," wrote Prof Khurana.\par \par \uc2 It was in 2002 that this notion of corporate leadership suffered its worst blows. One-time stock market favourites such as Enron, Tyco and WorldCom, suffered serious reverses. Their leaders - Kenneth Lay, Dennis Kozlowski and Bernie Ebbers - once the toast of the business celebrity industry, no longer were.\par \par \uc2 Not all the most celebrated chief executives saw their companies go wrong: GE and Microsoft are still market leaders. Virgin, in spite of the predictions of Sir Richard's detractors, is still in business.\par \par \uc2 But the public style of many chief executives of the 1990s is increasingly under question. What might replace it?\par \par \uc2 Three things: detailed understanding, inside knowledge and integrity. Take detailed understanding first. Quiet, purposeful leadership requires an in-depth knowledge of the company a chief executives leads, its culture and the skills of its employees, along with a thorough understanding of the markets in which it operates. All of Mr Collins's most successful chief executives understood their businesses inside out.\par \par \uc2 When markets shifted, they could move their companies with them. They had an intuitive understanding of what would motivate their employees to move in that direction, too.\par \par \uc2 Why?\par \par \uc2 Because they had been with them for so long. The vast majority of the most successful chief executives had grown up with their companies.\par \par \uc2 There are examples of chief executives who have come from outside and rescued struggling companies. Lou Gerstner, former head of IBM, is the best-known example. But he is a rarity. The most successful have inside knowledge.\par \par \uc2 No chief executive will thrive in 2003 without a reputation for integrity. Investors are suspicious. They have lost money, and sometimes their pensions, betting on people who seemed to be creating new markets and opportunities but who, in the end, showed they could not be trusted.\par \par \uc2 Many companies tried to win trust by spending money outside: Enron poured huge sums into its home city of Houston. Some became interested in the newly fashionable idea of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , trying to show they cared about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the communities in which they operated.\par \par \uc2 These are valuable trends, but they count for nothing if companies and chief executives engage in the sort of dubious accounting and financial engineering that destroys shareholders' investments, employees' pension savings and the hopes of all those community projects that were angling for corporate funding.\par \par \uc2 The idea of chief executive-as-celebrity has almost certainly not disappeared forever. It tends to be the product of boom markets, when everyone seems to be making money. It will no doubt re-appear when some new technology captures the public and investor imagination in the way the internet did.\par \par \uc2 But that is a way off. This year and the next few will be a time for sober, serious, trustworthy business leaders to demonstrate their qualities. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpa