\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Upstart's issues have become 'mainstream' - Pirc, the activist investor, was at one time the loudest voice in the City. But Tony Tassell finds it is now fi.\par \par \uc2 A yellowing, slightly crumpled fax from Lord Hanson hangs on the walls of the Pensions Investment and Research Consultancy, marking one of the corporate governance activist's first of its many victories.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The fax notified of the withdrawal of a controversial resolution at Hanson's annual meeting in 1993 that Pirc had protested would have diluted shareholder rights.\par \par \uc2 The dispute between what was seen as a radical upstart and the great and good of the City became a model for many others over the next decade.\par \par \uc2 But now Pirc finds of itself in an unusual position - many of the ideas that were once considered fringe extremism have now have been widely adopted in the boardroom. And where it may often have been a lone voice in the wilderness, it now finds itself competing to heard.\par \par \uc2 "Corporate governance (has) gone mainstream," says Alan MacDougall, Pirc's veteran managing director, at the consultancy's somewhat dishevelled Aldgate office. "We created a market for other people to serve."\par \par \uc2 While other corporate governance consultancies have sprung up, shareholders and industry bodies such as the Association of British Insurers and National Association of Pension Funds have become more active.\par \par \uc2 "There is definitely a lot more competition. It is a sign of maturity in the market, a sign of acceptance of the ideas," says Stuart Bell, research director. He points to such issues as voting on remuneration reports as an example.\par \par \uc2 "When we first mooted it back in early 1990s, it was met with large guffaws. Now, 10 years later, it is accepted as an important part of corporate accountability," he says.\par \par \uc2 Other issues that Pirc campaigned for that are now widely accepted include the independence of non-executive directors, the use of share options, and conflicts of interest over auditing.\par \par \uc2 Mr Bell, who used to work for the anti-apartheid movement before joining Pirc in 1993, says that, although the consultancy has an activist stance, its agenda is driven by the 50 or so clients of its voting advice and engagement services who collectively manage about \u163\'00\'A3400bn of assets.\par \par \uc2 These include the Railways Pension Trustee Company, TIAA-Cref, the California State Teachers' Retirement System and the pension funds of British Gas, South Yorkshire Authority Pension Fund and the West Midlands Pension Fund.\par \par \uc2 "We only get active on issues that we know our clients are concerned about. We aren't just dreaming it up. On two shareholder activities that we have led over the last decade - British Gas in 1995 and Shell in 1997 - our activities were determined by our clients," he says.\par \par \uc2 On British Gas, Pirc campaigned with other shareholders over the now infamous pay rise proposed for Cedric Brown, its then chief executive. And on Shell, Pirc had raised concerns over environmental and human rights issues at the oil group that "were severely out of tune with where investors wanted to go".\par \par \uc2 Mr Bell says: "We like to think we are ahead of the game somewhat. This can sometimes lead us into an exposed position in terms of sticking our heads above the parapet. But hopefully this is the role that most of clients want us to play. Thinking ahead."\par \par \uc2 Mr MacDougall, a former worker in the union movement before co-founding Pirc in 1986, adds: "We are fiercely to one side of the fence, not sitting on it."\par \par \uc2 He says this has meant that there are always some companies with which Pirc has had a difficult relationship.\par \par \uc2 "I think it would be fair to say our relationship with Sir Richard Greenbury (the former chief executive of Marks and Spencer) wasn't the most communicative," he says.\par \par \uc2 "After we sent reports on the company to him, he always typed a letter back, but he always signed it in flowing green ink. The signature was always embossed heavily on the paper, presumably due to his emotional state at the time."\par \par \uc2 However, Mr MacDougall says the criticisms Pirc made about the board and the lack of sufficient independent non-executives touched issues that were at the heart of what went wrong at M&S in the late 1990s.\par \par \uc2 He points to it as "a good example of where we were saying one thing that the market was simply ignoring at the time but subsequently became to be seen as part of the problem".\par \par \uc2 To adapt to a more competitive \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Pirc is expanding its voting service to provide advice on whether companies are meeting best practice on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues, such as human rights and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is also about to launch a US service.\par \par \uc2 It is moving more towards what Janice Hayward, finance director, describes as a "stakeholder model", bringing representatives of clients and its 30 employees on to the board.\par \par \uc2 This reflects a underlying philosophy at Pirc. Profits are not the motivation for its operations and all dividends are reinvested. In a City marked by corporate avarice, Mr MacDougall picks up the relatively modest pay of \u163\'00\'A352,000 a year and Mr Bell \u163\'00\'A349,000 a year.\par \par \uc2 "We are there to raise the issues," says Mr MacDougall.\par \par \uc2 London Edition 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \