b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , risk and reputation management and the supply chain.\par \par \uc2 The theory is that the attempt to be accountable to wider pressures than the bottom line and to meet the expectations of a diverse range of stakeholders holds the best promise of socially legitimate, long-term success.\par \par \uc2 One of the advantages of such a theory is that it is impossible to verify. Yet there can be no disputing the impact that CSR has had on business thinking. In a survey of 1,161 chief executives from 33 countries, carried out last year by PwC 68 per cent said CSR was vital to profitability.\par \par \uc2 Responsible behaviour toward employees, shareholders and communities is not a luxury for good economic times, but a core concern, they believe. And they revealed a strong inclination to disclose more information on CSR: a quarter said they currently issue a public report dedicated to responsibility issues.\par \par \uc2 CSR now overshadows the World Economic Forum each year. In 2002, McDonald's, the fast food chain, and 35 other leading companies announced they wanted to be "good corporate citizens". This year, (theme: "Rebuilding trust"), several organisations revealed CSR indicators for executive compensation packages.\par \par \uc2 Leo Martin, director of GoodCorporation, an organisation that helps companies implement and measure CSR programmes, says one of the principal drivers is that it is seen as a way of managing risk.\par \par \uc2 "Reputation is vital to share price, but sometimes the link is only properly realised following a major scandal," he says. "In the case of the utility mis-selling affair, for instance, had CSR been part of the overall management of the business, it may have prevented salespeople being incentivised to push services above all else, irrespective of customers' needs. CSR helps tackle reputational risk."\par \par \uc2 Yet CSR programmes have also netted companies a fair amount of bad publicity, too. The way important social causes have been manipulated so as to position brands and products as part of "the solution", has drawn heavy criticism. This was the fate that met Nike's drive against school bullying and Coca-Cola's information campaign about HIV in Africa.\par \par \uc2 The most penetrating critiques of CSR have come not from the anti-corporate left, but from the libertarian right. In a bracing assault, David Henderson, a former chief economist at the OECD, argued in an essay for the Institute of Economic Affairs that not only had business rolled over too easily in the face of the anti-globalisation lobby, but that CSR was intellectually and morally wrong.\par \par \uc2 His argument stemmed from Adam Smith's celebrated observation that people enjoy their daily bread, thanks - not to the benevolence of their baker - but to his pursuit of profit. Ever-inflating commitments to social responsibility will raise costs and prices, Henderson warned, which would eventually be born by society at large.\par \par \uc2 Further, it is not good for private companies to start weighing the merits of competing social, economic and environmental goals: that is a job for elected governments. Instead, managers should serve the people who pay their salaries. CSR risks making chief executives important socio-political players, when justice demands they should have just one vote along with everyone else.\par \par \uc2 Such purist messages are increasingly being drowned out, though and with the active encouragement of the Department of Trade and Industry.\par \par \uc2 Secretary of State Patricia Hewitt has spoken of the "win-wins" of CSR the growth of socially responsible investment, the desire of employees to work for "ethical" organisations, the increasing power of consumers to support "ethical" brands. As BAA executives Sir John Egan and Des Wilson put it in their book Private Business, Public Battleground: "A company that doesn't care will fail."\par \par \uc2 Everything hangs on what is meant by "responsibility": the social consensus will inevitably fluctuate. Nevertheless, sensitive to complaints of windy rhetoric, companies are nervously edging towards independent auditing of CSR commitments.\par \par \uc2 Performance can be measured against standards such as the Ethical Trading Initiative, the SA 8000 standard, the FTSE4Good index, or the 21-point GoodCorporation Charter or against them all, if desired. Article 13, a consultancy, advises organisations on how they can stay abreast of all such standards, giving, for example, detailed descriptions of how United Nations freedom of association clauses can be fulfilled among third world suppliers.\par \par \uc2 Yet if the management of risk is propelling more organisations to take up the cause of CSR, or at least to pay lip service to it, other strands of CSR "theology" are also being questioned.\par \par \uc2 In a study of 25 companies, IRS, the UK employment research organisation, examined the impact in the field of human resources of CSR commitments. Just one company felt CSR policies had brought "a marked improvement in employee loyalty, morale, commitment, motivation, productivity and recruitment and retention". Most felt they had made no difference. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 mks : \uc2 Marks & Spencer Group PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \tr