the rest made up of profit-sharing and short and long-term bonuses.\par \par \uc2 David Reid, the deputy chairman and head of international operations who is due to become part-time non-executive chairman next year, saw his total package rise from \u163\'00\'A31.99m to \u163\'00\'A32.6m.\par \par \uc2 John Gildersleeve, commercial and trading director, enjoyed a 10.9 per cent rise in salary to \u163\'00\'A31.93m.\par \par \uc2 Tim Mason, marketing director earned \u163\'00\'A31.56m ( \u163\'00\'A31.37m), Andrew Higginson, finance director, was paid \u163\'00\'A31.5m ( \u163\'00\'A31.31m), and Philip Clarke, in charge of logistics and information technology, got \u163\'00\'A31.43m ( \u163\'00\'A31.14m).\par \par \uc2 Rowley Ager, company secretary, was paid \u163\'00\'A31.42m ( \u163\'00\'A31.28m) and David Potts, retail director, \u163\'00\'A31.44m ( \u163\'00\'A31.15m).\par \par \uc2 Tesco, Britain's biggest retailer, said the pay packages reflected an outstanding year for the group, in which UK sales rose 7.9 per cent to \u163\'00\'A323.4bn and pre-tax profit was up 13.3 per cent at \u163\'00\'A31.36bn.\par \par \uc2 Group turnover in the 52 weeks to February 22 rose from \u163\'00\'A323.65bn to \u163\'00\'A326.34bn, while operating profit jumped 11.3 per cent to \u163\'00\'A31.48bn.\par \par \uc2 And Tesco pointed out that rewards were not reserved for the top, with all 220,000 staff in Britain sharing \u163\'00\'A3148m in incentive bonuses and share schemes.\par \par \uc2 The group said all directors had met challenging targets set by the independent remuneration committee. "All the directors have once again chosen to invest in the company by taking their bonuses in shares that have to be held for between two and four years' minimum," said Tesco.\par \par \uc2 "Remuneration for the main board reflects the highly competitive \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in retailing and the need to recruit and retain the best people," it added.\par \par \uc2