lvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Do not expect Shell's corporate web site to convey only glowing words of support for its "sustainable" energy policies. It is more a case of brickbats and barricades at "Tell Shell", the open debating forum that is one click away from the home page.\par \par \uc2 Take the topic "What is the appropriate role of multinationals in the 21st century?" The question provokes a gush of angry e-mails. "We will boycott Shell", declares one, castigating the company for its decision, with other western oil groups, to block Chinese expansion into the Caspian Sea.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Scroll down and there is a screed from an anonymous e-mailer on behalf of "Mother Earth" accusing Shell of "killing people and planet for profit".\par \par \uc2 CSR on the web\par \par \uc2 See the Futerra/CTN rankings for the FTSE 100\par \par \uc2 Go there\par \par \uc2 Hostility of this kind is easy to find on the internet, usually on dedicated anti-corporate websites such as McSpotlight. Most companies, while happy to promote themselves as socially responsible, balk at an uncensored washing of their dirty linen on their own web sites.\par \par \uc2 Yet is this not what "stakeholder dialogue" should be about? Is the internet not the ideal place for open debate on issues of trust?\par \par \uc2 If it is, the message appears to have reached only a handful of companies. The largest nearly all carry social, environmental or ethical information on their web sites. However, it seems many do not expect Joe Public to read the material, let alone want to comment.\par \par \uc2 Only 36 sites among the FTSE 100 and 17 of the FTSE 250 offer some means of interaction, according to a survey of the UK's biggest companies by CTN, a communications agency, and Futerra, a corporate responsibility consultancy.\par \par \uc2 While 81 provide a full report, reading these can be hard work. PDF versions of paper reports are common - in one case at an unmanageable 94 pages. Only 14 FTSE 100 websites use Flash animation and only Shell, BP and BT have a forum or bulletin board.\par \par \uc2 Just two, Royal Bank of Scotland and British American Tobacco, use webcasts. This is in stark contrast to the nearly 90 per cent that use webcasts for their financial reporting, says Richard Coope of CTN.\par \par \uc2 Only half the FTSE 100 sites and 36 of the FTSE 250 have direct links from their annual report or investor relations pages to their \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  sections - surprising, given mounting requirements from investors and government to provide such information. Only 23 of the FTSE 100 make CSR material usable by visually impaired people.\par \par \uc2 CSR is meant to be about engaging with stakeholders. Yet 28 of the FTSE 100 sites give no CSR contact details. Is this a dialogue of the deaf? Very few of the biggest international companies say they have taken action as a result of talking to stakeholders, according to a forthcoming survey of global reporting by the CSR Network consultancy.\par \par \uc2 How could companies improve their sites? BP, BT Group, J. Sainsbury and Shell top the Futerra/CTN rankings, which are based on a snapshot of sites in March and April and criteria from the Association of Chartered Certified Accountants. The top sites score highly for being a click away from the homepage, easy to navigate, up-to-date, entertaining and interactive.\par \par \uc2 BT's Betterworld site features independent commentaries on sensitive issues including: "Does communications technology make life better or worse?" It even runs a competition, although the April teaser "How many principles are there in the Global Compact?" - was definitely one for CSR nerds.\par \par \uc2 BP's environmental and social page invites users to create their own site from information including financial results, exploration data, human rights and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Some of these pioneers could be in danger of going over the top. An FT colleague recently had trouble finding basic corporate data amid all the environmental content on one oil company web site.\par \par \uc2 But for some, CSR remains a peripheral activity, says Solitaire Townsend, director of Futerra. "If they are not giving it public profile you have to question how far it's part of the fabric of the company."\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.csr-survey.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 http://www.csr-survey.org/}}}\par \par \uc2 The Futerra/CTN CSR online survey\par \par \uc2 Rank FTSE 100 company%\par \par \uc2 1BP 95\par \par \uc2 2BT Group 88\par \par \uc2 =3J. Sainsbury 87\par \par \uc2 Shell Transport and Trading 87\par \par \uc2 =5Abbey National 86\par \par \uc2 Aviva 86\par \par \uc2 Standard Chartered86\par \par \uc2 =8Reuters84\par \par \uc2 Marks &Spencer Group84\par \par \uc2 Rio Tinto 84\par \par \uc2 Severn Trent 84\par \par \uc2 Imperial Chemical Industries 84\par \par \uc2 =13Vodafone 82\par \par \uc2 Prudential 82\par \par \uc2 =15Unilever 81\par \par \uc2 Centrica 81