Institute. When asked to comment on factors contributing to corporate scandal, 72 per cent of respondents said they believed the personality of the executive was very important.\par \par \uc2 This ranked above a lack of commitment to corporate ethics, pressure to deliver shareholder value, conflict of interest by auditors and investment bankers and even the failure of corporate boards.\par \par \uc2 Students may just be trying to absolve themselves of responsibility, says David Rodbourne, vice-president at the Centre for Ethical Business Cultures in Minneapolis.\par \par \uc2 "They (MBA graduates) can set a culture at various levels of the organisation...culture is what the chief executive and senior management should be about. Some of them get it, some of them don't."\par \par \uc2 The survey, which was conducted at the end of 2002, is the latest in a series compiled by Aspen into the attitudes of MBAs. In December 2001 it published the result of a longitudinal study that looked at the changing views of MBAs as they progressed through the programme. It revealed that course participants were more aware of issues of social responsibility at the start of their MBA programme than when they graduated.\par \par \uc2 This year, however, the respondents - from eight US schools, three in Canada and one in the UK - expressed more concerns about issues of social enterprise. The question is whether this growing interest is a sustainable development, a knee-jerk reaction to corporate scandals or the dire lack of jobs for MBA graduates.\par \par \uc2 Many in business schools believe that there is a sea change in the way students view their MBA programmes and their careers.\par \par \uc2 Tom Gladwin, professor of sustainable enterprise at the University of Michigan, and probably the only academic to hold a joint appointment in the business school and the school of natural resources and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , believes corporate accounting scandals have led to a change in attitude.\par \par \uc2 "It's possible we're reaching a tipping point," he says. Sustainable enterprise, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , social responsibility and ethics, he believes "are now being accepted by entering students as a basic core from which all other management education must flow."\par \par \uc2 The big change has been as much in recruiter attitudes as students' views, he believes. Many chief executives are now voicing concerns that business schools are failing profoundly in what they teach, he says.\par \par \uc2 MBA students are voicing similar concerns, according to the Aspen survey. This year, respondents said that almost all subjects should address issues of social responsibility, but there was a marked increase in concern about finance and accounting courses. In 2001 only 35 per cent of students said that classes in accounting and auditing should address issues of social responsibility; in 2002 the figure had risen to nearly 85 per cent. In finance the figure rose from 35 per cent to 58 per cent.\par \par \uc2 However, 73 per cent of respondents said their accounting classes now addressed these issues, but only 32 per cent of finance classes did.\par \par \uc2 Introducing issues of sustainability and social responsibility to finance courses is not easy, concedes Prof Gladwin. Under pressure from students, he believes that subjects that are stakeholder-based, like marketing, have been able to migrate their teaching more swiftly than subjects that are shareholder-based and centred on maximising profits.\par \par \uc2 Like corporate bosses, MBA students believe business schools fall down when teaching issues of ethics. Women students expressed more concern about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  than men and were less satisfied with their MBA preparation for dealing with this.\par \par \uc2 Overall, only 22 per cent of those surveyed felt their business schools were doing "a lot" to prepare them to manage potential conflicts. One in five respondents said they were not being prepared "at all".\par \par \uc2 But does this matter? Not particularly, according to students. More than half of respondents said that the priorities communicated during business school were not important as a factor contributing to corporate scandals.\par \par \uc2 The other big issue is whether the appalling lack of jobs for MBA graduates in the traditional areas of banking and consulting now means that graduates are refocusing on jobs in non-governmental organisations and not-for-profit companies. If so, will they stick with these sectors when the boom time returns?\par \par \uc2 One telling question in the Aspen survey is what MBAs would do if a value conflict arose in their job. In 2001, 53 per cent of MBAs said they would quit, but in 2002 only 35 per cent of students gave this answer.\par \par \uc2 One interpretation is that MBAs are now more likely to fight for their beliefs. An alternative is that the job market is so difficult that ethics fly out the window.\par \par \uc2 Only time will tell whether sustainable development and social responsibility will become an integral part of the MBA portfolio and whether students will heed the lessons if they do.\par \par \uc2 The 12 business schools participating in the survey were: Columbia Business School University of Virginia: Darden Carnegie Mellon University of California, Berkeley: Haas University of Notre Dame: Mendoza University of Michigan University of Pennsylvania: Wharton Yale School of Management London Business School University of Western Ontario: Ivey University of Toronto: Rotman York University: Schulich\par \par \uc2 London Edition 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpa