palpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The oil company the greens love to hate - Carola Hoyos andSheila McNulty on why ExxonMobil's reputation over environmental, sustainability and human rights issues is so drastically different from the image promoted by Shell and BP.\par \par \uc2 Lee Raymondwould make a fine cowboy: he walks with a confident swagger, talks with a drawl and is apt to shoot from the hip.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 But Mr Raymond does not herd cattle; he runs the world's largest oil company, where his frankness has earned him a reputation as the oil executive whom environmentalists and human rights groups most love to hate.\par \par \uc2 Refusing to mince his words, ExxonMobil's chairman and chief executive said at the company's recent annual meeting: "We won't jump on the bandwagon just because others may have a different view ... we don't invest to make social statements at the expense of shareholder return."\par \par \uc2 ExxonMobil's environmental and social record may not be drastically different from that of its closest competitors, Royal Dutch/Shell and BP. But Mr Raymond's candour and, in particular, his scepticism over the link between carbon dioxide emissions and global warming have set him apart from Sir Philip Watts of Royal Dutch/Shell and BP's Lord Browne.\par \par \uc2 On sustainable development, Sir Philip's tone is far softer on green ears: "I profoundly believe that shareholder value includes behaving in a socially responsible manner and, specifically, the way Shell articulates its way of doing business is that we want to contribute to sustainable development, which is that difficult task of finding the balance of economics, \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social aspects of everything we do around the world."\par \par \uc2 In addition, Sir Philip devotes much of his spare time to his role as chairman of the World Business Council on Sustainable Development, giving speeches on renewable energy instead of sitting on corporate boards and discussing other companies' problems.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Lord Browne supports the Kyoto protocol, which sets limits to CO emissions, and has gone further than any of his peers in backing efforts by the Group of Eight and others to get oil companies to disclose the payments they make to national governments. On his watch, BP made a huge effort to improve its "big bad oil" image, even changing its logo and name from British Petroleum to Beyond Petroleum.\par \par \uc2 "I think ExxonMobil probably has a fairly good environmental record but the question is: 'What is the company's public image and are they out in front in this area?' No," says Amy Myers Jaffe, senior energy adviser at the James A. Baker III Institute for Public Policy at Rice University.\par \par \uc2 Whether ExxonMobil can afford to continue its plain-spoken ways was called into question at its most recent annual meeting. At the unusually raucous debate, two shareholder proposals - one suggesting that the company conduct a climate change report and another urging a report on sustainable development - won more than 20 per cent of the vote.\par \par \uc2 The resolutions, spurred by activists arguing that ExxonMobil's environmental stance could cost the company hundreds of millions of dollars in legal bills, ultimately failed to win a majority. But their support was "shocking by historical standards", says Robert Weissman, editor of the Washington-based Multinational Monitor, a magazine that tracks corporate responsibility in developing countries and in terms of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Indeed, the signs are that all oil companies need to guard their image - if only to get politicians and regulators off their backs. One energy lawyer says governments generally regulate those companies perceived as untrustworthy and unresponsive to public concerns. Analysts, meanwhile, watch carefully to see which companies are best positioned to handle new \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  regulations and international legal developments, such as sanctions.\par \par \uc2 Geography could go some way to explaining the contrasting attitudes of the world's biggest oil companies. BP and Shell are based in the UK and the Netherlands, where environmental issues are high on the government agenda.\par \par \uc2 But the view from ExxonMobil headquarters in Irving, Texas, is different. The US government refused to ratify the Kyoto protocol, and environmental issues come a poor second to America's dependence on cars and cheap fuel.\par \par \uc2 But while ExxonMobil's environmental burden may be lighter than that of its European rivals, it faces more restrictions on where it can do business - the result of US sanctions against Libya, Iran and Burma.\par \par \uc2 By contrast, Total, the French oil major, last month came late to the Anglo-driven glossy magazine party when it came out with its first report on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But the company, blessed with a government less active than that of the US in limiting trade ties for political ends, has no intention of changing its more controversial investments, including a pipeline in Burma.\par \par \uc2 In reality, distinguishing which of the three biggest listed energy companies - ExxonMobil, BP or Shell - is truly the most committed to environmental and social responsibility is far more difficult than pointing out which has the biggest spin machine.\par \par \uc2 One senior executive jokes that the money a company spends on environmental and social concerns is inversely proportional to the number of pages it devotes to the topic in its reports. Though that conclusion may be questionable, high-profile environmental campaigns often arouse suspicion and can backfire. BP's recent push was seen by many to have gone too far and Beyond Petroleum has quietly changed to call itself simply BP.\par \par \uc2 "My impression is that so-called 'environmentally progressive companies' - BP in oil, Rio Tinto in mining - are actually doing less towards solving the real environmental problems than those given a bad rap; Exxon in oil, Peabody in mining," says one mining company executive, in response to a Deutsche Bank survey asking: "Should Big Oil Turn Green?"\par \par \uc2 He adds: "Those companies criticised by the environmental community are normally standing behind better science and better economics in the debate over environmental regulations. My experience is that these companies are led by individuals who believe firmly that sustainable development can be achieved only by a balance of economic development, by energy security and by environmental improvement."\par \par \uc2 ExxonMobil argues a similar line. "Although ExxonMobil was the first major oil and gas company to pursue renewables in the late 1970s and early 1980s, we determined that investing in today's renewable technology is neither an economical nor a responsible way to reduce climate risk," says Tom Cirigliano, the company's spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Instead, he points to ExxonMobil's recent decision to invest $10m ( \u163\'00\'A36.1m) a year over the next decade in the global climate and energy project led by Stanford University, which he described as "dedicated to researching new, commercially viable energy technologies that can substantially reduce greenhouse gas emissions".\par \par \uc2 The environmentalists may not have accepted the argument but most of the money managers, analysts and consultants surveyed by Deutsche Bank were not concerned.\par \par \uc2 One institutional sales broker replied: "I'm actually surprised you wrote this - do you really think it's important? In a market where companies are watching their share prices sag every day, and investors are watching their retirement funds being flushed away, come on. Social responsibility is a bull market issue! If a company can provide nice environmental performance in addition to having high returns then that's fine. Ask yourself about your own investments - how much do you care?" {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/csr"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ft.com/csr}}}\par \par \uc2 London Edition 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\c