Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Has \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  had its day? Not the concept, you understand, but the terminology. During the past year, the term "CSR" has faded out of Business in the Community's vocabulary in favour of the broader notion of "corporate responsibility".\par \par \uc2 The most obvious manifestation of this is BITC's new Corporate Responsibility Index, a voluntary, web based tool for companies to measure how successfully they are turning fine words into action in their everyday business operations. The index covers not just community or social activities but also the workplace, the marketplace and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The previous emphasis on "social responsibility" limited expectations of companies and implied that CSR was essentially a matter of corporate giving, says David Varney, the chairman of BITC, who has presided over the new campaign language.\par \par \uc2 Changed times call for a different approach. By broadening its campaign, the charity is seeking to address the wave of revulsion following the corporate scandals that began with Enron. "We need a response to reputational risk which has got to go right through the company, says Mr Varney.\par \par \uc2 He adds that he has yet to meet anyone who feels confused by the shift from "CSR" to "corporate responsibility". Nevertheless, there is much that is still open to interpretation in the field of CSR, alias sustainability, alias responsible business.\par \par \uc2 This was demonstrated in the fury expressed by big companies, such as Reuters, at being ranked near the bottom of BITC's first CR Index rankings earlier this year. Reuters said it should be judged on its training of developing country journalists something that was directly relevant to its business - and not on how it addresses global warming.\par \par \uc2 For the past decade, BITC has been trying to persuade companies of the business case for responsible behaviour. That mission is being stepped up, which helps to explain the greater emphasis on employees and customers as well as the community and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "It would be ridiculous if BITC had a non-changing set of ideas in a sector where change and initiative and innovation are the cornerstones of commercial success," says Mr Varney, who is also chairman of MMO2, the mobile phone operator.\par \par \uc2 Companies need to adopt a more commercial approach. Corporate responsibility should be "a reciprocal arrangement in which business gets something back - otherwise it's not sustainable," he says. For example, companies have tended to talk about helping "deprived communities". Instead, they should see them as "underserved markets".\par \par \uc2 This is a message imported by Bill Boler, the US regeneration expert brought in by the government to work with business on identifying disadvantaged areas suitable for economic growth. The new thinking was given impetus by a BITC survey of European chief executives last year.\par \par \uc2 They said the factors that would have most impact on their business during the next five years were their ability to attract and retain a talented workforce and their ability to innovate.\par \par \uc2 This year, the charity commissioned research among 1,000 UK employees to see what they expect of their employers. The findings, to be released on July 9, show staff agreed with the European CEO's that responsible behaviour leads to greater innovation and profitability.\par \par \uc2 BITC has also sifted through the entries for this year s Awards for Excellence for examples of responsible behaviour leading to innovative products and services.\par \par \uc2 One is B&Q, the DIY retailer, shortlisted for the "diversity" award for its efforts to employ a mixed workforce, including older people (the company has no retirement age), disabled people and those from different ethnic minorities and religious backgrounds This drive has helped to attract more diverse customers and led to the design and sale of new products.\par \par \uc2 Sue O'Neill, social responsibility manager for diversity at B&Q, says the company sponsored the design of easy-to-use power tools known as the Gofer and the Sandbug. These are lightweight and designed to appeal not only to disabled people but to older customers. The idea of "inclusive" designs stems from research showing that people with disabilities want to shop at mainstream retailers, not just specialist ones, and that older customers do not necessarily want to buy products labelled "for disabled users", she says.\par \par \uc2 The retailer has also introduced products for a culturally diverse market, such as candle-holders and tea-lights for Diwali, Eid and Christmas, as a result of ideas from an employees' "cultural steering group". These products generated more than \u163\'00\'A3250,000 worth of additional sales in three months.\par \par \uc2 BITC is trying to broaden its work in other ways, notably by pushing into the public sectOr. The charity already works closely with the government and Stephen Timms, the minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "If corporate responsibility is to be a key feature of the public service, we must be able to find it in the job description of the prime minister and Sir Andrew Turnbull [the Cabinet secretary. It must run through every facet of government," says Mr Varney.\par \par \uc2 However, there is one controversial issue affecting corporate reputation that BITC does not intend to add to its campaign list: that of executive remuneration. The investor backlash against high rewards for failure will be more powerful than pressure from a charity, he argues. "I don't think we have got the skill base to set ourselves up as arbiters of 'fat' and 'slim cat' pay awards. Our franchise is over the broader issue of corporate responsibility. We cannot change every aspect." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | csmlbs : \uc2 Small Business/Entrepreneurs\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar