\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 There has been an unusual outbreak of plain speaking among the faithful this week. No, I am not referring to the Church of England and its row over gay priests but to a fast-growing movement that can perhaps be called Caring Capitalism.\par \par \uc2 The name it more usually answers to is \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) and like any self-respecting religion it has its own creed, high priests and devotional lexicon. The creed has it that companies have a duty to act responsibly, not just to their shareholders by maximising profits, but towards society as a whole through care of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , ethical practices, risk management and so on. That may seem self-evident but it all depends on how broadly you define responsibility.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The priesthood consists of a group of fund managers, index compilers, consultants and assorted intellectuals who decide which companies are elect, by virtue of adherence to CSR principles, and those that are damned because they do not.\par \par \uc2 More and more companies are ostensibly followers: more than 75 per cent of FTSE 100 companies produce extensive annual CSR reports, though it is hard to believe that many people plough through these since they often include pages of statistics that are about as comprehensible to the lay reader as pulpit Latin would have been to a medieval peasant. Maybe that is the point.\par \par \uc2 The pious tone of many is captured in a statement issued on Tuesday by mobile phone company MMOfor the launch of its first CSR report: "We firmly believe that our mobile service can help to tackle real social needs. This conviction is at the heart of our approach to corporate responsibility and we are determined to understand the different needs of our stakeholders and develop appropriate services to benefit society in different ways."\par \par \uc2 "Believe ... conviction ... determined ... benefit ..." It almost makes you want to burst into "Onward CSR soldiers, marching as to war..."\par \par \uc2 Companies' embrace of CSR is understandable. The intellectual climate has been moving in the direction of greater social involvement, due partly to government pressures and partly to the corporate excesses of the 1990s, which have undermined trust in business. Ignoring CSR is not good for the public image.\par \par \uc2 But as with all religious movements, it involves a degree of humbug and some of it was refreshingly exposed this week by Mark Goyder, who heads Tomorrow's Company. This is a business-supported think-tank that is sympathetic to CSR, provided it stems from a company's deeply held values.\par \par \uc2 "Unless CSR comes from the heart of the company," says Mr Goyder correctly, "it is an empty exercise." He thinks too much of what companies claim to do simply pays lip service to the idea.\par \par \uc2 There are lessons here for companies, which need to guard against being seen as cynical CSR groupies; for the movement's high priesthood, which could do with a little more humility (Mr Goyder takes a telling swipe at the imprecision of some of their language and, by implication, thinking); and for EU regulators, whom he rightly urges not to encourage more box-ticking by demanding a rigid CSR reporting framework.\par \par \uc2 As for large investors, the debate may seem about as relevant as discussions of the Arian heresy at Council of Nicaea in AD 325. A survey this week shows that British American Tobacco, Imperial Tobacco and Gallaher occupy the top three places in a league table of 30 leading fund managers' favourite FTSE 350 companies - even though they are barred from the FTSE4Good Index, which is supposed to promote CSR investment.\par \par \uc2 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | grel : \uc2 Religion\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  