the top of the enforcement tables and so many repeat offenders.\par \par \uc2 "It seems extraordinary that multi-million-pound businesses are still prepared to risk their reputations with careless and avoidable neglect of environmental responsibility."\par \par \uc2 The Environmental Services Association challenged what it called the agency's "rhetoric about reputable utilities". The trade body for the waste industry urged the agency to make a "much clearer distinction between criminals who deliberately evade the law and reputable regulated companies who occasionally lapse".\par \par \uc2 Water UK, which represents the water companies, said the industry was responsible for a "tiny" number of incidents in absolute terms, although lessons were being learned from all of them. Pamela Taylor, chief executive, said: "Given the scale of the task, which the report acknowledges, it isn't surprising that mistakes happen from time to time."\par \par \uc2 Overall, there was a 21 per cent cut in serious pollution incidents to 1,468 in 2002. The agency also recorded significant reductions in emissions of some important pollutants, notably a 34 per cent cut in particulates.\par \par \uc2 The waste industry was again responsible for the largest number of serious incidents last year, largely related to landfill sites, despite improvements since 2001. But the water industry was hit hardest by pollution fines, which totalled nearly \u163\'00\'A31m last year.\par \par \uc2 The chemicals industry was the only sector with an increase in serious pollution incidents. The performance of the metals sector, the construction industry and farming improved significantly.\par \par \uc2 The agency said a significant number of high street names was being prosecuted for environmental offences. Several wholesalers and retailers were fined for failing to comply with packaging recycling regulations.\par \par \uc2 BP Oil and TotalFinaElf were both fined more than \u163\'00\'A350,000 for fuel leaks from 