likely to spark a long battle by international businesses to prevent the move to enforcement being backed by the full 53-nation UN human rights commission.\par \par \uc2 The draft norms bring together a range of legal obligations for companies drawn from existing human rights, labour and environmental standards.\par \par \uc2 They state that "transnational corporations ... shall be subject to periodic monitoring and verification by United Nations, other international and national mechanisms".\par \par \uc2 An accompanying commentary suggests that action should be taken when businesses fail to comply: "The UN Commission on Human Rights should consider establishing a group of experts, special rapporteur or working group ... to receive information and take effective action when businesses fail to comply."\par \par \uc2 The element of compulsion and enforcement contrasts with the voluntarist approach of other international initiatives aimed at promoting \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and has been opposed by the Paris-based International Chamber of Commerce. "We don't have a problem at all with efforts that seek to encourage companies to do what they can ... to protect human rights," said Stefano Bertasi of the ICC. "We have a problem with the premise and the principle that the norms are based on.\par \par \uc2 "These norms clearly seek to move away from the realm of voluntary initiatives ... and we see them as conflicting with the approach taken by other parts of the UN that seek to promote voluntary initatives."\par \par \uc2 The ICC points instead to the UN's voluntary Global Compact on corporate governance, launched three years ago by Kofi Annan, UN secretary-general.\par \par \uc2 So far, 42 US companies and 24 in the UK have endorsed the compact's nine key principles governing human rights, labour rights and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Ronnie Goldberg of the US International Business Council, which also opposes the norms, said: "It's not clear to us how this would be binding, or what the legal principle involved would be."\par \par \uc2 Advocates of the new norms argue that the recommendations will benefit companies already seeking to comply with global standards, by increasing pressure on those that do not. They point out that the notion of effective enforcement is still at the "declaratory" stage.\par \par \uc2 "This is the first time that companies, not just states, are being put on notice that they will be expected to meet these basic standards," said David Danzig of the New York-based Lawyers Committee for Human Rights, which has lobbied for the adoption of norms. "This makes these codes crystal clear." {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/globaleconomy"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ft.com/globaleconomy}}}\par \par \uc2 London Edition 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ghum : \uc2 Human Rights/Civil Liberties | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | utdnat : \uc2 United Nations | ocat : \uc2 International Pol-Econ Organizations\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faau