li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 United we stand a chance - The relationship between the tax authorities, business and advisers is in danger. It is time to set out a bold new collaborative agenda LOUGHLIN HICKEY.\par \par \uc2 Tax planning has been the target of some emotional and ill-informed comment in the increasingly heated debate about morality and taxpaying.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The UK government is worried that tax revenues are falling. The Inland Revenue and Customs &Excise have attacked business and tax advisers for doing too little to stamp out avoidance, claiming that large amounts of revenue are being "lost" from the corporate sector. The government agencies argue that the gap between legal tax avoidance schemes and illegal tax evasion is becoming blurred and that the corporate sector should be reminded of the need to be "good citizens" - mindful of its obligation to pay all that is due. Tax advisory firms are caught in the middle.\par \par \uc2 This hostile \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is alienating business and stifling constructive debate. Why should this concern us? Put simply, we are in danger of killing the "golden goose" of corporate presence in the UK in pursuit of short-term revenue-raising measures. The UK tax system operates within national borders. The companies that create the profits and jobs that generate the tax-take, do not. They have operations and opportunities outside the UK and different stakeholders, be they shareholders demanding the best possible return or other countries competing for investment and their share of the tax-take.\par \par \uc2 Headline corporate rates in Europe are converging towards the UK rate, eroding its advantage, with some countries, such as the Republic of Ireland, reducing the corporate tax rate well below that of the UK. So a business-friendly \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is an important asset to attract and justify investment in the UK.\par \par \uc2 How has this situation become so critical? First, the tax authorities are increasing pressure on business as they seek to provide the tax revenues necessary to fund the government's public sector investment programme. The complexity of UK legislation, the increasing use of European Union law to interpret that legislation and the sophistication of business in safeguarding corporate assets, including cash savings through tax planning, have made it difficult to keep up the tax-take without raising rates or introducing new taxes. So there is a natural tendency to squeeze taxpayers for more.\par \par \uc2 Second, while businesses acknowledge the benefits of adopting wider social responsibilities for their actions, there has been little debate about how this affects the corporate stance towards tax planning. Recent academic comment concludes that it is difficult for business to know where to draw the line on tax schemes. Is staying within the letter of the law good enough to satisfy the requirement of "good corporate citizenship"? Or should business and its advisers be looking to steer clear of certain types of tax planning or avoidance, sometimes known as "aggressive" schemes? Ultimately, policy is the responsibility of government and it is the role of the courts, not the Inland Revenue or Customs &Excise, to decide what constitutes legal avoidance and illegal evasion. But debate on the conduct of both the companies and the government should be brought to the boardroom table.\par \par \uc2 There is a choice open to us. The first option is to continue on the path we are following, which will lead to more confrontation, litigation and erosion of trust between business and government agencies and damage the UK's ability to remain competitive.\par \par \uc2 The alternative is to change direction now to one of collaboration. Companies have an agenda of wealth creation and a host of stakeholders extending beyond national borders. Tax authorities have an agenda on UK tax collection and administration. Tax advisers help manage the complexity of tax law to create solutions that drive commerce within constructive compliance. Each of these has a role in ensuring that government and business work together fairly and effectively.\par \par \uc2 Before embarking on this bold new plan, there needs to be a wider debate on business ethics as it applies to tax and the relationship with government. The role of the tax authorities is crucial to this approach. In a debate on tax avoidance sponsored by the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales, Dave Hartnett, deputy chairman of the board of Inland Revenue, spoke of needing to "raise our eyes above the horizon of the black letter of the law", recognising that rules alone should not dictate behaviour. The initial success of an Inland Revenue pilot programme of working constructively with selected businesses is encouraging.\par \par \uc2 Corporate thinking has also shifted. At a recent public debate on tax, a prominent finance director made it clear that he recognised the link between tax planning and the overriding principles of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This may provide the vehicle to bring tax into the boardroom.\par \par \uc2 From the advisers' perspective, the time for a sensible debate is long overdue and it needs to be raised to the level of general business principles. The current debate fails to deal with the fact that tax is a vital business issue and that multinationals have to cope with numerous tax jurisdictions.\par \par \uc2 There is tremendous intellectual firepower within both the tax profession and the tax authorities. Perhaps contributing to the debate on the role of tax in business decision-making will at last harness the value that the tax community brings to business and government.\par \par \uc2 To change from the current path to one of collaboration will take four initial steps.\par \par \uc2 The first is for the tax community - that is, the tax authorities and advisers within companies and at professional firms - to recognise their roles in making the system work. The second is for common training for the tax community on a framework for ethical behaviour and clarity on their respective roles and responsibilities.\par \par \uc2 Third, tax authorities and advisers need to be connected to the wider business community, to bring tax into the boardroom so that principles can be adopted on the management of tax. Fourth, all players should sign up to a common agenda based on UK competitiveness, including a framework for constructive disagreement and challenge and a speedier way to settle disputes.\par \par \uc2 The UK government understands the use of tax as a competitive lever and has made this clear in the European debate. This understanding must extend to the administration of tax as well as the rates. But if the tone of the debate on the tax responsibilities of business remains belligerent, the result will be more regulation and enforcement, leading to confrontation and division of views.\par \par \uc2 It is not too late to change direction and explore the benefits of the collaborative agenda.\par \par \uc2 The writer is head of tax at KPMG\par \par \uc2 London Edition 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 e211 : \uc2 Government Taxation/Revenue | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics | e21 : \uc2 Government Finance | ecat : \uc2 Economic News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 London Edition 1 | ACCOUNTANCY | Comment &Analysis | Go