gners, such as media and telecommunications.\par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  reporting in the UK is reaching critical mass," said Simon Propper, managing director of Context, the CSR consultancy that carried out the Directions study with SalterBaxter, a corporate identity and communications firm. "In most sectors, it's only a small minority who don't report. Unless you're a maverick, this is an uncomfortable place for any company to be."\par \par \uc2 However Nigel Salter, of SalterBaxter, said some reports reflected genuine CSR efforts while others could be merely "a fine coat of worthy gloss paint".\par \par \uc2 This is underlined by a survey showing that, despite the emphasis on CSR, 74 per cent of employees believe they do not have enough opportunities to get involved with charities at work.\par \par \uc2 The survey, carried out by Shelter, the homelessness charity, to promote its Strip 4 Shelter campaign, found 47 per cent of employees unsure which charities their employers supported.\par \par \uc2 "This research clearly shows that what is happening at management level is not always communicated to employees," said Peter Lambert, of Business in the Community.\par \par \uc2 The Directions study showed that 84 FTSE 100 companies now produce reports, with 11 reporting for the first time this year, including BOC, British Land and mmO2. Non-reporters include Associated British Foods, Daily Mail &General Trust, and Hays.\par \par \uc2 Laggard sectors were leisure and hotels, where only three of 17 companies report, and software and computer services, where no companies report. The Companies Act is expected to require disclosure by large companies on environmental and social issues.\par \par \uc2 The study also analysed leading US and European companies, finding that 22 of the S&P top 50 and 40 of the top 50 European companies produce reports.\par \par \uc2 * Business in the Community has changed its corporate responsibility index in response to anger from some companies that emerged near the bottom of its first rankings in March. The second index, which companies can enter from today, gives more credit for what companies do and more scope to report on issues material to their own operations. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.econtext.co.uk"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.econtext.co.uk}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.strip4shelter.org.uk"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.strip4shelter.org.uk}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.bitc.org.uk"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.bitc.org.uk}}}\par \par \uc2 London Edition 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 genv : \uc2 Environmental News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trg