rd \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Hidden gems are schools that recruiters consider a ripe source of talented M.B.A. hires but that don't receive the attention and respect they deserve. With fewer recruiters prospecting for talent on campuses these days, however, the hidden gems may have to wait for a better job market to attract more companies.\par \par \uc2 For the third straight year, Babson College was named a hidden gem most often. Here are thumbnail sketches of Babson and the nine other hidden gems, including some reasons recruiters treasure them and some of their weak spots:\par \par \uc2 1. BABSON COLLEGE\par \par \uc2 F.W. Olin Graduate School of Business\par \par \uc2 Babson's claim to fame is its reputation as one of the leading M.B.A. programs for entrepreneurship. This fall, the school will expand beyond its traditional focus on new-business creation to put more emphasis on family-run companies, entrepreneurship within large corporations, and entrepreneurs with a social mission.\par \par \uc2 The Wellesley, Mass., school received enough recruiter ratings in The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive survey to be eligible for the overall business-school ranking, but its score wasn't high enough to make the top 50. Recruiters gave Babson students their highest marks for their ability to work well in teams, personal ethics and integrity, and entrepreneurial skills. But companies were much less impressed with students' international perspective and the school's career-services office.\par \par \uc2 Recruiters urged Babson to increase its name recognition outside the Boston area and to attract a more diverse group of students. Less than one-quarter of its full-time M.B.A. students are women, and only 6% are minorities. Babson hopes to attract more female students with its pioneering Center for Women's Leadership, which focuses on female entrepreneurs but also deals with issues affecting women working in corporations and nonprofit organizations.\par \par \uc2 2. EMORY UNIVERSITY\par \par \uc2 Goizueta Business School\par \par \uc2 Emory's business school, named for Roberto Goizueta, the former chief executive of Coca-Cola Co., prides itself on producing strong general managers, but it is also considered one of the top M.B.A. programs for marketing.\par \par \uc2 Emory aims to develop managers with a global perspective, so most students take two overseas trips to such countries as South Africa, Thailand and Brazil during the course of the M.B.A. program. The Goizueta School also says it emphasizes the importance of courage in facing the uncertainties of business and puts students' bravery to the test early in the program with such orientation activities as skydiving and white-water rafting.\par \par \uc2 The Atlanta school dropped six places this year, to No. 23, in the overall Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive ranking. Recruiters gave Emory's graduates strong ratings for communication and interpersonal skills, teamwork abilities and leadership potential. But they received lower marks for entrepreneurial skills, international perspective, and awareness of corporate-citizenship issues. Recruiters compliment students on their professionalism and like the career-services center. But they say Emory needs to strengthen its relationships with companies, especially in the Atlanta area.\par \par \uc2 3. (tie) BRIGHAM YOUNG UNIVERSITY\par \par \uc2 Marriott School of Management\par \par \uc2 Recruiters find that Brigham Young produces an especially valuable type of graduate these days: the ethical accountant. Brigham Young, which is sponsored by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, is considered one of the best schools for hiring students with high ethical standards. And academically, recruiters say, Brigham Young stands out most strongly in the field of accounting.\par \par \uc2 One of recruiters' major complaints about the Marriott School is its lack of diversity. With only 15% women and 5% minorities, its student body is one of the least diverse among major business schools. Aware of this shortcoming, Brigham Young has developed an "extended reach" program to try to attract more female and minority students and faculty members. It has organized a steering committee to lead the diversity initiative and is offering scholarships to minorities.\par \par \uc2 Brigham Young jumped 12 places, to No. 26, in the overall Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive ranking. In addition to ethics and integrity, recruiters gave students very high marks for analytical and problem-solving abilities, communication and interpersonal skills, fit with the corporate culture, and team orientation. Brigham Young received its lowest scores for the amount of work experience graduates have, faculty expertise, and students' original and visionary thinking.\par \par \uc2 3. (tie) VANDERBILT UNIVERSITY\par \par \uc2 Owen Graduate School of Management\par \par \uc2 Recruiters praise Vanderbilt students for their solid finance skills and general-management perspective. Although the Owen School has grown to more than 400 full-time M.B.A. students from 10 when it opened its doors in 1969, it still strives to maintain small classes and a collegial \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  with a 10-to-1 student-faculty ratio.\par \par \uc2 The school continues its strong focus on electronic commerce. It offered its first course in e-commerce in 1994 and recently got a grant from the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation to establish a Center for Internet Retailing. The center will study multichannel retailing, Internet customer experiences, consumer loyalty, and online pricing and marketing strategies.\par \par \uc2 Vanderbilt rose 11 places, to No. 15, in the overall Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive ranking. Recruiters gave students top marks for their communication and interpersonal skills, personal ethics and integrity, and ability to work well in teams. Vanderbilt got its lowest ratings for its faculty's expertise and students' international perspective and awareness of corporate-citizenship issues. Recruiters also said the Owen School needs to attract students with stronger work experience, as well as increase its name recognition in the corporate world.\par \par \uc2 5. RICE UNIVERSITY\par \par \uc2 Jones Graduate School of Management\par \par \uc2 Recruiters are especially fond of the Jones School's attentive career-services department and its plush new facilities. The school recently opened an architecturally striking $60 million building that is three times larger than Herring Hall, its previous home.\par \par \uc2 Rice attracts some of the top recruiters from the energy and financial-services industries, including Exxon Mobil Corp., ConocoPhillips Co., Merrill Lynch &Co. and J.P. Morgan Chase &Co. Such recruiters consider Rice to be among the top M.B.A. programs in the fields of finance and quantitative analysis. But recruiters also find Rice too Houston-centric and complain that many students are reluctant to relocate outside Texas.\par \par \uc2 Rice received enough recruiter ratings in The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive survey to be eligible for the business-school ranking, but its overall score wasn't high enough to make the top 50. Recruiters rated Rice students highest for their analytical and problem-solving skills and teamwork abilities. Rice also earned a high score for being a good value for the money that companies invest in the recruiting effort. But recruiters rated Rice lower for its graduates' international perspective, entrepreneurial skills and awareness of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues.\par \par \uc2 6. WAKE FOREST UNIVERSITY\par \par \uc2 Babcock Graduate School of Management\par \par \uc2 Recruiters like Wake Forest because of its "well-rounded team players," who are the products of the school's highly personalized approach. The Babcock School touts its 3/38 Plan in the full-time M.B.A. program, which features three sections of only 38 students each. Far smaller than the M.B.A. sections at most business schools, Wake Forest's student clusters are intended to encourage more interaction with classmates and professors.\par \par \uc2 As for career focus, finance is students' main choice, followed by marketing and sales. Wake Forest, which relies heavily on the case-method of instruction, also offers such academic concentrations as operations management, entrepreneurship, management consulting and information technology.\par \par \uc2 Wake Forest fell four places, to No. 27, in the Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive ranking. Recruiters gave students high marks for their analytical and problem-solving skills, personal ethics and integrity, and fit with the corporate culture. Graduates received their lowest ratings for international perspective, past work experience and entrepreneurial skills.\par \par \uc2 Recruiters believe Wake Forest should step up its marketing to prospective students and corporate hiring managers. As one respondent to the Journal survey said, Wake Forest needs to "get better PR to keep up with its North Carolina cousins -- Duke and UNC."\par \par \uc2 7. UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA AT BERKELEY\par \par \uc2 Haas School of Business\par \par \uc2 Berkeley's Haas School very much reflects its location near Silicon Valley with its strong emphasis on entrepreneurship and technology. In The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive survey, it was the No. 2 M.B.A. program among recruiters from technology companies. Indeed, even after the technology industry slump, 20% of the class of 2002 managed to find computer and Internet-related jobs.\par \par \uc2 Berkeley also focuses heavily on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues. Along with Columbia University and the Goldman Sachs Foundation, for instance, the Haas School offers an annual social-venture competition to promote new businesses that will produce both "financial and social returns on investment." Past winners have included a plan to convert ocean-wave energy into electricity.\par \par \uc2 Recruiters believe the Haas School remains a hidden gem at least partly because it hasn't exploited the prestigious, well-known Berkeley name enough. They encourage the school to develop a stronger national reputation by focusing more on the Berkeley brand.\par \par \uc2 Still, the Haas School managed to rise by one position, to No. 14, in the overall Journal ranking and can call itself the "best in the West." Though it often finds itself in the shadow of Stanford University's business school, Haas placed higher than any of the other business schools in the Western U.S. Berkeley graduates received their highest ratings for teamwork skills, analytical and problem-solving abilities, and personal ethics and integrity. Recruiters gave Berkeley its lowest ratings for the career-services office, willingness of students to relocate for their jobs, and the likelihood of recruiting "stars."\par \par \uc2 8. INDIANA UNIVERSITY\par \par \uc2 Kelley School of Business\par \par \uc2 Indiana University's M.B.A. students are considered strongest in marketing and accounting and are especially popular with such major Midwestern companies as General Mills Inc., Whirlpool Corp. and Eli Lilly &Co. In The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive survey, Indiana was rated second by recruiters from consumer-product manufacturers.\par \par \uc2 Indiana is increasing its technology focus, thanks in part to its close ties with alumnus John T. Chambers, president and chief executive officer of Cisco Systems Inc. The Kelley School has established an e-business major and an endowed chair in Internet systems in honor of Mr. Chambers. He also recently committed $1 million for an endowment to create Chambers internships for students majoring in information systems, entrepreneurship or e-business. They will get the chance to spend 10 to 12 weeks working alongside the chief executive or chief operating officer of emerging companies.\par \par \uc2 Indiana rose two places, to No. 12, in the overall Journal ranking. Recruiters gave Indiana graduates high marks for their teamwork skills, personal ethics and integrity, and fit with the corporate culture. Students scored lower, however, on international perspective and entrepreneurial skills. Recruiters also encouraged Indiana to try to attract more women and minorities to its M.B.A. program.\par \par \uc2 9. (tie) IESE\par \par \uc2 The International Graduate School of Management of the University of Navarra\par \par \uc2 Established in 1958, Barcelona-based IESE began life as an executive-education program for the Spanish-speaking market. After forging an alliance with Harvard Business School, IESE offered Europe's first two-year M.B.A. program in 1964.\par \par \uc2 The relationship between the two schools continues: They work together on executive education and recently collaborated on a Harvard M.B.A. course about competitiveness and economic development that IESE students received in Barcelona through Internet and digitized video technology.\par \par \uc2 IESE offers a general-management education but is distinctive in its humanistic approach, which emphasizes the personal, social and ethical consequences of business leadership and decision-making. Though it has links to the Roman Catholic lay organization Opus Dei, IESE notes that its admissions policies are nondenominational.\par \par \uc2 Although IESE received enough recruiter ratings in The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive survey to be eligible for the overall business-school ranking, its score wasn't high enough to make the top 50. IESE did, however, place eighth in a separate ranking of international business schools. IESE students received their highest ratings for personal ethics and integrity, general management point-of-view, and analytical and problem-solving skills. But recruiters were much less satisfied with the past acceptance rate of job offers by graduates and students' previous work experience. Some recruiters consider IESE too focused on Spain and not international enough in its reach.\par \par \uc2 9. (tie) Instituto de Empresa\par \par \uc2 Located in the heart of Madrid, Instituto de Empresa is an independent business school that was founded in 1973. More than a third of IE's M.B.A. graduates land jobs in financial services and management consulting. But entrepreneurship is a popular academic concentration, too. More than 15% of the school's M.B.A. graduates start their own businesses.\par \par \uc2 Even before the recent wave of corporate scandals, IE had focused on ethical issues in its curriculum. But Dean Angel Cabrera recently went further and drafted a proposed oath for M.B.A. students to pledge their commitment to ethics and social responsibility in their careers.\par \par \uc2 IE rose seven places, to No. 36, in the overall Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive ranking. In the international ranking, it placed third.\par \par \uc2 The school received its highest scores for students' teamwork abilities and general management point-of-view, the quality of past hires, and faculty expertise. Recruiters gave IE its lowest scores for graduates' fit with the corporate culture, the career-services office, and students' work experience. As with IESE, recruiters complained that IE doesn't market itself enough internationally and consequently fails to attract many companies from the U.S. and other countries.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Journal Link: Additional information on these hidden gems, plus more detailed results, is featured in "The Wall Street Journal Guide to the Top Business Schools, 2004," a Wall Street Journal Book, published by Free Press and available at WSJbooks.com. \par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLI