to\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Verifying the facts is a difficult task - PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT - But key performance indicators are finally becoming more sophisticated, writes Roger Cowe.\par \par \uc2 Executives are fond of the saying "what getsmeasured, gets managed" - and measuring \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) performance has been a boom industry in the past few years.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 There is more public reporting by companies than ever, and it is no longer restricted to the largest or most controversial multinationals. An analysis* published this month, found that more than half of the UK's top 250 companies now produce some kind of social or environmental information. These figures have grown rapidly in the past few years, driven largely by the requirements for inclusion in stock market indices such as FTSE4Good, and by the need to demonstrate responsible business behaviour.\par \par \uc2 Report content and quality varies greatly, and only 45 of the 132 documents were independently verified or audited.\par \par \uc2 The advance of the Global Reporting Initiative (GRI) is bringing greater uniformity, however, on an international level. This UN-supported, multi-stakeholder body has developed a set of generally applicable reporting principles and measures, and is now working on guidelines for individual sectors.\par \par \uc2 Research by the consultancy, CSR Network, found that almost half of the world's 100 biggest companies produced a social or environmental report last year, with most of the leaders making some reference to GRI. Even so, comparability will remain elusive. CSR performance cannot be encapsulated in two or three indicators - as financial performance can with measures, such as sales, earnings or asset value.\par \par \uc2 Simon Propper, an environmental reporting veteran and one of the consultants behind the UK reporting analysis, says it is naive to assume such reports can be used in the same way as financial accounts, to compare performance directly.\par \par \uc2 "The value of CSR reports is in what they reveal about a company," he says. "Good reports tell you very quickly that the company has thought seriously about these issues - and how they affect their business."\par \par \uc2 That is important, but it is not enough for investors who want to rank companies, nor for customers, employees or campaigners who want to assess corporate responsibility.\par \par \uc2 Increasingly, companies also want hard numbers to use internally in performance appraisal and incentive schemes, although such measures tend to be specifically related to executives' particular responsibilities, rather than generic issues.\par \par \uc2 Measurement is getting more sophisticated. Environmental performance is easiest to gauge, and one organisation has developed a method for narrowing it down to a single figure.\par \par \uc2 The company, Trucost, uses economic modelling and companies' own accounting information to assess the environmental "externalities" which are not captured in conventional financial accounts.\par \par \uc2 The Trucost rating indicates the scale of these unaccounted costs - and since this is a single number, it can be used to compare different companies or the progress of an individual organisation.\par \par \uc2 Much of the work on assessing CSR has been done by (or for) investors. Initially, this was based on pass/fail criteria which delivered a "seal of approval".\par \par \uc2 This is the case with the FTSE4Good indices, which include companies that meet set standards. They do not attempt to measure performance above that minimum to create a ranking.\par \par \uc2 The Dow Jones Sustainability Indices are slightly different. Rather than setting a hurdle, they include companies judged to be the most sustainable in their sector.\par \par \uc2 There is still no attempt to rank index members, although the DJSI does name sector leaders. For example, Toyota has just been named as the leading carmaker in the sustainability listings, while Pearson (the FT's owner) has won the accolade in the media sector.\par \par \uc2 This is fine for investors who simply want a basket of companies which are more responsible than the rest. But for those who want to pick individual stocks, more refined measurement is needed.\par \par \uc2 Morley Fund Managers, the investment arm of Aviva, provides some help with its socially responsible investment matrix.\par \par \uc2 Morley's analysts have graded FTSE100 companies according to two dimensions - the nature of the business they are in, and the level of responsibility with which the company is managed. Thus, BP and Shell are ranked D on an A to E scale, because the oil business is inherently unsustainable. But they both gain a score of two on the one-to-five management scale because Morley thinks highly of their management vision and strategy (none of the top 100 yet merits a perfect score of one).\par \par \uc2 Specialist rating agencies have now taken this kind of approach further. Organisations, such as CoreRatings and Innovest, assign CSR ratings in the style of the debt markets, with a pinnacle of AAA, down through AA, A to BBB, and so on. These grades are based on in-depth analysis of the issues facing companies and how well they deal with them.\par \par \uc2 These approaches are all aimed specifically at investors. Business in the Community (BitC) has developed an index for wider consumption, which aims to create responsibility league tables, based on information supplied by the participating companies.\par \par \uc2 It covers companies' impacts in the community, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the market and the workplace and aims to assess the extent to which companies translate strategy into responsible practice.\par \par \uc2 The first Corporate Responsibility Index was published earlier this year, and proved highly controversial, especially among companies which were ranked at the bottom of the league, despite what they regarded as important social responsibility initiatives.\par \par \uc2 After some tweaking, the organisation has just launched the research for the second Index - and David Varney, chairman of BItC and of the mobile phone company mmO, says it is important for companies to submit to such measurement.\par \par \uc2 "A sceptical audience wants what companies are doing to be measured and wants what they are saying to be verified," he says. "It's also important because companies learn from one another - and that provides an opportunity to improve their impact."\par \par \uc2 Based on its index experience, BitC has also recently published a set of indicators which aim to capture CSR performance across the board. They demonstrate the fragmented nature of CSR measurement - there are 33 core indicators and a further 17 relevant only for certain industries.\par \par \uc2 The BitC team comments: "The difficulty of finding like-for-like information was identified, making it difficult to compare across sectors - and even within sectors. This was especially true for social impact areas."\par \par \uc2 This is a key problem for both internal and external assessment - social and environmental responsibility covers a wide range of issues, many of which are not easily susceptible to measurement.\par \par \uc2 There is a danger that any assessment ends up with a mass of measures which may be meaningful individually, yet, collectively, are of little use. However, companies are now becoming smarter at focusing on the key issues - and in developing Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) which are integrated in management processes. For example, the construction group, Carillion, has encapsulated sustainability in just 13 KPIs, ranging from workforce diversity to customer retention, and including a single measure for "sustainability targets achieved".\par \par \uc2 These KPIs link both to group objectives, such as earnings growth, and sustainability objectives, such as environmental protection.\par \par \uc2 Carillion demonstrates that it is possible to hack through the tangle of measures to create indicators that are both useful and meaningful. But it is still hard to be sure that what is measured is what should be managed rather, than simply what can be measured. * Directions 3, published by Context Group and Salter Baxter\par \par \uc2 3. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15