 \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The Johannesburg Securities Exchange hopes to capitalise on both trends by launching a socially responsible investment (SRI) index. The index will include only companies that meet "triple bottom-line" criteria, covering financial, social and environmental responsibility. It will be the world's third such index, and the developing world's first, with a launch expected early next year.\par \par \uc2 JSE officials say the idea grew out of last year's United Nations World Summit on Sustainable Development, held down the street from the exchange in the Johannesburg suburb of Sandton. "Everyone was talking about what to do to put flesh on the bones of what this country is doing," says Russell Loubser, the exchange's chief executive officer.\par \par \uc2 Exchange officials admit that more than do-gooding is at stake. Since the technology-stock bear market and the string of corporate scandals, big US pension funds like Calpers have become doubly scrupulous about investing their money only in companies and markets with top-notch corporate governance and ethical standards.\par \par \uc2 A UK law passed in July requires pension fund trustees to disclose their policies on socially responsible investment. While the law sets no specific quotas on social investment, the new rules are expected to lead to a significant increase in ethical investment.\par \par \uc2 "We'll be able to use this as a focus for a marketing perspective internationally," says Nicky Newton-King, the JSE's deputy CEO. "Whether you like it or not, if you're in an emerging market - and in an emerging market in Africa especially - you have to be squeaky-clean."\par \par \uc2 The JSE needs all the attention it can get after a year in which its share trading volumes have fallen sharply. Mr Loubser warned the exchange's staff last month that at least 10 per cent of them would have to be made redundant due to tough trading conditions. The SRI may indeed help the JSE draw in new niche investors.\par \par \uc2 But giving South African companies a clean bill of health will take several more months. The exchange plans to invite the top 160 of the JSE's roughly 450 companies, accounting for 99 per cent of its R 1,5000bn total market capitalisation, to participate. Companies will be asked to complete questionnaires on their corporate governance standards, environmental policies, health and safety records and other practices.\par \par \uc2 In devising methodology for the SRI, JSE officials studied the two existing SRI benchmarks, London's FTSE4Good index series and the Dow Jones Sustainability Indexes. The exchange plans to "grade" companies on its triple bottom-line credentials, with each of the three pillars divided into several aspects covering such areas as corporate governance, health and safety and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Given South Africa's different social realities, says Ms Newton-King, the JSE's index will also quiz companies on such issues as their black economic empowerment credentials and HIV/ Aids policies. Companies which exceed given criteria in an area will be granted additional points, allowing the exchange to rank companies on their social responsibility.\par \par \uc2 Unlike FTSE4Good, the JSE's SRI index will not automatically exclude industries some investors consider unethical, such as tobacco, gaming or arms production. The exchange was due to release final criteria for the index at the end of September, as this report went to press.\par \par \uc2 Does it pay for companies to be socially responsible? JSE officials hope to have a partial answer once the new SRI index begins trading and can be measured against the JSE's others. The real test will be whether the benchmark succeeds in drawing new money into the JSE's listed companies.\par \par \uc2 Whether or not it does, exchange officials say they need to begin screening companies on responsibility standards as a matter of course. "I don't assume it's a passing fad," says Mr Loubser. "It's putting things in place that can eliminate reasons people have not to invest."\par \par \uc2 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 e12 : \uc2 Economic/Monetary Policy | e51 : \uc2 Trade/External Payments | ecat : \uc2 Economic News | m11 : \uc2 Equity Markets | mcat : \uc2 Commodity/Financial Market News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 1 | INVESTING IN SOUTH AFRICA | Economic News | Equities | Inward &Outward Investment | Market News | Markets | South Africa | Africa | Sub-Saharan Africa\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PUB\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\r