say in the future of the industry. In such an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it is all too easy to neglect the most important voice of all: the customer. Even the best-run telecommunications companies can struggle to maintain their focus.\par \par \uc2 And the external pressures have become greater in the wake of corporate scandals at companies such as WorldCom, the cable company Adelphia and Enron. Michel Powell, chairman of the US Federal Communications Commission (FCC), said recently that the behaviour of such companies "violates the trust of their employees, violates the trust of the market, violates the trust of the consumers and people cry out to be protected."\par \par \uc2 But arguably the greatest challenge for telecoms companies is an internal one - how to change the mindset of their own staff. According to Nigel Deighton, vice-president and director of research at the Gartner research and advisory firm, "even the biggest players have yet to learn how to really listen to their customers." He says that one of the few examples of companies which have done this was Energis in its early days in the UK. "They did listen and for a while they took a lot of business from BT. They had no choice because they were the new kids on the block."\par \par \uc2 One manifestation of the problem, adds Mr Deighton, is that companies persist in trying to sell technologies such as ISDN, DSL, Wap, GPRS or 3G - instead of developing services that deliver value to the end user. "If there is no value proposition," he says, "then people won't buy."\par \par \uc2 He argues that telecoms companies are still failing to grasp that they face a problem of social engineering. "One of the biggest barriers to the take-up of new services is that they usually require people to change they way they behave. The business and technology aspects might be fine, but that's no good if people won't use it."\par \par \uc2 One of the reasons why mobile voice services took off so rapidly was that they did not face this problem, he adds. "Everyone understands the value of a payphone in the pocket," he says. "Mobile phones are easy to use, they have utility and you can use them everywhere. The transition to the next stage will be much more difficult."\par \par \uc2 Usability is a key issue in this respect, (see article below on Nokia), as is the industry's ability to give consumers a wide choice of devices. Qualcomm, the US pioneer of CDMA technology which supplies chipsets to manufacturers of mobile handsets and infrastructure, agrees that segmentation is crucial to satisfying customer needs.\par \par \uc2 Jeffrey Belk, the company's senior vice-president of marketing, points out that mobile operators in South Korea and Japan, which have been by far the most successful in the world in introducing advanced mobile services, offer their subscribers a huge range of differentiated handsets from a variety of manufacturers. He argues that operators and manufacturers have to realise that different customers have different needs and to act appropriately. "The phrases 'killer application' and 'anytime, anywhere' are both banned in my office," he says.\par \par \uc2 At the same time, telecoms companies have to be aware that there is a growing need to satisfy other customer requirements. In the US, for instance, consumer concern with \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) is running at a 10-year high, partly in response to the wave of corporate scandals and partly as a result of the events of September 11 2001, according to the recently released 2002 Corporate Citizenship Study by Cone/Roper, a strategy firm linking companies and social issues.\par \par \uc2 Cone/Roper adds that previous studies had emphasised that, provided that quality and price were equal, consumers preferred to buy from companies that supported good causes. But the latest study indicates that consumer views have moved further and that now they "are willing to use their individual power to punish those companies that do not share their values."\par \par \uc2 Paul Scott, director of Next Step Consulting, a UK consultancy focusing on corporate environmental and social policy, strategy and communications, warns that there is a wide range of issues waiting to trip up companies once one starts looking at corporate responsibility and brand reputation - especially in the information and communication technology sector.\par \par \uc2 "Some of these issues are widely recognised - such as handset recycling, the siting of base stations, or the evidence of health impacts from electro-magnetic radiation," he says. "But supply chain issues for complex products will rise up the public agenda. For instance, mining an ore for a vital component - tantalum capacitors - is currently fuelling conflicts in the Democratic Republic of Congo."\par \par \uc2 He adds that companies are recognising that they need both to tackle such issues, and also to report publicly on what they are doing. Next Step tracks this through its website CorporateRegister.com, claimed to be the world's largest online directory of non-financial reporting, which analysts, regulators and consumers use to keep abreast of individual company performance.\par \par \uc2 One way to address the question of values is through cause-related marketing. Several studies indicate that sponsorship of "good causes" is a particularly effective marketing tool.\par \par \uc2 The company Tribute Third Millennium, which specialises in entertainment-based campaigns involving live televised events, says that telecommunications companies are showing a growing interest in this area. Tribute is setting up a series of five global cause-related campaigns, the first two focusing on the issues of peace-making and disadvantaged children, which it expects to generate an aggregate world television audience of more than 3bn over the next five years. Tony Hollingsworth, chief executive, says that telecoms companies increasingly see the value of this sort of exposure.\par \par \uc2 Neil McCartney is the director of McCartney Media (neil.mccartney@mccartneymedia.co.uk)\par \par \uc2 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i7902 : \uc2 Telecommunications\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | c31 : \uc2 Marketing\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 usa : \uc2 United States | namz : \uc2 North America\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \ce