tbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Studying the ecology of the threatened barasingha deer was how Swiss-born Claude Martin, director-general of the World Wildlife Fund, began his career at the organisation in the early 1970s.\par \par \uc2 Then, as a young science graduate, he found himself living in India. His experience is a good example of the sorts of career paths that are possible within the non-profit sector.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "Senior positions are often filled by people who've come up from being young graduates," says Dorothy Bray, director of WWF International's human resources development department.\par \par \uc2 "People tend to stay within the organisation because it's an attractive, intellectual, stimulating and multicultural \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in which to work."\par \par \uc2 Of course, this also means that these organisations are competitive places in which to seek a position. Mary Blue Magruder, director of public affairs for the Earthwatch Institute in the US, recalls that an advertisement for a job as a web designer at the organisation attracted about 800 applicants.\par \par \uc2 And not all organisations are as large as the WWF and Earthwatch. "We have 150 paid employees and we don't have a high staff turnover," says Carol Hughes, human resources manager at Friends of the Earth in the UK. "So if you do the maths, you'll see that there aren't always a lot of shoes to move into."\par \par \uc2 However, non-profit organisations can grow rapidly, providing a wider range of career opportunities for those that remain with them. When Ms Magruder joined Earthwatch, it had 300 volunteers and a budget of $300,000. Today, it has 4,000 volunteers and a budget of $10m.\par \par \uc2 What is more, while organisations will be looking for people with appropriate skills - the WWF, for example, needs scientists and people with environmental and ecological qualifications - such organisations also rely on a wide range of support staff, including accountants, marketing executives, fundraisers and administrators.\par \par \uc2 Salaries in the sector, while not matching those of companies, have risen in the past decade. "Our policy is to be in the middle of the market," says Ms Bray. "And we do regular salary surveys to make sure that's where we are."\par \par \uc2 At the same time, the non-profit sector has become far more professional in the way it operates. As \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  gains ground, a growing number of charities and non-governmental organisations (NGOs) are working with companies in the private sector.\par \par \uc2 Training and development has also taken on more importance.\par \par \uc2 "The sector is becoming more professional," says Paul Canal, managing director of Charity People, the UK-based recruitment agency.\par \par \uc2 Mr Canal advises graduates to gain some life experience, such as heading a local scout's organisation or running a branch of Greenpeace, before applying for a job in the non-profit sector.\par \par \uc2 HR directors from the sector also stress the importance of doing volunteering work, either during holidays while studying, or immediately after graduating. "Volunteering is always incredibly helpful both for the graduates and the organisation," says Ms Hughes. "Because it gives graduates an idea of the sorts of things that go on [in the sector] and they can ask themselves: 'Is this what I want to do and is it consistent with my values?' which is very important for a lot of graduates now." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gedu : \uc2 Education | gjob : \uc2 Labor Issues | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | genv : \uc2 Environmental News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 india : \uc2 India | switz : \uc2 Switzerland | asiaz : \uc2 Asia | devgcoz : \uc2 Emerging Market Countries | dvpcoz : \uc2 Developing Economies | eurz : \uc2 Europe | indsubz : \uc2 Indian Subcontinent | sasiaz : \uc2 Southern Asia | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clv