spnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 NEW YORK -- For a growing number of business-school graduates, the business of behaving ethically is back in vogue.\par \par \uc2 At business schools across the U.S., future business leaders are learning how to be kinder, gentler managers. In fact, if you are thinking about getting a master's of business administration degree, be prepared to learn how to use your financial analysis, accounting and marketing skills to help out the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the community.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 While that may come as a surprise to those who think of business school as a breeding ground for hard-charging executives obsessed with bottom-line results, it also reflects the realities that corporations are dealing with today. As companies go global, their shareholders are demanding more-responsible business practices.\par \par \uc2 Jen Boulden, 30 years old, is a big believer that businesses can be powerful agents of change in the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . After working in technology marketing for eight years, she decided to get her M.B.A. at George Washington University in Washington, D.C., in part because the school's curriculum would allow her to combine her passion for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  with her business skills. "I wouldn't have gone back to school if I didn't find an environmentally oriented program within an M.B.A. structure," Ms. Boulden said.\par \par \uc2 Once relegated to the fringes of the curriculum, the topics of ethics and social and environmental management are now being integrated into core business-school classes. At Stanford University, for example, classes on social and environmental issues are woven into 12 of the 14 courses that business-school students are required to take. At some schools, students can choose a concentration in environmental management or sustainability, the idea that a business can meet its financial goals without hurting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Outside the classroom, schools are holding more seminars and conferences on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while schools themselves are setting up research centers dedicated to such topics.\par \par \uc2 That is according to "Beyond Grey Pinstripes 2003," a biennial study released earlier this month by the Aspen Institute's Business &Society Program and the World Resources Institute's Sustainable Enterprise Program. This year, about 45% of the schools that participated in the survey require students to take one or more courses on such subjects as ethics and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . That's up from 34% in 2001, the last time the survey was conducted. The survey's highest-rated schools -- George Washington, University of Michigan, University of North Carolina, Stanford, Yale University and York University in Toronto -- offer four times as many courses on social and environmental subjects as the other schools polled.\par \par \uc2 "The idea of just focusing on shareholder value isn't enough for companies," said Meghan Chapple, manager of business education at WRI. Now, companies have to work with a broader variety of shareholders, such as the community and employees, she said.\par \par \uc2 Fifty years ago, a business would have to deal only with its local competitors, said Todd Thomson, chief financial officer at Citigroup Inc., at the "Beyond Grey Pinstripes" awards ceremony in New York earlier this month. Today, "the toughest competition is likely to be from another country, not another state," he said.\par \par \uc2 Student interest also is rising. At UNC's Kenan-Flagler Business School, about 20% of students attend the program because of its concentration in sustainable enterprise. At Michigan Business School, when Timothy Fort, a professor of business ethics, first started teaching there 10 years ago, his biggest hurdle was trying to convince students that business ethics was an important issue. Today, with the number of students in his class having more than quadrupled to over 400, his biggest challenge is trying to convince them they won't be able to solve all the world's problems immediately.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, participation in Net Impact, a network of M.B.A. graduates with an interest in social and environmental business issues, has grown to 8,000 members from 1,350 in 1998, while the number of chapters has jumped to 85 from 45 over the same period. "It's not just the tree huggers anymore, it's more mainstream," said Benjamin Klasky, the network's executive director.\par \par \uc2 In fact, one of the biggest concerns Sue McGeachie, 34, faced when she was a student at York's Schulich School of Business was that sustainability wouldn't be mainstream enough. But after talking to people in the financial business, she felt reassured that her area of interest was here to stay.\par \par \uc2 "I was already changing careers," said Ms. McGeachie, who is a senior analyst at Innovest Strategic Value Advisors, an investment-research firm that analyzes companies' performance on environmental, social and strategic-governance issues. "I didn't want to jump into something that was going to dwindle."\par \par \uc2 Though students with an interest in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  are likely to find jobs in the nonprofit sector or at companies where such values are part of the corporate culture, experts say the biggest opportunity might lie with multinational companies. "If you can make huge multinationals move a little bit in the right direction, it can have a huge impact on environmental and social issues," said Mr. Klasky at Net Impact.\par \par \uc2 Marc Lavine, a 34-year-old student at Michigan Business School, agrees. The "interesting" opportunity lies with students who are able to apply their exposure to business ethics and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  in more traditional functions, said Mr. Lavine, who spent a summer internship at Chiquita Brands International Inc. gathering research on the social and environmental performance of one of the company's divisions.\par \par \uc2 Though more employers are expressing an interest in candidates with environmental and social sustainability backgrounds, students still have to be grounded in the basics, said Mindy Storrie, director of M.B.A. career services at UNC, adding that the number of students who took jobs at companies with a sustainability component has climbed in recent years. \par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=wjco20031022000158"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx7