m\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Understanding Corporate Governance(Part2) - Workforce Governance - Techniques that keep staff toeing the line. The best boards make sure that company policies on corporate governance are communicated to and understood by all employees.\par \par \uc2 Since 2001, the debate about corporate governance has spun off in many directions. It has taken in executive remuneration, financial reporting standards, the effectiveness of non-executive directors, auditor independence, investor trust, the split between the roles of chairman and chief executive, and wider conflicts of interest. The unifying theme of all such issues is that they primarily concern company boards. The subtext is clear: corporate governance is the preserve of very senior businesspeople.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Yet it has perhaps been overlooked that corporate governance also has far wider resonance. The Turnbull Report of 1999, for example, aimed at spreading best practice in UK governance, made clear that while responsibility for internal control ultimately rests with a board, managing risk involves employees too. "All employees have some responsibility for internal control as part of their accountability for achieving objectives," the report states. "The system of internal control should be embedded in the operations of the company and form part of its culture."\par \par \uc2 Bill Waite, chief executive of The Risk Advisory Group, an investigations and intelligence consultancy (Nigel Turnbull is the company's chairman), says that like so many other things in business, governance involves the quality and competence of a workforce. "The biggest risk in any company comes from staff. Even where the threat is external, you usually find an employee has been befriended and then exploited."\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, staff can also be antennae for malfeasance. When investigating the Tyco International fraud, the Manhattan District Attorney remarked that he found it "extremely troublesome ... that no whistleblowers had come forward." The majority of FTSE 500 companies now have whistleblowing procedures in place.\par \par \uc2 Traditionally, of course, human resource practices have been seen as somewhat beneath the interest of boards. Yet if the systems and procedures operating within an organisation to mitigate risk are governance issues, theoretically that ought to change. So how far should companies go towards embedding ethical behaviour?\par \par \uc2 Andrew Wilson, director of the Ashridge Centre for Business and Society, says the answer depends on both the internal culture of individual companies and the national business cultures in which those companies operate. US companies, he says, tend to take a very compliance-driven attitude to governance, setting down on paper exactly what is expected of employees. "Gift policies sometimes say a case of wine is inappropriate, while a bottle of wine is fine - it is that detailed," he explains.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, European companies prefer broad principles that allow greater scope for individual discretion. Ideally, says Mr Wilson, governance should allow for "disciplined empowerment".\par \par \uc2 "A rule-based, bureaucratic approach encourages people to think about what they can get away with, when what you want are sensible judgments in line with business values. Perhaps the classic question to ask is 'How would I feel if this (action) was reported in the press?'"\par \par \uc2 At Johnson &Johnson, the healthcare and hygiene products company, a decentralised global structure has led it to adopt a similarly decentralised approach to governance. Its values statement, which has been given the quasi-religious name of "the credo", describes its duties to consumers, employees and communities (shareholders come last). But different business units are required to interpret it in line with different national and sectoral expectations.\par \par \uc2 Textbook models of corporate governance sometimes envisage an idealised flow of principle into policy, policy into process, and process into practice. In reality, communicating a culture of governance is very difficult. In this, the corporate governance agenda overlaps substantially with that of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 For contemporary CSR, says Leo Martin, director of GoodCorporation, a business ethics consultancy, "the holy grail is how you get things off a bit of paper and into the day-to-day behaviour of individuals."\par \par \uc2 One approach is to treat governance like health and safety. From an initial risk assessment, procedures are devised to mitigate the risk and, thereafter, no opportunity is lost to reinforce messages in the minds of employees: through manuals, training seminars, wall plaques and so on.\par \par \uc2 Yet governance and corporate responsibility may involve too many fine judgments for this sort of treatment. Take anti-bribery policies, for instance. The starting point for many organisations is that anything which places employees under an obligation is unacceptable. But that leaves significant scope for discretion. When does corporate hospitality turn into an unspoken expectation? In response, some companies go further, noting the monetary value of all gifts and accepting or rejecting them on that basis.\par \par \uc2 David Watts, a partner in accountant KPMG's business assurance services group, says it is important for governance to be seen as a question of business effectiveness rather than compliance. Nonetheless, boards still need to know that the objectives they set are being met. Therefore, they need to take an interest in the mechanisms that enforce accountability: targets, key performance indicators, lines of reporting and internal audits.\par \par \uc2 This interest may even go as far as recruitment, he says: "Boards should be concerned with whether organisations are recruiting and retaining the best people and filtering down expectations. But that is not to say they need to know the results of appraisals."\par \par \uc2 One example of the way governance can be integrated into HR practice involves Storebrand, the Norwegian financial services group. The company has set a high priority on corporate responsibility. In addition to the usual requirements of the graduate recruitment process, it asks applicants to demonstrate "social intelligence" - loosely translated as an ability to analyse the roles of business in a social context.\par \par \uc2 Elsewhere, reward policies are a favourite mechanism for entrenching attitudes and behaviour. All BP managers, for instance, are set objectives in the form of a "performance contract". As one might expect, this mainly concerns financial measures. Yet the contract also features the company's five main policy areas - ethical conduct, employees, relationships, health and safety, and control and finance. Up to 30 per cent of the contract can involve non-financial measures. Since remuneration is dependent on assessment against the criteria included in the performance contract, the policies tend to have more impact.\par \par \uc2 According to Brian Gregory, European marketing director of Oracle, the software company, corporate governance may serve to break down "the fortress HR mentality", as boards take a greater interest in an area normally seen as off-limits. "There has been a huge amount of attention on accountancy, but so much less on the people aspects of risk," he says.\par \par \uc2 The renewed focus on corporate governance has given a spur for HR information technology systems to be developed that are able to interact with accountancy and other business systems, he says. Information about the skills, competencies, background, aspirations and expenses claims of individual employees is now no more than a few mouse clicks away from security-conscious board members. Modern HR software enables "additional checks and balances" on employee risk. "At the end of the day," concludes Mr Gregory, "governance is about making sure there are no surprises."\par \par \uc2 WHISTLEBLOWING: HOW THE UK AND US DIFFER\par \par \uc2 No company likes hearing bad news. But the law has now moved to make whistleblowing much easier in both the UK and US. However, there are different approaches on either side of the Atlantic.\par \par \uc2 In the US, the 2002 Sarbanes-Oxley Act introduced extended protections for whistleblowers - but only in connection with securities law. In addition, the act only covers workers involved in official investigations. In other areas of a company's activity, such as the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , or health and safety, whistleblowers are offered more limited redress, varied by federal statutes.\par \par \uc2 In the UK, however, the 1998 Public Interest Disclosure Act extends far more widely. In any legal obligation to which an employer is subject, whistleblowers are protected if they raise concerns. Following recent judgments, PIDA is also widely believed to cover an employee's contractual obligations.\par \par \uc2 According to Public Concern at Work, a UK-based independent authority on whistleblowing, the two most frequent concerns they deal with are health risks and financial misconduct.\par \par \uc2 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ccpgvn : \uc2 Corporate Governance/Investor Relations | c41 : \uc2 Management Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \q