attacks on the World Trade Center in September 2001. Fortunately, all the staff survived, but Mancini Duffy's offices, housed in Tower Two, were demolished.\par \par \uc2 However, in the following days clients, friends and even competitors came forward to help on the strength of the firm's good name, says Mr Mancini. They donated office space, furniture, computers and technical assistance. Two years on, the firm has reclaimed its place as one of the US's leading design and architectural practices. "If we hadn't had a good reputation, we couldn't have come back from that," he says.\par \par \uc2 While Mancini Duffy's case is an extreme test of corporate goodwill, it does shed light on the value of reputation and how it can help build success in good times and help companies to survive in bad times.\par \par \uc2 Corporate scandals such as those of Enron and WorldCom have raised the profile of reputation for companies. But, while few doubt its importance it remains extremely difficult to define, assess and measure - unless it is damaged or lost. What exactly constitutes reputation? Who controls it and how can it be measured?\par \par \uc2 Approaches range from the purely intuitive - whether the company "feels" trustworthy - to surveys of stakeholder groups and sophisticated instruments that measure every aspect of reputation, including financial performance, vision and leadership and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 John Low, author of The Invisible Advantage, says one way to measure reputation is by classifying it as an "intangible" asset, like goodwill. Mr Low believes this is appropriate in the modern economy, where intangibles such as innovation, talent and relationships, which lie outside traditional business metrics, are crucial.\par \par \uc2 Steven Wartick, professor of management and policy at the University of Northern Iowa, suggests that most attempts to measure reputation are misguided because they do not start with a clear definition. Reputation is often muddled with vague concepts of identity, image, prestige, goodwill, esteem and standing.\par \par \uc2 Charles Fombrun, professor emeritus of the Stern School of Business, New\par \par \uc2 York University, defines reputation as "a perceptual representation of a company's past actions and future prospects that describes the firm's overall appeal to all of its key constituents when compared with other leading rivals".\par \par \uc2 While this definition may sound academic, it holds all the elements of a reputation: perception, past record, future expectations, appeal to constituents and comparison with rivals.\par \par \uc2 Prof Wartick defines reputation as "the aggregation of a single stakeholder's perceptions of how well organisational responses are meeting the demands and expectations of many organisational stakeholders".\par \par \uc2 As for measurement, the best-known, most popular methods are surveys or interviews. These can be as informal as canvassing individuals or interest groups about an organisation, or a more structured survey, such as Fortune's Most Admired Corporations, which asks respondents (generally senior executives, directors and financial analysts) to grade companies on specific criteria and offers a ranking for companies.\par \par \uc2 While the MAC survey has yielded valuable data on reputation, it has drawn criticism for not taking account of subtler measures of reputation, such as "trust", and for having a purely business-focused set of respondents.\par \par \uc2 A more sophisticated measure of reputation was developed for Fortune by Leslie Gaines-Ross, now chief knowledge and research officer at Burson Marsteller, the global communications consultancy, and Yankelovich Partners, a US research firm. Called "leveraging corporate equity", the study, which has been published regularly since 1993, relies less on financial performance than the MAC and includes factors such as trust, doing business in a caring way, innovation and exemplary behaviour. However, as in the MAC survey, respondents consist of business people rather than the public.\par \par \uc2 More recently, Ms Gaines-Ross has been conducting studies on "CEO Capital" that have shown that in the US, UK and Australia, the personal reputation of a CEO can account for up to half of corporate reputation (and 64 per cent in Germany). Her surveys of 1,200 "business influentials" (CEOs, executives, financial analysts, institutional investors, business media and government officials) over the past five years have shown that five factors contribute to CEOs' reputation: credibility; code of ethics; internal communication; good management; and motivating and inspiring employees. "(These) factors are more important in shaping perceptions of CEOs than even shareholder gains," she says. "Evidently, financial importance is important, but simply not enough."\par \par \uc2 While surveys offer a good general measure of reputation that is pragmatic and easily understood and integrates ideas of image, identity and reputation, they can be limited in terms of detail.\par \par \uc2 A more complex measure of reputation is the Reputation Quotient (RQ), developed by Prof Fombrun and Harris Interactive, the US market research company. The RQ is calculated on the basis of 20 attributes in six main categories and measures perceptions of companies across a range of industries and a wider stakeholder group (members of the public who may or not be customers, plus employees of identified companies).\par \par \uc2 The instrument might be sophisticated, but Prof Fombrun says the analysis of corporate reputation can be distilled into five simple principles: distinctiveness (among stakeholders for a product/service); focus (a single core theme); consistency (in actions and communications); identity (based on espoused principles rather than advertising or "spin"); and transparency (disclosing more information and engaging in dialogue with stakeholders).\par \par \uc2 "People form impressions of companies based on what they read, what they hear and what they see, based on their direct experiences of a company, such as consumer interactions, and indirect experiences, such as media reports," says Prof Fombrun. "These experiences create a 'halo' around a company that constitutes its reputation."\par \par \uc2 Clearly, Mancini Duffy's "halo" was visible in the aftermath of September 11. But Mr Mancini believes the concept can be simplified even further: "Reputation is measured only one way: is the company or person trustworthy? If you are trust-worthy you have respect. And you don't measure that yourself."\par \par \uc2 ADMIRED COMPANIES AND THE PERCEPTIONS OF DECISION MAKERS\par \par \uc2 * Fortune Most Admired Corporations Published annually since 1983. Includes assessments of 300 or more companies across 60 or so industries. Industry rankings and top 10 list across industries. Criticised for having no non-business respondents, focusing purely on senior executives, non-executive directors and financial analysts.\par \par \uc2 * Leveraging Corporate Equity Developed in 1994 by Leslie Gaines-Ross and Yankelovich Partners to complement the Fortune MAC, it looks at factors such as "trust" and "supportive behaviours", but focuses on "decision-makers" (DM). Awards a corporate equity score based on five components of corporate reputation: awareness (how aware are DMs of the company?); familiarity (how familiar are DMs with the company?); overall impression (how favourable are DMs towards the company?); perceptions (how is the company perceived?); supportive behaviours (to what lengths will a constituency go in support of the organisation?).\par \par \uc2 * Reputation Quotient Developed by Charles Fombrun of NYU, the RQ instrument can be used by companies to survey 20 attributes of reputation. The Reputation Institute uses it to conduct customised surveys and annual RQ survey (with Harris Interactive), a poll of the general public only. The survey is designed to capture the concept of the "halo" around a company's performance, which means exploring impressions rather than facts. RQ is based on six categories: emotional appeal (how much a company is liked and respected); products and services (perceptions of quality, innovation, value and reliability); financial performance (competitiveness, profitability, growth prospects and risk); vision and leadership (does the company demonstrate clear vision, strong leadership and an ability to recognise and capitalise on market opportunities?); workplace \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  (is the company well managed? what is it like to work there? what is the quality of its employees?); social responsibility (does the company have high standards in its dealings with people, good causes and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ?).\par \par \uc2 London Edition 1. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 manduf : \uc2 Mancini Duffy Associates Inc\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Ind