faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2003 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Cost cuts and false economies - Better business behaviour might mean higher spending but can bring a variety of benefits, writes Michael Skapinker.\par \par \uc2 Whenever you visit a supplier, ask to use their toilets. That was the advice Marcus Sieff, chairman of Marks and Spencer, the retail chain, and grandson of its founder, gave in his memoirs 17 years ago. "You can tell a great deal about the general standards of a firm by looking at those maintained in their washrooms and lavatories," he wrote in his book Don't Ask the Price.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The British retailer was a pioneer of decent working conditions for its staff. When it insisted its suppliers treated their staff well too, their performance always improved, Lord Sieff wrote.\par \par \uc2 He recounted a visit to a store that was being rebuilt. The M&S executives found the contractors' building workers eating lunch with only a tarpaulin to shelter them from the pouring rain. Their toilet was a chemical closet.\par \par \uc2 When you work for us, M&S told the contractors, build a temporary canteen, providing hot food, and decent facilities. The company, Bovis, complied. Its productivity increased, labour turnover dropped and costs fell.\par \par \uc2 That was in 1958. Yet companies worldwide are still struggling with the issue of how much responsibility they should take for their suppliers' behaviour.\par \par \uc2 Increased competition has sharpened the dilemma. With companies battling for customers, and offering ever-lower prices, many have closed their own factories and contracted out their manufacturing to factories thousands of miles away - where wages are low and working conditions often primitive.\par \par \uc2 Companies, such as Nike, paid the price. In Pakistan, campaigners discovered that village children were hand-stitching Nike footballs. In Cambodia, the company's contractors were accused of using child labour. Nike's reputation took a battering. So did the good name of Gap, the clothing company. Both companies have taken extensive steps to ensure that its contractors treat their staff decently and do not employ child labour.\par \par \uc2 Ensuring that contractors do not use under-age labour is not easy, particularly in countries where the registration of births is haphazard or where, as in Cambodia, records have been destroyed under the Khmer Rouge.\par \par \uc2 Nor does the pressure ever ease. John Sabapathy, senior research manager at AccountAbility, an institute that attempts to set standards for sustainable development, says that knowing what is happening in contractors' factories is no longer enough. Companies need to ensure that their insistence on proper working conditions is not undermined by other company policies.\par \par \uc2 For example, one part of the company could be attempting to ensure contractors' employees are not exploited, while the buying department is pressing for lower prices. This forces contractors' margins down, which makes it more difficult for them to raise wages or give staff time off.\par \par \uc2 Companies' inability to forecast demand for their products can also have a detrimental effect on working conditions in contractors' factories, Mr Sabapathy adds. If companies suddenly demand more products in a hurry, contractors might push employees into excessive overtime work.\par \par \uc2 But isn't price a principal driver of competition? As companies attempt to cut prices, and costs, is it not inevitable that suppliers will feel they have no choice but to pay their people less and work them harder?\par \par \uc2 Mr Sabapathy says companies have found that the way to deal with this is to work in concert and to sign up jointly to initiatives that promote better working conditions, such as the Ethical Trading Initiative.\par \par \uc2 The initiative is a tripartite alliance of companies, campaigning organisations and trade unions, committed to a code of employment practice. Among the provisions of the code are that working conditions are safe and hygienic, that there is no use of child labour, that living wages are paid and that working hours are not excessive.\par \par \uc2 But the initiative's sponsors state clearly that it is not an accreditation agency, nor does it perform external audits. "It primarily exists to share experience and promote learning about implementing international labour standards in international supply chains," it says.\par \par \uc2 The problems of promoting ethical supply chains, however, go well beyond the auditing of working conditions, or even ensuring that all parts of the company are pulling in the same direction. While most people would agree, for example, that employing children is wrong and that they should be at school instead, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is never that simple.\par \par \uc2 In his book, Empires of Profit: Commerce, Conquest and Corporate Responsibility, Daniel Litvin, a former policy adviser to Rio Tinto, the mining company, told the following story: Delwar Hos sein, a 12-year-old Bangladeshi clothing factory worker, lost his job after western campaigners objected to the employment of child labour. The campaigners threatened a boycott of clothes from Bangladesh over the child labour issue.\par \par \uc2 Did Delwar go to school instead? No. Deprived of his factory job, he sold waste paper he picked up in the streets. This work did not provide him with the $20 a month he earned at the factory. His family could no longer pay the rent and began skipping meals.\par \par \uc2 Here is another problem for companies facing pressure to ensure their supply chains are squeaky clean: consumers tell researchers that they worry about the conditions under which their clothes are made, but their purchasing patterns tell a different story.\par \par \uc2 Nike's reputation may have suffered during its child labour crises, but its sales did not. And while consumers can buy "fair trade" food, coffee and tea - produced on farms and plantations where the workers get decent wages - most do not bother.\par \par \uc2 A study last year - by the UK's Institute of Grocery Distribution - found that consumers were staying away from fair trade products. "Self-interest is at the centre of food choice for most consumers," the study said. "Few consumers consider the impact of their purchase decisions on anyone or anything but themselves or their family."\par \par \uc2 The UK's Co-operative Bank, in another study, said that while sales of fair trade products were growing, they still accounted for a tiny proportion of the market. The bank called it the "30:3 syndrome": 30 per cent of consumers claimed to be ethical shoppers, but most fair trade products, or those that protect the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  or animals, had a market share of less than 3 per cent.\par \par \uc2 Kate Fish, formerly vice-president for public policy at Monsanto, the company at the forefront of the controversial development of genetically modified food, says there is another danger for companies that set up and publicise their ethical supply chains: they are more likely to become targets of campaigners who will attempt to hold them to their promises.\par \par \uc2 So while the moral case might be clear, is the business case? Why should companies bother with ethical supply chains?\par \par \uc2 Supporters of better business behaviour offer three reasons. First, because, as Lord Sieff wrote, happier workers do better work. It may cost more to employ them, but it will not always cost as much as companies think. Insisting that building contractors provide decent facilities added only 1 per cent to M&S's construction costs.\par \par \uc2 Second, while consumers might not act on their stated moral qualms, employees often do. Nike found that while its sales did not suffer after it was targeted by anti-sweatshop campaigners, employee morale did. People want to be proud of their employers.\par \par \uc2 Third, as Ms Fish, now an independent consultant, points out, companies never know when bad publicity is going to cost them sales. Monsanto suffered badly when it under-estimated the extent of consumer opposition to genetically modified food. Ethical business practice is just another form of risk management, she says.\par \par \uc2 2. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpa