\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It is the season of goodwill and evenlawyers, not a grouprenowned for showing their caring side, are getting in on the act.\par \par \uc2 This Christmas, as every year, a small band of solicitors will turn up to advice centres and drop-in shelters to offer free legal advice to the poor or homeless. But legal advice offered pro bono publico - lawyerly Latin parlance meaning "for the public good" - is increasingly featuring high on the agenda of hard-nosed City law firms all the year round.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 As corporate law firms become ever larger, turning themselves into global businesses with billion-pound turnovers, they know that the demands of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  require such profitable enterprises to put more back into the community. And, ever the pragmatists, they are waking up to the fact that there is a strong business case for pushing pro bono work.\par \par \uc2 No firm wants to be perceived as weak on community commitment. Clifford Chance, the world's biggest law firm, demonstrated that in the US when it was forced to confront a crisis in morale among its New York staff. Pro bono work has long held a higher profile in the US than in Britain, and one of the lawyers' main complaints was that they were offered limited opportunities to do pro bono work.\par \par \uc2 The firm responded with a push to encourage associates to do more free work and make a "contribution to the community", one of the core criteria used in assessing lawyers and awarding bonuses.\par \par \uc2 In Britain, the firm has a well developed and expanding community programme. So do its rivals. There are good reasons for that, says Michael Smyth, Clifford Chance's pro bono partner. "We are doing more and others are doing more too. I wouldn't pretend we were unique in this. It is something that distinguishes a liberal profession, that perhaps sets lawyers apart from other businesses. I think it is a regard for the public interest, a consideration for something other than the next billable hour."\par \par \uc2 Mr Smyth is quick to acknowledge, though, that pro bono work brings definable benefits for law firms. He says clients are increasingly concerned about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and are demanding the same considerations of their advisers. So a well planned pro bono programme can shape perceptions of the firm and offer "a good client fit".\par \par \uc2 It is also important for morale. It is a fact that many junior and trainee lawyers are keen to work outside their normal corporate sphere. For example, Clifford Chance's London office spent more than 25,000 hours pro bono in the past financial year, involving just over a third of its lawyers in the capital.\par \par \uc2 Among other things, the firm runs evening drop-in legal advice clinics at law centres in Hackney and Tooting, with more than 100 lawyers volunteering regularly.\par \par \uc2 In addition, more than 60 lawyers put in 6,500 hours in all last year helping families obtain local education funding to meet the needs of autistic children in partnership with the National Autistic Society. The firm also works with Victim Support, representing clients at Criminal Injuries Compensation Board appeals, and offers 12 trainee solicitors each year the opportunity to spend three months at not-for-profit west London community solicitors Law For All as part of their formal training. Four more trainees are seconded each year to Liberty, the civil liberties campaign group.\par \par \uc2 But some are unconvinced by the value of all this good work. They worry that firms' junior or trainee solicitors, who have little experience or training in social welfare law, are being allowed to make their mistakes on pro bono work safely away from commercial clients.\par \par \uc2 Geoffrey Bindman, senior partner at Bindman &Partners, specialists in civil liberties and human rights law, says: "I think the rich City law firms should be giving money to support legal aid and law centres if they want to ensure the professional skills that are appropriate are made available, rather than letting their youngsters loose on an unsuspecting public."\par \par \uc2 At a time when legal aid is being squeezed and solicitors are leaving publicly funded work in droves, he is worried that pro bono work will be seen as an acceptable way of plugging the gap. Mr Bindman also says big firms often run into conflicts of interest when their charity clients want to take action against, for example, large property groups or financial institutions.\par \par \uc2 He adds: "You can understand why they do it. It's to retain their young people who are doing their boring and not very socially useful work and want to feel that they are able to make some contribution to society."\par \par \uc2 However, Graham Bucknall, project manager at the Solicitors Pro Bono Group, believes law firms can offer crucial help to people who do not have legal aid and could not otherwise afford a lawyer. He thinks the influx of big US law firms into London over the past few years has helped to spur interest in pro bono work there.\par \par \uc2 Mr Bucknall admits that pro bono activity is "certainly not as big here as in the US" but he adds: "The big increase in US firms operating in the UK has added to the competitive incentives because they are bringing the American pro bono culture with them."\par \par \uc2 The SPBG is a charity with about 60 law firms as members, including most of the big City firms, set up to encourage lawyers to provide more free legal help to needy individuals and community groups. Under its "LawWorks" banner, it co-ordinates free legal advice to charity groups, runs clinics that solicitors attend on a rota to help with individuals' problems and offers social welfare law training for solicitors specialising in other areas. It encourages students to get involved and runs a web-based advice service that operates through Citizens' Advice Bureaux and other advice agencies.\par \par \uc2 It claims to have helped 300 charities since September 2001 and says interest in pro bono work is growing.\par \par \uc2 Mr Bucknall says the drive for such work often comes from law students. Increasingly, a well developed pro bono programme is being seen as a tool for attracting the brightest graduates. "Firms will often get better law students because they have a good pro bono programme," he says.\par \par \uc2 It can also help to retain staff and reduce "burn-out", he believes, by offering a completely different working \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  that, while still challenging, comes as a relief from the hothouse atmosphere of high-pressure corporate deals.\par \par \uc2 "If part of the motivation is self-interest, at least it is of the enlightened sort," Mr Smyth agrees. "It is a reminder for many of why they went into the law." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i835 : \