rved  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Even globalization's biggest advocates admit that while the phenomenon is unstoppable, it would be nice to control it a bit more.  \par \par \uc2 In particular, many wish there was some way to ensure that manufactured goods flooding in from low-wage countries are not the product of child labor, inhumane working conditions or environmental depredation. But without global manufacturing regulations or extremely restrictive trade policies, that goal remains elusive.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A strategy that is gaining traction would use the power of publicity and financial "transparency" to make foreign manufacturers do the right thing, while still keeping fair and responsible behavior entirely voluntary. In doing this, the federal government may have a key role, according to a recently convened group of business, academic and advocacy leaders.  \par \par \uc2 "What we tried to figure out was how the U.S. government could better use its good offices to increase best practices and promote uniform standards, and to encourage companies in each industry to follow suit," said Barbara Fiorito, chairman of Oxfam America, the U.S. chapter of the worldwide relief agency.  \par \par \uc2 "We should never lose sight of the role that government can play and should play to address critical globalization issues," said Bruce Moats, vice president for worldwide government affairs and public policy for Levi Strauss & Co., the bluejeans maker. "We argued that there is a void in the United States government in addressing issues of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."  \par \par \uc2 Fiorito and Moats chaired a study group late last year that came up with 18 recommendations of things the federal government could do to help ensure better treatment of workers producing raw materials and finished goods for U.S.-based multinational companies. Assembled by the Frank Hawkins Kenan Institute of Private Enterprise, part of the University of North Carolina's business school, the panel included executives from Starbucks, Toys R Us, the AFL-CIO, the Fair Labor Association, the Sierra Club and numerous academic and nongovernmental organizations.  \par \par \uc2 Among the aims of the recommendations are to require U.S. companies to describe overseas practices that may make them liable for damages; to promote "socially responsible" purchasing by federal agencies; and to review and catalogue how federal policies and programs affect corporate behavior overseas.  \par \par \uc2 "The government has to recognize that it needs to send clear signals to its market actors," said Susan Aaronson, an economic historian and senior fellow at the Kenan Institute, who set up the study group.  \par \par \uc2 As an example of a confusing signal, Aaronson said the government forbids use of certain pesticides in the United States because they are hazardous to workers or the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but permits importation of fruit and vegetables grown overseas with the assistance of those same chemicals.  \par \par \uc2 The panel said the Securities and Exchange Commission should consider requiring that publicly traded companies include in their annual reports accounts of social and environmental practices overseas that may have implications for their bottom lines.  \par \par \uc2 France requires that companies report on social and environmental, as well as financial, performance, and Britain requires pension funds to describe these aspects of their investments. In some cases, shareholders are demanding the information on their own. Early last month, the investment company Boston Common Asset Management asked Newmont Mining Corp., the world's largest gold-mining operation, to prepare a report on the potential risks to its profits from controversial mining practices in South America.  \par \par \uc2 Some companies already make such calculations, using methods suggested by an independent entity called the Global Reporting Initiative ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.globalreporting.org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.globalreporting.org}}}\uc2 ).  \par \par \uc2 The idea, Aaronson said, is that disclosure will allow market forces to help drive companies to act responsibly. Now, many companies are willing to take the competitive advantage that may come with practices that are inhumane or pollute the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  because few Americans know about the practices and the companies may not be held liable for them.  \par \par \uc2 "If we require that companies report -- if everybody has to reveal it -- more companies will decide to take on the best practices," Aaronson said.  \par \par \uc2 Levi Strauss, which closed its last American plant last week, has relatively elaborate standards on worker treatment that its foreign contractors must meet before they are allowed to make the company's clothes.  \par \par \uc2 "My competitors spend a lot more than I do on damage control," Moats said. "While I can't point to specific savings by having this program, I can say I don't spend a lot of money on reversing bad behavior."  \par \par \uc2 The Kenan panel said the federal government should also push for incentives for good behavior in trade agreements. Aaronson pointed to the Clean Diamond Trade Act, passed in April, which allows the United States to ban importation of diamonds that have not passed the international Kimberley Process Certification Scheme. That process certifies that production of gems has not promoted armed conflict or the abuse of human rights, as is the case with many "blood diamonds" mined and traded in West Africa.  \par \par \uc2 The panel also said the federal government can support humane and just labor practices through its own purchases. Federal agencies today must buy energy-efficient appliances. They might also be required, for example, to buy only "fair-traded" coffee -- a designation that describes coffee whose growers are guaranteed to have gotten a minimum wage for their labor.  \par \par \uc2 Aaronson and some members of the Kenan panel recently briefed a group of lawmakers and Capitol Hill staffers on the recommendations. Over the next few months, they will present them to people at several Cabinet-level departments and executive agencies.  \par \par \uc2 A Bush administration initiative specifically mentioned by the panel as a vehicle for promoting \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the Millennium Challenge Account (MCA). Through that program, some countries could receive development aid from the United States if they show their governments operate fairly and transparently.  \par \par \uc2 When the same rules apply to everyone, it is much easier for companies to do the right thing, said E. Anthony Wayne, assistant secretary of state for economic and business affairs.  \par \par \uc2 Legislation creating MCA is now part of the omnibus appropriations bill pending before Congress.  \par \par \uc2 "I think that our best companies recognize that they are in business for the long term, and that means being good corporate citizens in their communities, wherever those communities are," Wayne said. "We want to work with them in support of that approach."  \par \par \uc2 A full description of the 18 recommendations is available online at:  {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.kenan-flagler.unc.edu/KI/kiWashington/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 http://www.kenan-flagler.unc.edu/KI/kiWashington/}}}\uc2 .   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CT\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 http://www.washingtonpost.com\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\a