t-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2004 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This year's World's Most Respected Companies survey was conducted against a background of continuing economic uncertainty and geo-political volatility that made 2003 a challenging period for business.\par \par \uc2 At the same time, companies were coming to terms with a low-growth, low-inflation \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  that now appears set to become a fact of life for some time to come - in Europe, at least.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Companies also faced new conditions in their drive to build corporate reputation and public trust.\par \par \uc2 The US corporate scandals of 2001 meant that in 2002, it was mainly US businesses that were perceived as facing an uphill battle to create reputational capital. A year ago the results underlined that viewpoint, with US corporations' presence in the top 50 World's Most Respected falling to its lowest since this research began.\par \par \uc2 However, this year's results serve to reaffirm the fact that corporate reputation is not just a task for US companies, but for corporations worldwide. By claiming 13 of the top 20 places in CEOs' global rankings of companies they respect, and increasing their share of the top 50 for the first time in three years, US corporations have hit back.\par \par \uc2 Businesses from elsewhere in the world may detect a touch of irony in the fact that US boardrooms' greater focus on governance and reputation post-Enron may have provided a platform for this revival in their collective reputation.\par \par \uc2 That said, while there have - as ever - been shifts in many companies' rankings within the top 50, once again the views of our 1,000 CEO respondents worldwide exhibit one characteristic above all: consistency.\par \par \uc2 The top two positions in the global World's Most Respected table, and several other places in the top 10, have been claimed by the same companies every year since 1998.\par \par \uc2 Further down the rankings, companies' precise position may fluctuate year on year, but the fact remains that many of the same names are always present.\par \par \uc2 This consistency may reflect a number of truths. One is the long-term nature of the effort to build and sustain reputation.\par \par \uc2 Unless there is a cataclysmic event, reputations simply do not change overnight. The other is the long-term sustainability and resilience of these businesses - and of their reputations - even during the difficult and frequently tumultuous business conditions of the past few years.\par \par \uc2 This resilience is all the more striking if you look behind the findings and examine the changing basis on which CEOs and other respondents are making their decisions.\par \par \uc2 When our CEOs are asked what factors drive their choice, a comparison of the past four surveys shows that factors such as ethical responsibility, customer focus and global reach are on a clear upward track - therefore becoming steadily more influential in their decisions.\par \par \uc2 In contrast, the importance of business strategy is still at the same level as in 2000, while the weighting accorded to "vision" has slumped during the same period.\par \par \uc2 Such changes confirm a continuing re-evaluation of why any particular company is respected or trusted. Yet despite this moving target, the same companies are able to claim high places in the rankings year on year. To an extent, they are changing and evolving as businesses. But far more important is their consistent ability to present a transparent, accurate and coherent picture of their real drivers of value to all their various groups of stakeholders.\par \par \uc2 This in turn enables stakeholders to build a realistic view of what makes these businesses tick, and why they are worthy of respect.\par \par \uc2 The ability of some businesses to present this "all-round view" becomes all the clearer when the findings gleaned from our CEO respondents are compared with those from other stakeholder groups. The World's Most Respected Companies Survey extends beyond CEOs to canvass the views of fund managers, non-governmental organisations (NGOs) and the media. The more consistent a company's ranking across these different constituencies, the more complete and congruent its dialogue with stakeholders.\par \par \uc2 With this in mind, it is significant that fund managers' top four choices as companies that create value for shareholders - General Electric, Berkshire Hathaway, IBM and Microsoft - are all ranked in CEOs' top six companies for the same category. This suggests that these companies are impressing their peers in other boardrooms as well as the investment community.\par \par \uc2 However, perhaps more surprising are the similarities between the views of stakeholder groups with contrasting agendas. When NGOs are asked to nominate companies worldwide for exhibiting good \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the top two are Microsoft and IBM - both of which are also high up in CEOs' rankings on CSR. Interestingly, NGOs rank Coca-Cola and McDonald's more highly for CSR than do CEOs.\par \par \uc2 Such findings appear to show two things. One is that real transparency can build trust simultaneously in very different stakeholder constituencies with different - and, some might even have thought, irreconcilable - interests and expectations. The second is that the leaders in reputation worldwide are increasingly following an approach based on responsiveness and engagement, on issues where the delivery of financial shareholder value has to be balanced with wider ethical and reputational considerations.\par \par \uc2 This approach is increasingly evident in all sectors, including industries to which NGOs have traditionally been hostile, such as defence and mining. Whatever a company's area of activity, it is in its interests to build a long-term reputation among all its stakeholders by giving clear and open explanations of the basis of its business, and of the commercial decisions it takes. Some people may not like what it does - but at least that dislike will be based on fact, which is something it can control or influence, rather than hearsay, which it cannot.\par \par \uc2 From our own experience of advising leading companies, we know that the majority now recognise many of these issues, and are striving to move in the right direction. They know that sound corporate values are a prerequisite, but that building real long-term trust needs more: the right internal processes for collecting and recording information about their business's real drivers of value - and a framework for communicating the relevant elements accurately, clearly, effectively and coherently to all stakeholders.\par \par \uc2 As a professional services firm, my own organisation also has an absolute need to get all this right - and we would be the first to admit that we still have much to learn. It was pleasing to find ourselves recognised in the top 50 of this year's rankings. But as a new member of this particular club, we know there is much more for us to do before we can emulate the corporations that have established themselves in the upper reaches.\par \par \uc2 In reputation, as in other areas of business, sound ideas and a good approach are a start. But the key is execution. And the ability to keep on executing - no matter what the economic conditions or questions thrown at your business. These are qualities that consistent top performers in the World's Most Respected Companies survey exhibit to the full.\par \par \uc2 Kieran Poynter is Chairman, PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP. For more information, please visit {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.valuereporting.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.valuereporting.com}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccpgvn : \uc2 Corporate Governance/Investor Relations | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | e11 : \uc2 Economic Performance/Indicators | e1103 : \uc2 Inflation/Prices | ecat : \uc2 Economic News | c41 : \uc2 Management Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PUB\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 The Financial Times Limited (AAIW/EIW)